<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Malaysia-Refugees     04-26 0156</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Malaysia-Refugees,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 226,000 Vietnamese Refugees Have Arrived In Malaysia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From 1975 to this March, 226,091
Vietnamese boat people have landed in Malaysia, an official said
today.
   The influx of Vietnamese refugees began in 1975 after U.S.
forces withdrew from South Vietnam and it fell to communist forces
from North Vietnam.
   Of the 226,091 refugees, 217,812 resettled in other countries,
including 128,000 in the United States, said Eric E. Morris, the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees for Malaysia and
Brunei.
   In the first three months of this year, 2,921 boat people
reached Malaysian shores, higher than the 1,702 for the same period
last year, he said.
   Morris told reporters the increase was due, in part, to
Thailand's decision to forbid boats of refugees to land on its
shores.
   The boat people generally land on the east coasts of Malaysia
and Thailand by cutting across the South China Sea.
</TEXT>
