<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0028EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Contras     04-26 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contras,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras In `Liberated Zone' Say They Won't Lay Down Arms</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs.</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The writer, a photographer for The Associated
Press in Managua, accompanied the Contra rebels for two days. Here
is his account:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MAURICIO OROZCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PUNTA GORDA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commander Halcon and his band of
Nicaraguan rebels move freely around what they call their
``liberated zone'' in the jungles near the Caribbean coast.
   They are willing to talk peace but won't lay down their arms.
   ``We have received orders from our high command to stop
shooting,'' Halcon said as he sat under a tree while his men rested
nearby. ``But we are not dropping our guard. The enemy cannot be
trusted.''
   A peasant widow provided food and coffee to his company of young
rebels, including several women.
   Halcon, a former Sandinista who fought against the National
Guard of late strongman President Anastasio Somoza, and his troops
are in the jungles of Southern Zelaya province near the Caribbean
coast.
   They are part of the Southern Front of the Democratic Nicarguan
Force, or FDN, the main Contra force which has fought to overthrow
the Sandinista government.
   The area is one of seven set up under a 60-day cease-fire
agreement between the U.S.-backed Contras and the Sandinista.
   Under the agreement, the Sandinistas have promised not to attack
Contra troops congregating in the areas.
   ``They don't come here anyway,'' Halcon said. ``We liberated
this zone a long time ago.''
   Looking around at his troops, Halcon said, ``There is no one
here among us against his will.''
   ``The people know we are not mercenaries,'' he said.
   Journalists traveled with the group for a day, visiting
different camps where they met groups of rebels. Halcon said he
commands three companies of 100 men each in the rugged eastern zone.
   Sandinista army troops evacuated many of the residents from the
mountainous region two years ago in an effort to remove the rebels'
``social base'' but some people refused to leave.
   They often help the Contras and provide food. They do the same
for the Sandinista army when it moves in.
   Some cattle still roam the area and Contra groups use abandoned
farms.
   Halcon and his men appeared to be well-armed and in good
spirits. They had enough medicine and beef and plenty of U.S.-made
candy to eat. At night they danced to tapes of Mexican ``ranchera''
music, then slept in hammocks made of silky parachute cloth.
   The commander said the last air drop of U.S. supplies to the
group came a month ago.
   Under the cease-fire that took effect April 1, rebels may
receive humanitarian aid through neutral international
organizations once they are settled in the designated zones.
   Details of the truce are still being worked out in talks which
will resume Thursday.
   Halcon said he had received two letters from the regional
commander of the Sandinista army asking him to meet with the
government represntatives ``in an effort to achieve peace.''
   He said he was waiting for further instructions from Contra
headquarters. There have already been several meetings of army and
rebel groups on the field since the cease-fire went into effect.
   ``We will do whatever our leaders tell us,'' Halcon said. ``If
we had a complete cease-fire, it would be the most beautiful thing.
We have been fighting among Nicaraguans for too long. But we are
armed campesinos and we are willing to fight ... and we are not
going to lay down our arms unless there is a definitive
cease-fire.''
   ``We will lay down our arms when the Sandinistas lay down
theirs, when there is a democratic government in Nicaragua.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ManilaVice     04-26 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Manila Vice,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Crack Down On Manila's Red Light District</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The police chief is vowing to close
down Manila's honky-tonk district, which he claims had made it the
``Sin Capital of Asia.''
   His targets are nightspots in the neighborhood known as the
city's ``tourist belt,'' where scantily clad girls bump and grind
to disco music and _ for a price _ go out with male customers.
   Although the Ermita district pumps millions of dollars each year
into the city's economy, authorities have called for replacing the
nightspots with more wholesome family entertainment.
   ``Now, we are known internationally as the center of the flesh
trade, the Sin City of Asia,'' Brig. Gen. Alfredo Lim, the
capital's police chief, said recently. ``When we hear of this
reference, all of us feel a furious sense of outrage, for we all
know that we don't deserve such notoriety.''
   However, bar owners say the crackdown will cause worse problems,
add to economic hardship and advance the spread of sexual disease.
   Last month, police began raiding bars and discos in the city's
Ermita district. They have rounded up more than 2,000 barmaids,
known as ``hospitality girls,'' and detained dozens of foreigners
who operate some of more than 505 bars, restaurants, discos,
nightclubs and brothels in Ermita's 10-block strip.
   President Corazon Aquino has backed the raids, saying ``what we
should guard against is sacrificing the dignity and honor of the
Filipino woman.''
   But in a country with many economic problems, sex is big
business.
   Lim said he expects bar owners _ mostly Americans, Australians,
West Germans, Japanese and Filipinos _ to fight back by waging a
smear campaign against him and his police force.
   ``They are employing all tricks to stop us so they can earn
bundles and bundles of money,'' Lim said. ``They are capitalizing
on our women.''
   Indeed, an typical Ermita bar earns about $715 dollars on a
regular day. The bigger establishments average about $1,666 daily.
   But Gilbert Compuesto, general manager of the Hollywood Show
Palace, said the raids have been hurting the once-thriving
entertainment industry, cutting daily earnings by as much as 70
percent.
   Moreover, Ronnie Rueda, operations manager of a leading club
called Firehouse, said closing bars will force tens of thousands of
Manila prostitutes to go underground. She says that will make it
difficult to trace carriers of acquired immune deficiency syndrome
and venereal diseases.
   Lim said 80 percent of 2,000 women picked up in the raids have
been found suffering from venereal disease. The Department of
Health said at least 50 Filipinos, mostly hospitality girls, have
been infected with the AIDS virus, but none has developed its
active symptoms.
   ``The problem of venereal disease will spread out because the
women will become freelancers. They will hang around hotels and
restaurants,'' Rueda said. ``Who will manage them and check them
for diseases?''
   Compuesto said his group has offered to help police by closing
some establishments and ridding the area of free-lance prostitutes.
But he says their offer has been ignored.
   ``If they are really trying to cure the problem of morality,
this campaign should be nationwide,'' Compuesto said. ``How can
they solve immorality, prostitution or drug abuse if they are only
concentrating on Ermita?''
   Other critics say closing Ermita's seedy establishments would
force some displaced workers into a life of crime. ``If you're
starving and you're the only breadwinner in the family, I think
there is nothing else to do,'' said Kit Samson, a disc jockey.
   Compuesto said most bar girls are earning more than the $3
minimum daily wage of factory workers, not counting what they earn
once they leave the bars with customers.
   ``Thousands of people don't have jobs. We have jobs that we
enjoy, but now they want to get it from us,'' Compuesto said.
``What kind of logic is that?''
   ``It's really a hypocrisy of people to say that when tourists
come to the Philippines, they just want to see the sights in
Tagaytay, Baguio or some other part of the country,'' Compuesto
said. ``They need entertainment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
