<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0053EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PentagonVeep Bjt   04-26 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pentagon Veep, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: A Double-Duty Vice President for the Democrats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imagine it: newspaper stories next year that
begin with the words, ``Vice President and Secretary of Defense Sam
Nunn said today that ...''
   There would be a lot of ifs to be surmounted if Georgia's senior
Democratic senator were in a position to assume such a jawbreaking
and unprecedented dual title.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis would have to win the
Democratic presidential nomination, ask Nunn to be his running
mate, offer him the Pentagon as an inducement to accept, and then
win the fall campaign.
   But the idea is being floated _ apparently seriously _ by such
leading Democrats as former Virginia Gov. Charles Robb.
   Others say Nunn as a prominent Southerner and respected defense
expert would so strengthen a Dukakis ticket that he should be
promised he could be secretary of state or national security
adviser _ if he also agrees to run for vice president.
   Nunn has said that no matter what inducements might be offered,
his interest in the vice presidency is just about one on a scale of
10.
   But he has never said never.
   No vice president has ever served simultaneously as secretary of
defense.
   No vice president has ever served simultaneously as a member of
a president's Cabinet.
   But a number of people who became vice president had previously
served in presidential cabinets.
   John C. Calhoun served as vice president in one period and as
secretary of state at another.
   Presidents have appointed vice presidents to task forces on one
subject or another.
   President Reagan named Vice President George Bush to head a task
force on drugs and narcotics. President John F. Kennedy named his
vice president, Lyndon B. Johnson, to head a task force on space
exploration.
   Other vice presidents have had a strong influence on their
administrations. But that has been the rare exception rather than
the rule.
   While not barred by the Constitution, a vice president
simultaneously serving as secretary of defense might well discover
a thicket of unexpected conflicts.
   While the vice president has his job by election, a cabinet
officer must be confirmed by the Senate.
   The only job specifically assigned the vice president by the
Constitution is to serve as president of the Senate.
   Unexpected strains might arise if the Senate were asked to
confirm its own presiding office to serve as well in a Cabinet post.
   In the role of the Senate's presiding officer, the vice
president's only real power is his ability to cast tie-breaking
votes at moments of legislative impasse.
   Some senators might demand that a vice president who was also
the secretary of defense abstain from breaking a tie on closely
divided defense issues directly affecting his department.
   Such a decision would deprive the administration of its ability
to decide the issue in its favor by breaking the tie.
   Since 1981 Bush has broken seven ties, five of them on defense
issues.
   Secretaries of defense routinely testify before congressional
committees in defense of military budgets. There is some potential
awkwardness in a situation when the witness is also president of
the Senate.
   Concern might also be triggered if it became necessary for an
elected vice president also serving as secretary of defense to
travel with a president to an overseas conference.
   That would place both the president and vice president out of
the country at the same time. And that might become a more
worrisome situation if the country they were visiting were the
Soviet Union.
   Naming Nunn the national security adviser might create fewer
such problems since the person who fills that post is not confirmed
by the Senate.
   The vice presidency has not always been a happy post for the
person who held the job. Many have complained it consists of little
more than attending the funerals of foreign leaders.
   John Adams, the nation's first vice president, had some thoughts
on his job which he shared with his colleagues on the eve of a
visit to their chamber by President Washington.
   ``Gentlemen, I feel great difficulty (in) how to act,'' Adams
said.
   ``I am possessed of two separate powers. I am vice president. In
this I am nothing, but I may be everything.
   ``But I am president also of the Senate. When the president
comes into the Senate, what shall I be?''
   Some politicians are still thinking about what a vice president
shall be, at least when Sam Nunn's name comes up for discussion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Soviet-Summit Bjt   04-26 0772</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Summit, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Worry That Reagan Backing Away</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet officials are giving up hopes of sharp
cuts in strategic nuclear arsenals before President Reagan leaves
office and fear he may be returning to Red-baiting as he prepares
to make his exit.
   ``The problem is that the American position is moving not
forward but backward,'' said Valentin Falin, chairman of the
semi-official Novosti news agency.
   ``As far as I can see, we don't have enough time to prepare any
formal treaty'' before the Moscow summit May 29-June 2, Falin said
in an interview on Monday.
   Falin, a non-voting member of the policymaking Soviet Central
Committee and former Soviet ambassador to West Germany, blamed the
Reagan administration and the U.S. political process for what he
called wasted time since the summit in Washington last December.
   ``Certainly we cannot accomplish in the following four weeks
what we have failed to do in four months,'' said Falin.
``Certainly, we cannot expect miracles.''
   Falin also criticized a U.S. intelligence report saying the
Soviet economy has not improved despite economic reforms by Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   He said the joint report by the Central Intelligence Agency and
Pentagon analysts might have been done ``to show the president that
the Soviet Union is almost on its deathbed and it needs just
another push, that he should not talk with the Soviet Union, but
push it.''
   Falin contested the pessimistic U.S. intelligence report, and
said that under Gorbachev industrial production rose more than 4
percent last year and agricultural production was up 9 percent,
``higher than any rate in a decade.''
   The U.S. intelligence studies said the production of goods and
services last year in the Soviet Union grew by only 0.5 percent,
after a 4 percent jump in 1986.
   Falin said the gloomy U.S. intelligence report and recent
speeches by the president may signal a return to the harsh
anti-Soviet rhetoric of Reagan's first years in office, when he
called the Soviet Union an ``evil empire.''
   ``I would say that in his most recent speech, as well as his
speeches in March and February, the president was preoccupied with
rhetoric,'' said Falin. ``Bearing in mind that he will not remain
in office for a long time, he is trying to say in his last speeches
what he lost the chance to say in 1981 and 1982.
   ``We have already passed the time when we could tolerate such
rhetorical escapades.''
   Gorbachev complained after meeting with Secretary of State
George P. Shultz in Moscow last week that the administration was
``marking time'' in arms control negotiations.
   Reagan has said that he will not tailor his arms control
positions to meet political deadlines, and does not expect the
meeting in Moscow to wrap up the proposed Strategic Arms Reduction
Treaty to cut strategic nuclear arsenals by 30 to 50 percent.
   Previously, Soviet officials were more optimistic in public
assessments of the summit. Falin's comments reflected what has
become public pessimism by the Kremlin.
   Falin also accused the Reagan administration of dragging its
heels in negotiations for an international convention to curb
chemical weapons and on Warsaw Pact proposals for cuts in
non-nuclear forces in Europe.
   But whatever the prospects for the summit, said Falin, Reagan
``will be accorded our very warm and very deep hospitalities.''
   ``As we look at summits, we think they are convened not to
express sentiments, but to become milestones in the development of
bilateral and international relations,'' said Falin. ``This is a
problem for the president, because it is important for him how he
finishes his political career.''
   At best, said Falin, the meeting may produce a ``framework ...
for the development of future negotiations. This will make
negotiations easier.''
   But no START accord is likely by the end of the year, and it is
doubtful that Reagan and Gorbachev would meet again for what would
be their fifth summit, he said.
   After Moscow, said Falin, ``I do not think that your president
will have enough authority to make obligations which would have to
be fulfilled by his successor.''
   The Soviets, he said, are frustrated by the American political
process.
   ``In your country, it is a dead political season,'' said Falin.
``Every four years in your political life, one year is wasted.''
   He declined to say whether the Kremlin would prefer to deal with
Vice President George Bush, who has virtually clinched the
Republican presidential nomination, or with the Democratic
front-runner, Michael Dukakis.
   ``The Soviet leadership would prefer to negotiate with the
person who will be elected to the White House by your people,''
said Falin.
</TEXT>
