<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush Bjt   04-26 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, Bjt,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Set To Lock In Nomination With Delegates Picked Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush has had a virtual lock on the
Republican presidential nomination since late March, but today's
Pennsylvania primary should make it a mathematical certainty.
   The contest, in which Bush only faces token opposition from
former television evangelist Pat Robertson, should raise his
delegate total to more than the 1,139 needed for nomination at the
GOP convention in August in New Orleans.
   Savoring the situation on the eve of that vote, Bush told an
airport rally in Scranton, Pa., on Monday: ``We got a break in this
primary process. ... I'm glad it's gone my way.''
   The vice president noted that due to his overwhelming lead in
the race for the GOP nomination, the campaign spotlight has been
mostly on the Democratic contenders. But he said he wasn't
complaining.
   ``The news is being dominated by the Jackson-Dukakis fight.
That's the way it should be,' said Bush. ``I wouldn't trade
places.''
   Bush predicted that the general election ``is going to be hard
fought; it's going to be close.''
   The vice president was campaigning today in Ohio and Indiana,
both of which hold primaries a week from today. Bush was attending
a rally in Lima, Ohio, addressing the Ohio Broadcasters Association
in Cincinnati and holding an airport rally in Evansville, Ind.
   Bush tells audiences he'll still campaign through to the end of
the primary season and ``can't wait'' to debate the Democratic
nominee, who he has predicted will be Michael Dukakis.
   Even so, Bush remains vague on the terms for such events.
   ``I'm not going to let some outside group, even within my own
party, set the agenda,'' he told reporters in Pittsburgh.
   ``I'll appoint somebody who knows about setting up debates'' and
who could work with Democrats in coming up with a process agreeable
to both parties, he said.
   On another subject, Bush said in Pittsburgh that he fully backs
President Reagan's vow to veto trade legislation nearing a final
congressional vote.
   However, Bush said he hoped that some other way could be found
to notify workers of impending plant closings.
   The bill _ which Dukakis has said he would sign if he were
president _ contains a provision requiring 60 days advance when
plants are to be shut down.
   ``Maybe there's a compassionate way to give notice to a worker
and his family. But it has nothing to do with the trade bill,''
Bush said. ``I know it's an emotional issue but (the bill)
interferes with our ability to compete.''
   Bush did acknowledge that there were still areas of Pennsylvania
and elsewhere that had not shared fully in the economic recovery
that is now in its sixth year. But he criticized Democrats, saying
they ``talk about despair and agony.''
   ``You're going to see a clear choice'' in the general election,
he said.
   Bush has had a huge lead for the GOP nomination since his
remarkable 17-state sweep in the March 8 Super Tuesday contests, a
lead he solidified with the withdrawal from the race on March 29 of
Sen. Bob Dole, his only remaining major rival.
   Robertson is still technically a candidate but has ceased active
campaigning, saying there is no way Bush can be denied the
nomination. He has a scant 31 delegates, to Bush's 1,081.
   At his campaign appearance Monday at the Scranton-Wilkes-Barre
airport, Bush was confronted by about two dozen protesters.
   ``I'm glad to see the (Jesse) Jackson supporters here, or maybe
the Mike Dukakis supporters,'' he said.
   Of the Democrats, he said: ``I will welcome them in debate, I
will welcome taking on their ticket and we will beat them in the
fall.''
</TEXT>
