<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0112EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Kennedy'sRole     04-26 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Kennedy's Role,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supreme Court Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, two
months on the job, has given liberals their first real cause for
concern that he will help forge a solid conservative court majority.
   Kennedy was part of a 5-4 majority that said Monday it is
thinking about overturning a 1976 decision considered a key civil
rights victory.
   The ruling 12 years ago, never undone by Congress, interpreted a
Civil War era law as allowing lawsuits for monetary damages against
private businesses and individuals over alleged racial
discrimination.
   The decision in Runyon vs. McCrary, adopted in hundreds of lower
court cases since, has become what one civil rights lawyer called
``a major strand of the civil rights enforcement infrastructure.''
   Monday's announcement sparked sharp criticism and dire
predictions. Four justices said it could shake minorities' faith in
the court.
   ``Time alone will tell whether the erosion of faith is
unnecessarily precipitous,'' said Justice John Paul Stevens, a
swing vote who most often sides with the court's liberals. ``But in
the meantime some of the harm that will flow from today's order may
never be completely undone.''
   Ira Glasser, executive director of the American Civil Liberties
Union, agreed. ``The message is there's a new court and previous
rulings are up for grabs,'' he said. ``If this decision possibly
can be overturned, perhaps a lot more are endangered.''
   The court's three Reagan appointees _ Kennedy and Justices
Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia _ joined Chief Justice William
H. Rehnquist and Byron R. White in voting to restudy the 1976
decision.
   Joining Stevens in dissent were Justices William J. Brennan,
Thurgood Marshall, the court's leading liberals, and Justice Harry
A. Blackmun, another swing vote.
   Will there be five votes to overturn the 1976 precedent?
   Rehnquist, long the court's most conservative member, and White,
a conservative with a generally liberal voting record in civil
rights cases, dissented from the 1976 decision. Two likely votes to
overturn.
   Scalia is considered as conservative as Rehnquist. A third vote.
   The keys may be the votes of O'Connor, who in recent years has
shown greater independence from the court's conservative bloc, and
Kennedy, who joined the court last Feb. 18.
   Kennedy won Senate confirmation only after Reagan's nomination
of Robert H. Bork was rejected.
   Bork's critics in the Senate and among the civil rights
organizations who opposed him said they feared his replacing
centrist Lewis F. Powell on the court could threaten 30 years of
civil rights precedents.
   In its first seven years, the Reagan administration has had
little success persuading the court to adopt the president's
conservative agenda: outlawing abortion, restoring prayers in
public schools and curtailing affirmative action.
   Kennedy, whose views on such matters are unknown, is viewed as a
staunch conservative less ideological than Bork. Some liberals
voiced the hope that he would assume Powell's role as the court's
voice of judicial restraint.
   But the concerns voiced during the Bork nomination fight were
echoed Monday.
   Calling Kennedy the key to a ``new court,'' the ACLU's Glaser
said: ``Bork had an extensive record of civil rights animus and
Kennedy did not. But this isn't encouraging.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Richard Carelli has covered the Supreme Court for
The Associated Press since 1976.
