<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NukeInvestigation     04-26 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuke Investigation,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Nuclear Agency Should Improve Its Internal
Investigations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nuclear Regulatory Commission Chairman Lando
Zech says he agrees with a congressional study recommending that
the agency improve its internal investigations.
   He made the statement Monday as his agency released a study by
the General Accounting Office that said the NRC needs to ensure
that its investigations are done professionally and competently.
   ``The commission will give careful consideration to (the) entire
report in our continuing efforts to assure that we carry out our
investigative responsibilities fairly and efficiently,'' Zech said.
   In the study, GAO said ``the important mission and critical
safety role of the NRC require that it possess a first-rate
investigative capability.''
   GAO, the investigative wing of Congress, said the study was
based on review of three investigations made within the nuclear
agency. GAO said that in two cases, the work done by the NRC's
Office of Inspector and Auditor was not thorough enough.
   One case involved allegations by an NRC inspector that superiors
had pressured him to change findings in 1986 about safety
conditions at the Comanche Peak Steam Electric Station in Texas.
   The other involved alleged improper discussions in 1986 between
Victor Stello, the NRC's executive director of operations, and
Steve White, head of the Tennessee Valley Authority's NRC-regulated
nuclear program.
   GAO said its review supported the findings of NRC investigators
who said neither matter was improper. But in both cases GAO said
that NRC investigators had not interviewed individuals with key
roles.
   The third case looked into NRC's probe of how a copy of an
internal NRC document turned up in 1985 in the files of the
Louisiana Power and Light Company's Waterford III plant _ along
with a memo from LPL's holding company saying the document had been
``received from sources inside'' the NRC.
   GAO said notations on the copy indicated it was duplicated from
the file copy in the office of NRC Commissioner Thomas Roberts, who
was in charge of investigating the alleged leak.
   GAO was critical of the ``very limited'' investigation made by
Roberts, but GAO said it was unable to determine how the copy
reached the regulated utility.
   ``A properly conducted investigation might have provided NRC
with the identity'' of the leaker, according to GAO.
   The case, GAO said, ``demonstrated that a regulated utility
secured unauthorized access to NRC documents. The ability to obtain
such materials could impact on the NRC's enforcement program,
licensing functions and regulatory procedures.''
   ``The NRC should assure that its investigators conduct their
work in a competent manner using professional standards,'' said
GAO, adding that there is a lack of coordination between the NRC's
Office of Investigations and Office of Inspector and Auditor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
