<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArmsTreaty     04-26 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Treaty,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Leaders Try To Find Way To Assure May INF Ratification</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republicans are trying to make sure the
medium-range missile treaty is ratified before President Reagan
meets Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev in Moscow on May 29, but
the majority leader says Democrats won't be rushed.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., appealed on Monday for
swift action on the treaty. He said the president deserves to be
accommodated on his wish not to go to Moscow empty-handed.
   President Reagan has said it is important for the Senate to
ratify the treaty before he meets Gorbachev because there is little
chance the two sides will make further arms control progress unless
the Senate has acted favorably.
   But Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia said he
refused ``to be rushed or harried'' on the matter before remaining
problems are cleared away.
   Byrd said he will not call up the treaty for debate before May
9. He added he may not do so then unless it can be shown the
Soviets agree with the U.S. position that the pact bans
medium-range ``futuristic'' weapons such as those using laser rays
or particle beam generators.
   Dole and other Republicans huddled Monday with White House chief
of staff Howard Baker and national security adviser Colin Powell to
devise a strategy to deal with Byrd's concerns and get the treaty
debate started.
   Byrd replied: ``I want to accommodate the president too, and
will accommodate the president where I can. ... But that is not my
first responsibility. ... That is not my first objective.
   ``I'm going to accommodate the Senate and our responsibilities
under the Constitution first, before the accommodation of anybody
else or any other office.''
   The treaty is silent on future weapons, but U.S. negotiators
contend the pact bans all weapons with ranges of from 300 miles to
3,400 miles, no matter how they are armed.
</TEXT>
