<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--BrazilOilFire     04-26 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Brazil Oil Fire,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Rig Fire Cuts Brazilian Production By 11 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three ships were fighting a fire
on Brazil's largest offshore oil rig, and the state oil company,
Petrobas, said the blaze has caused an 11 percent drop in the
nation's petroleum output.
   Carlos Pinto, Petrobras spokesman, said the fire broke out
Sunday when gas leaked from the Enchova platform in the Campos
Basin, Brazil's richest oil-producing region, 120 miles east of Rio
De Janeiro. The 250 workers on the oil rig were safely evacuated to
a ship, he said.
   Three ships on Monday continued to spray the platform with water
in an effort to put out the fire, the spokesman said.
   Enchova and four connected fields were shut down, halting the
production of 71,000 barrels of oil and 2 million cubic meters of
gas per day, Pinto said.
   The campos basin offshore fields produce 60 percent of the
nation's oil output of 615,000 barrels a day and 40 percent of the
17 million cubic meters of gas. Brazil imports about 45 percent of
the oil it uses.
</TEXT>
