<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     04-26 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Appeared Relaxed Heading Into Today's Pennsylvania Contest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was story time for 28 toddlers and the
choice was an old favorite, ``The Very Hungry Caterpillar.'' But
the storyteller was a newcomer to the Discovery School _ Michael
Dukakis, the front-runner in today's Pennsylvania primary.
   He was a hit with the preschool set. Monday was a day of big
crowds and loud cheers for Dukakis, and the Massachusetts governor
was trying out a relaxed campaign style.
   Dukakis held a big lead over rival Jesse Jackson in
Pennsylvania, and about all aides had to wonder about was how big a
delegate victory he could win in the state.
   ``I look forward to working with you and to winning with you
tomorrow,'' Dukakis told about 500 people in Pittsburgh on the eve
of the primary.
   In his final day of campaigning before the Pennsylvania vote,
Dukakis was at ease and ready to quip.
   ``I saw a Bush sign around here some place,'' he asked 1,000
gathered on the University of Scranton campus.``You know, Bush is
the only guy who had a baseball league named after him.''
   Then he asked if the crowd held any fans of the Baltimore
Orioles _ the team with the worst record in baseball at the moment.
   ``Where are the Orioles fans around here? You know if you're an
Orioles fan you have to be headed for a career in social work or
something. You have to be very charitable,'' he said.
   But Scranton brought Dukakis face-to-face with some of the most
strident demonstrators of the campaign thus far. Fifty
anti-abortion protesters sought to form a gantlet for the candidate
outside the hall at the University of Scranton.
   ``Stop Dukakis! Stop abortion!'' they chanted. Dukakis was
escorted to the car by a group of aides and police officers, amid
much pushing and shoving.
   From Philadelphia to Pittsburgh, from Erie to Harrisburg,
Dukakis took his message of jobs and party unity.
   ``There is no more important challenge facing the president of
United States. Make no mistake about it. I'm a dyed-in-the-wool,
true-blue full-employment Democrat,'' he said in Erie.
   He repeatedly urged his supporters to ignore the polls and to
get out the vote _ ``Pollsters don't vote,'' he said.
   A win in the complicated election Tuesday would boost his lead
for the 1988 Democratic presidential nomination in both delegates
and momentum.
   ``It isn't enough just to vote for me,'' he told 2,000 cheering
supporters at a park in Erie. ``This is one election where you've
got to vote more than once and it's legal. I need your vote as a
candidate. Our delegates need your votes. ... We must do both.''
   The crowd was enthusiastic, often interrupting Dukakis with
applause and cheers. After the speech, many in the crowd pressed
forward to touch Dukakis and to shake his hand. Several babies were
handed to him. Smiling, he kisssed them.
   ``With your help, we can leave Pennsylvania with the kind of
enthusiasm and the kind of energy and the kind of momentum that a
victory will give,'' he told them.
   At his first stop in Phildelphia, Dukakis reached out to the
black community that is the core of Jackson's support.
   ``We have too much to do in this country to divide ourselves,''
Dukakis told about 60 people gathered a black church in Northeast
Philadelphia. ``I'm someone who believes that one of the jobs of a
governor and a president _ perhaps the most important job _ is to
bring this country together, brown, black and white, business and
labor. These past seven years have been a divisive seven years.''
</TEXT>
