<HEAD>Clerical Strike Closes Many Businesses In Iceland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strike by 15,000 clerical workers
interrupted domestic airline service and forced many shops and
businesses to close.
   The workers began their strike on Friday in an attempt to win a
27 percent increase for the lowest paid among them.
   Icelandair halted local flights because of the strike, and
clerical workers were expected to walk out of Keflavik
international airport on Wednesday.
   Hotels in Reykjavik were nearly empty on Monday, and hotel
managers said their financial loss will be considerable if the
strike continues.
   The workers struck after the employers' organization turned down
a demand by the unions that minimum wages be increased by 27
percent.
