<HEAD>Retired Roman Catholic Cardinal Treated For Lung Congestion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John Dearden, the retired Roman Catholic
archbishop of Detroit, has been hospitalized after doctors
corrected fluid congestion in his lungs, officials said.
   Dearden, 80, was resting comfortably Monday afternoon at
Providence Hospital in Southfield and would be kept several days
for observation, said Brenda Marshall, a spokeswoman for the
archdiocese.
   Doctors treated the congestion with medication and did not
expect complications, Marshall said. But Dearden was listed in
serious but stable condition because of his age and because he
suffered a heart attack in 1977, she said.
   Dearden cited health reasons and age for retiring in 1980 as
spiritual leader of the 1.2-million-member archdiocese, a post he
had held 21 years. He was succeeded by the Rev. Edmund Szoka.
