<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Harvard Resignation,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvard Law Dean To Resign Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harvard Law School Dean James Vorenberg
announced he will resign at the end of the 1988-89 academic year to
return to teaching, the school said.
   Vorenberg, 60, was appointed dean in 1981.
   Harvard President Derek Bok said Monday he accepted the
resignation with ``great regret but much admiration for his
tenure.''
   ``Under Jim Vorenberg's leadership, the law school has not only
maintained the traditional excellence of its academic program but
has broadened its curriculum to meet the challenges of contemporary
society and the needs of today's legal profession,'' he said.
   Bok said that under Vorenberg the law school has developed new
programs in areas such as human rights, law and economics, and
international criminal justice.
   Vorenberg also introduced a plan to help pay educational loans
for students and alumni accepting low-paying, law-related jobs, Bok
said.
   Bok said a search for Vorenberg's successor would begin this
summer.
