<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     04-26 0886</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lyng Says Europe Needs to Address Market Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community needs to get
serious about seeking solutions to ``an increasingly chaotic
condition'' in global agricultural trade, says Agriculture
Secretary Richard E. Lyng.
   But the EEC ``is unwilling to even define a longterm goal in the
reform of the rules of international trade,'' Lyng said. ``They
term our proposal to eventually eliminate trade-distorting
subsidies as `unrealistic' or `too far, too fast.' Yet, they have
not stated what alternative they will accept.''
   It has been almost a year and a half since the new Uruguay Round
of multinational trade talks began under the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade, or GATT. Yet, Lyng said, the major agricultural
shippers are expanding export subsidies rather than reducing them.
   Lyng warned that failure to make progress in the negotiations by
the time of the GATT midterm review in Montreal next December
``will bring into question the chance for eventual success'' of the
Uruguay Round.
   ``I'm not pessimistic, but I'll have to admit there's not a
whole lot to be optimistic about at this point,'' Lyng said.
   Lyng said the EEC, for example, has just paid a subsidy equal to
$126 per metric ton to wheat exporters, and continues to pay ``huge
subsidies on a host of other commodities'' including mixed feed,
$291 per ton; durum wheat, $281 per ton; and barley, $130 per ton.
   The United States, he said at a meeting of the Newspaper Farm
Editors of America, is calling for agricultural trade reform at the
Uruguay Round. Ultimately, under the U.S. proposal, international
trade barriers and subsidies would be eliminated over a period of
10 years or so.
   Lyng said the ``excessive influence of governments in farm
product markets leads to a grossly inefficient allocation of
resources in developed countries and leave poorer, developing
countries in economic shambles.''
   The worst offenders are the big nations ``who are unwilling or
reluctant to change,'' he said. Japan, with huge trade surpluses
from exports of industrial and consumer goods, clings to import
barriers on products such as beef, rice and citrus.
   Other exporting countries, including the EEC, say they are not
alone in subsidizing agricultural trade and point to the Export
Enhancement Program operated by the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
   Under EEP, as it is known, private exporters are given surplus
USDA-owned commodities so they can sell grain or other products to
selected foreign countries, including the Soviet Union, China and
others. Department officials claim EEP was necessary to compete
with Europe's subsidized exports.
   After Lyng spoke to the farm editors, his department routinely
announced several more export subsidy actions under the program.
China was sold an additional 95,000 tons of U.S. wheat, which
carried subsidies of $27.52 per ton.
   Another EEP subsidy was for 300 tons of frozen broiler chickens
or fryer legs sold to the Canary Islands. The subsidies amounted to
about $237 per ton. Officials said an additional 400 tons of frozen
poultry are still available for sale to the Canary Islands at
subsidized prices.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rick Richards of the Gary (Ind.) Post-Tribune
is the winner of this year's Glenn Cunningham Farm Editor of the
Year award by the Newspaper Farm Editors of America.
   Richards and other annual contest winners were honored Monday
night at the association's 35th annual dinner at the National Press
Club.
   Winners in specific categories included: farm news, Steve
Painter, The Wichita (Kan.) Eagle-Beacon; farm column, Steve
Painter; farm feature, Dan Miller, Iowa Farmer Today, Cedar Rapids;
and farm series, Rick Richards, Post-Tribune, Gary, Ind.
   Galen Moses of the Gainesville (Fla.) Sun was elected president
of the association, succeeding Sonja Hillgren, United Press
International, Washington, D.C.
   The association also voted to change its name to National
Association of Agricultural Journalists and to expand its
membership base to include agricultural magazine writers and
editors.
   Other officers include: Kathleen Davis, Lubbock (Texas)
Avalanche Journal, first vice president; and Audrey Mackiewicz,
Huron, Ohio, executive secretary-treasurer.
   Regional vice presidents named were:
   Northeast _ Roger Runningen, Small Newspapers, Washington, D.C.,
bureau.
   Southeast _ Thornton Hartley, Florida Times-Union, Gainesville
bureau.
   Midwest _ Kelly Boldan, Agri-News, Rochester, Minn.
   Southwest _ Steve Painter, The Wichita (Kan.) Eagle-Beacon.
   West _ Helen Willard, Prosser (Wash.) Record-Bulletin.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private contractor has helped farmers in
five southwest Kansas counties beat a federal deadline for
conservation planning, says the Agriculture Department.
   Wilson Scaling, chief of the department's Soil Conservation
Service, said Monday a consulting company _ John Ho and Associates
Inc., Dallas, Texas _ completed planning by mid-April, less than
half the time called for in its one-year contract.
   The 1985 farm law gives farmers until Dec. 31, 1989, to complete
conservation plans for protecting highly erodible land. Scaling
said district conservationists in Kansas said they would not be
able to help all the farmers with planning in time to meet the
deadline.
   ``One of the most successful ideas was to contract out the
planning to a qualified private company,'' he said.
   Kansas has the second-largest amount of cropland of any state,
some 29.1 million acres, he said. Of that, the agency estimates
more than one-third is highly erodible.
   The counties included in the contract with the Texas firm were
Finney, Greeley, Hamilton, Seward and Wichita.
</TEXT>
