<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Abortion-Arizona     04-26 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion-Arizona,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arizona House Narrowly Defeats Anti-abortion Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill banning abortion, which sponsors
said was designed to force the U.S. Supreme Court to reconsider a
1973 decision, fell just one vote short of passage in the Arizona
House.
   Supporters said they may attempt to revive the measure, termed
``obviously unconstitutional'' by its opponents.
   The House voted 30-28 in favor of the bill, one short of the 31
needed for passage.
   The Supreme Court legalized abortion with its landmark Roe vs.
Wade decision in 1973. Backers of the Arizona legislation, which
would have made abortion illegal except to save the life of the
mother, said they believed that the present Supreme Court might
reverse the 1973 decision if given the chance to do so.
   Supporters of the bill said its passage would make Arizona the
first state to outlaw abortion since the Supreme Court decision.
   Noting how close they had come to getting the bill passed,
backers said they would consider bringing it back for another vote
before the end of the current legislation session.
   But, even if it succeeds in the House, the chances of the bill's
becoming law appeared to be slim.
   Gov. Rose Mofford announced that she probably would veto it.
   ``My impression is that it's unconstitional,'' Mrs. Mofford
said, adding ``I can't legislate morality.''
</TEXT>
