<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoxOffice     04-26 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Beetlejuice' Beats `Casual Sex' and `Colors' by Wide Margin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Beetlejuice,'' the supernatural spoof
featuring Michael Keaton's romp in the hereafter, was the nation's
film box office leader last weekend, beating ``Casual Sex?'' and
``Colors'' by a wide margin.
   ``Beetlejuice'' returned $6.2 million while the teen-movie
``Casual Sex?'' narrowly edged the gang-film ``Colors'' for the No.
2 spot. Both movies made $3.8 million.
   Other than a few fistfights, the debut two weeks ago of
``Colors'' didn't incite the violence predicted by some officials.
But last weekend, gunfire erupted between suspected gang members
outside a theater in Stockton.
   A Los Angeles gang member reportedly upset with the way his gang
was depicted in the movie fatally shot a possible rival gang member.
   Mann Theaters of Los Angeles voluntarily pulled the movie from
the Regency Theater where the shooting occurred, said San Joaquin
County District Attorney John Phillips.
   The non-stop carnage in ``Above the Law,'' featuring a Chicago
cop's single-handed drug-ring battle, brought in $3.2 million to
finish fourth last weekend.
   ``Biloxi Blues,'' the Neil Simon yarn starring Matthew Broderick
as an Army boot camp private, was fifth at $2.8 million.
   ``The Last Emperor,'' the Bernardo Bertolucci epic that won nine
Academy Awards earlier this month, was sixth with $2.6 million and
``Moonstruck,'' which won Oscars for Cher and Olympia Dukakis, was
seventh with $2.3 million.
   The Disney Studios took the No. 8 and No. 9 spots with ``Return
to Snowy River II'' and ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' respectively.
The ``Snowy River'' sequel brought in $2.1 million and ``Good
Morning, Vietnam'' grossed $1.4 million.
   The Robert Redford-directed film ``Milagro Beanfield War''
rounded out the top 10 with $1.4 million.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release, and estimated production costs when available.
   1. ``Beetlejuice,'' Warner Bros., $6.2 million, 1,582 screens,
$3,919 per screen, $40.36 million, four weeks, n-a.
   2. ``Casual Sex?'' Universal, $3.84 million, 1,264 screens,
$3,038 per screen, $3.8 million, one week, n-a.
   3. ``Colors,'' Orion, $3.80 million, 480 screens, 7,923 per
screen, $10.7 million, two weeks, n-a.
   4. ``Above the Law,'' Warner Bros., $3.19 million, 868 screens,
$3,686 per screen, $8.15 million, three weeks, n-a.
   5. ``Biloxi Blues,'' Universal, $2.8 million, 1,246 screens,
$2,265 per screen, $31.4 million, five weeks, $16 million.
   6. ``The Last Emperor,'' Columbia, $2.59 million, 877 screens,
$2,981 per screen, $33 million, 22 weeks, n-a.
   7. ``Moonstruck,'' MGM-UA, $2.3 million, 1,009 screens, $2,318
per screen, $66.8 million, 18 weeks, $17 million.
   8. ``Return to Snowy River II,'' Disney, $2.1 million, 1,092
screens, $1,963 per screen, $6.1 million, two weeks, n-a.
   9. ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' Disney, $1.467 million, 1,042
screens, $1,408 per screen, $113.6 million, 17 weeks, $21 million.
   10. ``Milagro Beanfield War,'' Universal, $1.464 million, 390
screens, $3,755 per screen, $4.9 million, six weeks, n-a.
