<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmExports     04-26 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Exports,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Barriers Hamper US Sales Abroad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Belgians crave crawdads but have yet to sample
catfish, while Saudi Arabians find American rice so much to their
liking that they package rice from Thailand to make it look as if
it came from here, the Department of Agriculture says.
   Those are a few of the useful bits of knowledge for Americans
who want to export food products compiled by the department in a
recent 204-page book called ``Trade Policies and Market
Opportunities for U.S. Farm Exports.'' It tells of quotas, tariffs,
surcharges, health and sanitary rules and other restrictions that
plague American exporters to more than 100 countries.
   The April issue of the department's magazine, ``Foreign
Agriculture,'' gives an account of the report.
   For example, wine can't be advertised in Norway and Sweden _
governments there want to hold down drinking. In France, it's
margarine that can't be advertised because the government wants to
protect French dairy farmers from competition on their sales of
butter.
   Egypt won't buy almonds at all because it's protecting its
meager stock of foreign exchange. India won't buy tallow for
religious reasons: the cows it is made from are sacred to Hindus.
Italy is said to know too little about American tallow to order it.
   None of the 12 countries in the European Community will buy
foreign meat if it's mixed with soy protein _ they say it's to
protect consumers.
   There's no duty in Austria on imports of that American rice the
Saudis like so much. Bahrain, a Saudi neighbor, buys rice almost
entirely from India and Pakistan.
   The book makes no judgment on whether the obstacles are fair or
unfair, an issue much discussed in Congress during the current
debate on the trade bill.
   ``Virtually every country provides support and protection to
agriculture in some degree,'' it explains. ``In some cases this is
done primarily through policies that raise prices to consumers by
protecting the domestic market; in other cases, assistance is
provided through subsidies financed by the taxpayer.''
   In some cases, the countries do not believe that their actions
constitute barriers. In other cases, the book implies that American
producers could do more to sell their products. Under the heading
``reason for the barrier'' a frequent explanation is ``lack of
awareness.''
   That is the cause it gives for low sales in Japan not only of
American catfish and crayfish _ which are lumped together _ but
also grapefruit juice, frozen potatoes, wood panel products,
hardwoods from temperate climates and beer.
   Belgium is also noted as a country where lack of awareness of
the American product keeps down the sale of catfish. The book says
nothing about the Belgian appetite for crayfish, which is
considerable.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0040EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Saudi-Nuclear     04-26 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Saudi-Nuclear,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kingdom To Sign Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia on Tuesday decided to sign
the nuclear weapons non-proliferation treaty, a strong indication
it will not seek nuclear warheads for intermediate-range missiles
it recently acquired from China.
   The official Saudi Press Agency reported that King Fahd made the
decision during a Cabinet meeting in Riyadh, the Saudi capital.
   The meeting was called in response to a recommendation by Prince
Saud al-Faisal, the Saudi foreign minister, that the kingdom sign
the international treaty against the spread of nuclear arms.
   An account of the Cabinet discussions and decisions at the
meeting, which ended before dawn, was issued by Information
Minister Ali al-Shaer and distributed by the agency. The agency,
monitored in Bahrain, did not elaborate.
   It appeared the timing of the decision was designed primarily to
reassure the United States that the kingdom will not try to arm its
CSS-2 missiles with nuclear warheads. The decision also was viewed
as an attempt to blunt Israel's allegations that the missiles
constituted a threat to its safety.
   Saudi Arabia, the Middle East petroleum giant and the world's
largest exporter of crude oil, was reported to have recently
acquired from Beijing an undisclosed number of CSS-2 missiles
capable of reaching virtually any point in the Middle East,
including Israel.
   Israel has voiced fears the Saudis might be seeking to acquire
nuclear warheads for the missiles and indicated it might deal a
preemptive blow.
</TEXT>
