<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Trade     04-26 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tug Of War Over Trade Bill Under Way in Senate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tug of war is under way in the Senate as
sponsors of a 1,000-page trade bill move to line up enough votes to
show they could override a threatened presidential veto.
   ``You let this bill go down the tubes and I'll tell you where
the champagne corks will be popping,'' Finance Committee Chairman
Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, told senators Monday. ``They'll be popping
in Japan and they'll be popping in Germany.''
   The bill is expected to clear the Senate with votes to spare.
But from there it heads for the White House and, evidently, a
presidential veto.
   The question is whether it will receives the two-thirds support
it would need to override a veto. Sponsors and the administration
are looking for any wavering votes they can still find.
   Major provisions of the bill would streamline the system under
which the United States imposes import curbs to punish
international trade violations and aid industries threatened by
foreign competition.
   Other provisions range from billions of dollars in new
agricultural subsidies to repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil
companies.
   The administration has saved most of its fire lately for a
provision that would require all but the smallest employers to give
60-day notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs.
   The Senate had been set to vote today, but with neither side
satisfied that it had done everything possible, leaders said they
might wait until Wednesday.
   As the showdown neared, lawmakers and congressional staffers on
both sides said the outcome appeared too close to call.
   Democrats were expected to vote for the bill overwhelmingly
while Republicans were divided on whether to stand by the Reagan
administration in hopes of getting a slimmed-down version later.
   ``It's close,'' Bentsen told reporters. ``It was an uphill
battle, but now it's a tossup.''
   The House approved the measure 312-107 on Thursday, more than
enough to override a veto.
   ``I know this is an election year and the majority party may be
looking for a campaign issue rather than a trade bill, but I am
confident the Congress could pass a better bill if this one is
rejected,'' Sen. Robert T. Stafford, R-Vt., said.
   Democratic leaders have been saying it would be tough to bring
another trade bill onto the Senate floor before Congress leaves
Washington to campaign full time this fall.
   For one thing, they say, bringing such a bill onto the Senate
floor without something like the year of committee consideration
that shaped the current version could make the new one a target for
an array of amendments that in themselves could torpedo the measure.
   As dubious as they have been about a stripped-down trade bill,
however, Democratic leaders have left the door open a crack for
such an effort if Reagan's veto is sustained.
   One of the first items to go in any new bill could be the
plant-closings provision.
   Business groups say it would dry up capital for investment and
frighten off customers, but it has strong backing from labor.
   Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo., told the Senate ``high officials
of the administration'' had told him that portions of the bill
``are acceptable to the administration.''
   ``We pulled off the hat trick, we pulled off the miracle,''
Danforth said. ``The administration now says that while it's not
perfect it is something that the president would be willing to sign
without plant closings.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FishOil     04-26 0686</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fish Oil,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fish Oil May Solve Serious Transplant Drug Problem, Says
Researcher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fish oil may help the thousands of patients
each year who receive life-saving organ transplants only to develop
serious kidney disease from the toxic effects of a drug needed to
prevent organ rejection, a researcher says.
   Dr. William M. Bennett said Monday that three medical centers
now are testing the use of fish oil to smooth out the harsh side
effects of cyclosporine, a drug taken by transplant patients to
prevent organ rejection.
   The beneficial effects of cyclosporine have made it possible for
thousands to receive kidney, heart and liver transplants. The
primary action of the drug is to supress the body's immune response.
   Side effects of the drug, however, can be very serious for
patients already in delicate health.
   Bennett, speaking at a National Kidney Foundation seminar, said
virtually every patient who takes cyclosprine suffers some change
in kidney function, probably as the result of constricted flow
through blood vessels of the kidney.
   At least one heart transplant patient, he said, has survived the
transplant operation only to suffer complete kidney failure due to
the toxic effects of cyclosporine.
   Bennett, a professor at the Oregon Health Sciences University in
Portland, said he and other researchers determined in laboratory
studies that by mixing cyclosporine with a fish oil high in omega-3
fatty acid its bad side effects can be reduced without blocking the
good results.
   Oil from fishes such as salmon and other cold water fish, said
Bennett, are known to reduce the formation of thromboxanes, a
protein that causes blood vessels to constrict. In laboratory
animals, he said, this effect of fish oil seems to counter kidney
damage caused by cyclosporine.
   A limited number of patients now are receiving the fish oil and
cyclosporine at clinics in Portland, Ore. and Boston, he said.
   Bennett said if the toxic effects of cyclosporine can be
countered successfully, then there may be expanded uses for the
drug. Use of cyclosporine has been suggested in such auto immune
diseases as rheumatoid arthritis and some types of diabetes.
   Another researcher at the National Kidney Foundation seminar
said extensive clinical trials are under way on a new
genetically-engineered hormone that will counter anemia among
patients who must depend on artificial kidneys.
   Dr. Joseph W. Eschbach, a professor at the University of
Washington in Seattle, said more than 100,000 Americans with failed
kidneys are receiving dialysis, a procedure that cleans the blood
of impurities normally filtered out by the kidneys.
   Up to 75,000 of these patients suffer from anemia, characterized
by a shortage in their blood of red cells, which carry oxygen to
the cells. For about 25,000, the problem is so serious that they
must receive blood transfusions.
   Because of the anemia, Eschbach said that only about a third of
the dialysis patients are able to return to work and many ``become
part of the couch. All they can do is just lie there.''
   The federal government spends about $2 billion a year caring for
dialysis patients, he said, and some of this money could be saved
if more patients were able to correct their anemia.
   Eschbach said research has shown that the reason for this anemia
is that the failed kidneys no longer produce a hormone called
erythropoietin. In normal function, the kidneys secrete this
hormone when red cells are reduced in the blood. The hormone goes
to the bone marrow and causes blood formation tissue there to make
more red blood cells.
   Scientists have now isolated the human gene that makes the
hormone. This gene has been inserted into the nucleus of Chinese
hamster ovary cells which now are producing large amounts of
erythropoietin.
   Dialysis patients who have received erythropoietin injections,
said Eschbach, have recovered from their anemia and many have
returned to work.
   Some have improved to the point that they have been able to
receive kidney transplants and are no longer on dialysis, he said.
   The hormone now is in clinical trials and is expected to be
available for general use by next spring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0205EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra     04-26 0766</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North, Other Iran-Contra Defendants on Collision Course with Judge</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WX6-7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for Oliver L. North and his
Iran-Contra co-defendants are on a collision course with the judge,
as they argue for dismissal of the case on grounds that evidence
was gathered illegally.
   A pre-trial hearing Monday began on a sour note for the defense
team, when U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell ruled lawyers for
North and two other defendants violated his ground rules for the
hearing, and would be barred from presenting any witnesses.
   From that point the proceeding rolled downhill for the defense
lawyers, as Gesell rebuffed their request to question the top
prosecutors _ and grand jury witnesses _ about their exposure to
testimony given to Congress under a grant of immunity.
   Nor would Gesell permit the defense to immediately review
instructions given by independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh and his
staff to grand jurors, when they were advised in their secret
proceedings to avoid news accounts of the congressional hearings.
   ``I have a great sense of unfairness for my client,'' complained
North lawyer Brendan V. Sullivan Jr. as the hearing dragged on.
   Gesell responded moments later, ``I don't think lawyers should
run'' the hearing. ``I should.''
   Nonetheless, Gesell made no final ruling on Sullivan's charge of
``enormous taint'' in the case, and the judge scheduled another
hearing for Wednesday.
   If Gesell finds after that hearing questions remain about the
validity of the prosecution evidence, he can order further hearings
on the subject that could push back the judge's initial hope for a
July trial date.
   Walsh is barred from using a witness' immunized testimony to
prosecute that witness, except for perjury. However, the judge said
it would still be possible to have a trial even if some evidence
were obtained improperly, because the ``tainted'' evidence and
certain witnesses could be barred from the case.
   Three defendants testified before Congress last summer under
immunity grants: North, the former National Security Council
staffer who directed the once-secret operations that sent arms to
Iran, and to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels when such assistance was
prohibited by law; his boss at the time, National Security Adviser
John M. Poindexter; and businessman Albert Hakim, who handled the
millions of dollars in Iran arms sales profits that were stashed in
Swiss bank accounts.
   Hakim's partner, retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V. Secord,
is the fourth defendant but his leadoff testimony at the
congressional hearings was given without an immunity grant.
   The defendants are charged with conspiring to use U.S. arms
sales profits illegally to aid the Contras, and to cover up their
actions. They also are accused of theft of government property,
obstruction of government inquiries, making false statements, and
destruction of documents.
   While Monday's proceedings were under way, defense lawyers filed
a notice that they would appeal Gesell's pre-trial rulings that
went against them.
   The judge had invited them to do so during the hearing, saying
the defense objections ``stand out like the Statue of Liberty.''
   ``Go ahead and have your romp upstairs (in the appeals court),''
Gesell said.
   The only witness Monday was Walsh, who testified about his
repeated written and oral instructors to his staff, to witnesses
and to grand jurors to avoid being influenced by immunized
testimony. He said his evidence was gathered independently, and
filed weekly with the court.
   Walsh did admit, however, that one of his assistants,
Christopher Todd, has voluntarily withdrawn from aspects of the
case because of possible exposure to immunized testimony.
   ``I don't know anything about the conditions'' that prompted
Todd's decision, Walsh said. ``He didn't want to taint me. I don't
know whether he was tainted or not.''
   Sullivan hammered again and again at Walsh's admission that he
didn't know whether everyone complied with his orders. Compliance,
Walsh said, sometimes required a degree of common sense.
   The prosecutor sarcastically told Sullivan ``there was no
discussion of how quickly you could turn off the television'' if a
report on the congressional hearings came on.
   And when Sullivan pointed out that comedy shows such as
``Saturday Night Live'' made references to immunized testimony,
Walsh said he had no idea whether those receiving his instructions
turned off the programs.
   But Walsh said each of his assistants knows ``he's jeopardizing
the investigation if he's careless.''
   Herbert J. Stern, a former federal judge and veteran prosecutor
representing Walsh on the immunity issue, said he can show ``every
bit of the evidence was independently derived.''
   ``The extensive procedures of insulation are just extras and are
really not needed,'' Stern said.
</TEXT>
