<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0212EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Arabs     04-26 0784</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Arabs,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Despite Some Tensions, Arab-American Groups Still Seem To Back
Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson appears to be retaining the
support of his most loyal constituencies, the Arab-Americans,
despite upsetting many of them with comments about Palestine
Liberation Organization chief Yasser Arafat.
   ``There's still a great deal of spirit out there for Jesse,''
especially after Jackson modified his remarks on Arafat, said
Abdeen Jabara, president of the American-Arab Anti-Discrimination
Committee.
   Arab-Americans have contributed more than $400,000 to Jackson's
1988 presidential campaign, including some $90,000 raised Sunday at
a private home in Washington, according to his key Arab affairs
adviser James Zogby. A handful of fund-raising events are scheduled
in coming weeks in California, Michigan, Pennsylvania, New York and
Ohio.
   One of Jackson's most prominent Arab-American backers, radio
personality Casey Kasem, is planning a big fundraiser in Los
Angeles just before California's June 7 primary.
   And there are 43 Arabs and Muslims running to be Jackson
delegates in California, according to Salam Al-Marayati of the
Muslim Political Action Committee in Los Angeles.
   Jackson appears to have assuaged the concerns of some Arab
supporters who were upset by his comment on CBS-TV's ``Face the
Nation'' that as president he would not meet with Arafat.
   Jabara accused Jackson of ``caving in'' to Jewish groups, and
said many members of his group were dismayed by the TV interview.
   But the transcript of a subsequent interview that was printed in
the New York Times seemed to ``clear up any misunderstandings,''
Jabara said.
   In that interview, Jackson pointed out there is a law, which he
said should be changed, prohibiting U.S. officials from talking to
the PLO because the PLO does not recognize Israel.
   He said the PLO is ``by far the most representative organization
of the Palestinian people'' and should be represented at the
negotiating table.
   The developments were important to many Arab-Americans, who have
long looked to Jackson as their voice in the U.S. political world.
   Jackson's relationship with the Arabs goes back to 1979 when as
a private but well-known citizen he visited the Middle East on a
fact-finding tour and was photographed embracing Arafat.
   That picture still angers many American Jews. But the Arabs see
Jackson as a leader who is interested in the rights of their people
as well as the security of Israel.
   For many years Jackson has held that the U.S. policy against
negotiating with the PLO is counterproductive.
   His support for establishment of a Palestinian homeland also has
endeared him to the Arabs. But he also contends the Arab states and
Palestinians must recognize Israel's right to exist.
   During Jackson's 1984 presidential campaign, his Arab ties
created a stir when it was disclosed that his Chicago-based civil
rights organization had received $200,000 from the Arab League, a
group of Arab governments.
   The contributions to the education-oriented PUSH for Excellence
and the PUSH Foundation caused controversy, especially among Jewish
groups who contended Jackson was too dependent on Arab money.
   Zogby, head of the Arab-American Institute, said Arab-Americans,
who number an estimated 2 million throughout the country mostly
concentrated in about a dozen cities, had achieved finanical and
social security but felt excluded politically until Jackson's 1984
presidential race.
   ``Jackson brought them into the process and they don't forget
that.''
   He acknowledged Jackson's televised comments two weeks ago
caused, ``an initial round of concern.''
   But he said Arab support again was pouring in by the time the
New York campaign ended April 19, and New York Mayor Ed Koch had
savaged Jackson as being anti-Israeli.
   After the ``Face the Nation'' interview, some members of the
National Association of Arab-Americans raised questions, said Liela
Calnan, New England coordinator for the group.
   ``They didn't understand. I know a few Arabs in California that
thought the would be turning against them,'' she said.
   But she said they were willing to give Jackson another chance
because of his record. ``He defends Palestinians constantly... He
never fails, whether there's Arabs there or not, to mention
Palestinian self determination.''
   She said Arabs would be unlikely to support Dukakis ``because of
his wife'' who is Jewish.
   Jabara initially wrote a public letter to Jackson accusing him
of ``tailoring your positions'' to appease Jewish voters before the
New York primary.
   Jackson had said on ``Face the Nation'' that it ``would be a
mistake'' to try and sit Arafat at a negotiating table with Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir because that would be ``asking for a
bonafide explosion.''
   Asked if he himself would sit down with Arafat, he said, ``I
would not. And it's not necessary to do that. We must not equate
Arafat an the PLO with a sovereign people, the Palestinian people.''
</TEXT>
