<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     04-26 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Makes Election-Eve Appeal At Harrisburg Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BLOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Jesse
Jackson made an election-eve appeal for support in today's
Pennsylvania primary, telling a chanting crowd at a rally: ``This
room is full of hope today.''
   Jackson came to the state capital for a meeting with Gov. Robert
P. Casey and staged a rally that drew a crowd of 2,000.
   Jackson was holding meetings in Washington this morning with a
State Department official and members of Congress, and heading
later to Ohio, which holds its primary a week from today.
   At the Harrisburg rally, Jackson stressed the themes that have
been the cornerstone of his campaign: reversing Reagan
administration economic policies, fighting drug abuse, and bringing
more Americans into the political process.
   ``This room is full of hope today. A great dimension of our
campaign is to keep hope alive. Our mission is to keep America
strong and make America better,'' Jackson told the crowd.
   ``In this room today are farmers and workers; the black, the
white, the brown, the red, the yellow, the middle class, the lower
class .... We the people have come together to find common
ground,'' he said.
   Jackson's campaign stop in Harrisburg was one of several he made
across Pennsylvania Monday, the day before the state's 2.8 million
Democrats were going to the polls to voice their preference for the
party's presidential nominee.
   Jackson also made appearances in Pittsburgh and Philadelphia,
where much of his support is rooted.
   In Pittsburgh, Jackson was questioned repeatedly about a
statement he made Sunday regarding negotiation with terrorists.
   Jackson said Monday he could conceive of situations where he
would grant safe passage to hostage-takers, saying ``I choose
negotiation over blind bloody confrontation.'' He rejected what he
called ``material concessions'' to terrorists but did not rule out
political accommodation
   ``If we are going to deter terrorism, we must address the
underlying causes of terrorism,'' he said after an appearance at a
high school in Pittsburgh. ``Terrorism does not emerge out of the
blue.''
   Jackson said Sunday he disagreed with Dukakis' position that
``we should not negotiate with terrorists.'' Jackson said, ``I
disagree with that; if I could get the hostages out, I'd do it.''
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Monday the U.S.
government will ``talk to anyone, to any group, to any government
about the well-being and release of the Americans still held
hostage in Lebanon.''
   But she added, ``We will not make concessions to terrorists or
compromise our fundamental principles.''
   Jackson, who polls say is lagging behind Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis in today's contest, has been campaigning heavily in
urban areas in recent days.
   A poll released Monday by KYW-TV in Philadelphia and KDKA-TV in
Pittsburgh showed Dukakis led Jackson by 26 percentage points, with
57 percent for Dukakis, 31 percent for Jackson and 12 percent
undecided.
   Jackson arrived at the Harrisburg rally behind schedule. The
wait, however, did not dampen the spirits of those attending the
rally, and Jackson was greeted at the podium by thunderous applause
and shouts of encouragement.
   ``I seek to lead our nation beyond racism, beyond sexism, beyond
anti-Semitism, beyond escapism and beyond war. We must make America
better and keep America strong,'' Jackson said to cheers.
   He called for more spending to fight drug abuse.
   ``You just don't say no to a $150 billion-a-year industry,''
Jackson said, referring to First Lady Nancy Reagan's advice that
youngsters ``just say no'' to drugs.
   ``If you want to fight a war you've got to have a budget,'' he
said.
   Following his address, Jackson met briefly with Casey, also a
Democrat, who has not endorsed a presidential candidate.
   ``We're very impressed with the ideas he's expressed for
investing in America, infrastructure investment programs and the
war on drugs ....'' Casey said.
   Reginald Williams, a Hershey resident who attended the
Harrisburg rally, said he was impressed with Jackson's concern for
all residents.
   ``We have a chance to make history. Even if his nomination fails
on the convention floor, we have made history,'' he said.
</TEXT>
