<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Robertson-Libel     04-26 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robertson-Libel,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Ordered To Pay $28,000 In Court Costs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for both Pat Robertson and the former
congressman he sued for questioning his war record said they were
pleased by an order that the former television evangelist pay
$28,000 in court costs.
   Rep. Paul N. ``Pete'' McCloskey was sued in 1986 after he
claimed that Robertson had used the political influence of his late
father, Sen. A. Willis Robertson, D-Va., to avoid combat duty
during the Korean War.
   Robertson dropped the lawsuit last month rather than go to trial
on March 8, when he ran in Republican primaries on Super Tuesday.
Robertson officially remains a contender for the Republican
presidential nomination, although George Bush is expected to amass
sufficient delegates to clinch the nomination in today's
Pennsylvania primary.
   U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green dismissed the lawsuit on
the condition that Robertson pay McCloskey's court costs because
the former congressman is the prevailing party.
   McCloskey had sought $42,845 in court costs following the
dismissal last month of Robertson's $35 million libel action. But
the clerk of the U.S. District Court here rejected $14,845 of that
amount.
   ``We are pleased that even at the clerk level it was knocked
down substantially from $42,000 down to $28,000,'' said Joel E.
Leising, one of Robertson's attorneys.
   McCloskey's lawyer, George Lehner, said he was pleased with the
award.
   Robertson's lawyers, who had originally argued their client
should only be assessed $6,000, have five days to file further
objections with the judge.
   ``We will consider whether to seek a further reduction,''
Leising said, noting that ``at some point, the cost of legal fees
in seeking a reduction might outweigh what we would get.''
   The clerk disallowed more than $7,000 in fees for an expert
witness McCloskey had hired to rebut Robertson's claims that he
suffered economic hardship as a result of the statements, which
were contained in a letter to Rep. Andrew Jacobs, D-Ind.
   The letter was printed by several syndicated columnists,
prompting the libel suit.
</TEXT>
