<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Glance     04-26 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Glance,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korean National Assembly Election At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Korea, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief look at the parties and issues in today's
election:
   CANDIDATES: 1,045 for 224 seats in single-member districts.
Another 75 seats in the 299-member National Assembly will be
decided according to the parties' nationwide vote proportions.
Winners will serve four years.
   MAJOR PARTIES: President Roh Tae-woo's Democratic Justice Party;
the Reunification Democratic Party of Kim Young-sam; the Party for
Peace and Democracy, which split with Reunification to back rival
opposition leader Kim Dae-jung's bid for the presidency in last
December's elections; the New Democratic Republican Party of former
Prime Minister Kim Jong-pil.
   FORMER ASSEMBLY: Elected in February 1985, it had 276 seats,
with the Democratic Justice Party holding 160, the Reunification
Democratic Party 55, the Party for Peace and Democracy 24, and the
New Democratic Republican Party 8, with the rest held by
independents or splinter groups. Roh won a five-year term in the
December presidential election with 36 percent of the vote as the
opposition vote was mainly split between the two main opposition
parties.
   ISSUES: Roh's party says it must win to ensure stability for
continued progress in the economy and democratic reforms announced
by Roh last summer as the governing party chairman. It accuses the
opposition of fomenting unrest. The opposition says a governing
party victory will bring more of the authoritarian rule and
corruption experienced under the administration of former President
Chun Doo-hwan. Chun's younger brother has been arrested in an
embezzlement scandal.
   VOTERS: 26.2 million registered. Voting hours were 7 a.m. to 6
p.m. at 13,812 polling stations.
</TEXT>
