<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites SUB a0462 04-26 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites, SUB, a0462,0261</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf of 2nd item to CORRECT that girl sustained
minor injuries, sted was unhurt</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   DeAndra Anrig, the 8-year-old ``kite
crusader'' who soared for 100 feet at the end of a kite string last
month, still has her head in the clouds, her mother says.
   ``It's amazing. The (attention) still hasn't died down,'' said
Debbie Anrig. ``This child has just eaten it up.''
   On March 20, DeAndra was flying her 12-foot kite at Shoreline
Park in Mountain View when a plane landing at Palo Alto Airport
caught the kite's 200-pound test line and carried the child 10 feet
into the air. She flew for 100 feet, let go as she approached a
clump of trees and fell to the ground, sustaining minor injuries.
   Since then, talk shows keep discussing her adventure and stories
have appeared in newspapers nationwide.
   Fan mail also continues to pour in from all over the country.
DeAndra _ or Andi, as family and friends call her _ is so
well-known that some of it is delivered without an address.
   ``All it says is DeAndra Anrig, Dublin, Calif.,'' Mrs. Anrig
said. ``The postman knows who it is.'' Some letters, she says, are
addressed to ``The Kite Crusader'' and ``The Little Flying Girl.''
   The only bad thing is that Andi's 4-year-old brother, Dean,
feels a little left out, Mrs. Anrig said. But the Anrigs have
promised him a kite of his own.
   Andi herself plans to fly kites again, but not near airplanes.
</TEXT>
