<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0211EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Canada-Politics Bjt   04-26 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Politics, Bjt,0764</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Heads For Washington; Keeps Eye On Manitoba
Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Money figures are in U.S. dollars.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<HEAD>By JEFF BRADLEY</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Prime Minister Brian Mulroney visits
Washington for his summit with President Reagan, he'll be keeping
an eye on the results of a provincial election back home.
   Mulroney, who arrives in Washington tonight, is trying to decide
soon when to call a federal election. The choice of a new
government today in Manitoba, a blue-collar industrial province in
central Canada, may show the way.
   Manitoba has been controlled by the socialist New Democratic
Party for 15 of the past 19 years, but all polls indicate
Mulroney's Progressive Conservative Party will win the election,
after narrowly losing to the socialists in 1986.
   Mulroney has 16 months to go in his five-year term, but it is
traditional for Canadian leaders to set an early election date when
political omens are favorable. In a weekend interview, Mulroney
said he wanted to clear his government's legislative agenda before
calling a ballot.
   That agenda includes ratification of a comprehensive Free Trade
Agreement negotiated with the United States last year, passage of
the Meech Lake constitutional accord recognizing Quebec as a
French-speaking ``distinct society,'' a child day care program and
the privatization of Air Canada.
   The FreeTrade Agreement will be discussed at the Washington
summit. The U.S. Congress is expected vote on it this summer, while
the House of Commons will consider legislation on the agreement
next month.
   Recently, Mulroney has been making campaign-like stops around
the country to test the political waters.
   His 48-hour Washington visit includes a host of photo
opportunities including a 19-gun salute at the White House and
separate meetings with Reagan, Secretary of State George Shultz,
Vice President George Bush and leaders of both the House and Senate.
   On Wednesday afternoon, he is to address both houses of Congress.
   A former lawyer and corporate executive from Quebec, Mulroney,
49, has devoted much of his term to repairing Canada-U.S. relations
strained under former Liberal Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau.
   Despite Reagan's reluctance to clean up U.S. smokestack
emissions causing acid rain north of the border, he and Mulroney
agree on key trade and defense issues. According to White House
officials, Reagan spends more time talking with Mulroney on the
telephone than any other world leader.
   Domestically, Mulroney has had a stormy time in office in spite
of the 140-seat majority he won four years ago in the 282-member
House of Commons.
   He has lost eight Cabinet members in scandals ranging from a
defense minister who visited a German strip club to a transport
minister tried for fraud.
   Mulroney has shepherded Canada's economy to the fastest growth
among major industrialized countries, with 4 percent inflation and
unemployment at a 6{-year low of 7.8 percent. Now the Conservatives
are now neck-and-neck in the polls with the Liberals and New
Democrats.
   Mulroney nevertheless has a credibility problem and is liked by
only about one-third of the electorate, according to polls.
   In contrast, New Democratic Party leader Ed Broadbent gets high
marks as Canada's most admired politician. Mulroney dubs his
nemesis ``perfection personified.''
   ``I don't know if I'll ever close in on perfection,'' the prime
minister said. ``But I don't have to, to win an election.''
   He said when the time comes, voters will not take a chance by
electing what would be the country's first socialist government at
a federal level.
   Broadbent's vulnerable spot is his party's vow to pull Canada
out of the NATO alliance and to renegotiate the NORAD air defense
pact with the United States.
   Canada was a charter member of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization and has 6,900 troops stationed in West Germany.
Mulroney and Reagan agreed in 1986 to renew the North American
Aerospace Defense pact for five years, protecting the continent
against Soviet attack over the North Pole.
   The New Democrats would bring the troops home and cancel
Mulroney's $6.5 billion plan to acquire Canada's first fleet of
nuclear-powered submarines.
   Aware of the unpopularity of its NATO pledge, the New Democratic
Party softened its stance this month by promising not to start the
withdrawal in a first term.
   Mulroney ridiculed the change, saying Canadians would never
support ``a policy that says we're going to pull out of our most
sovereign undertaking with regard to national defense, but by the
way, we're not going to do it right now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
