<DOCNO> AP880426-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Cuba-Tourism Bjt   04-26 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-Tourism, Bjt,0783</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Looking To Foreigners To Boost Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TINA SUSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA, Cuba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the heat of the Havana day, La Bodeguita
del Medio resembles the steamy cantinas of Mexico, with a bit of
the Big Apple thrown in.
   Like New York's Cadillac Bar, the walls are covered with
graffiti left by visitors who pack the cramped restaurant tucked
along a side street of Old Havana. Like the cafes of Tijuana, a
sweating chef stirs metal tubs of pork and beans, swatting at an
occasional fly and wiping his brow with a dishcloth.
   But there's a difference. Here, above the din of clattering
plates and the strum of the strolling guitarist, you're as apt to
hear German, Italian, French and English being spoken as you are to
hear Spanish. It's a sound the government loves to hear.
   With its Caribbean climate and calm beaches, Cuba, is a natural
lure for tourists. Before the revolution, U.S. visitors plunked
down millions of dollars in the cabarets and casinos of Havana.
   The casinos are closed now and tourists from the United States
vanished when relations soured between the two countries. U.S.
tourists who spend money in Cuba are subject to prosecution under
the U.S. Trading with the Enemy Act.
   The communist island nation, largely dependent on Soviet aid and
sugar exports, is making an all-out effort to bring in money from
elsewhere.
   From the bustle of Havana to the serene beaches of Santiago de
Cuba, the government is putting up new hotels and renovating old
ones in hopes of making tourism its No. 2 earner of hard currency,
after sugar, by the year 2000.
   Numbers are hard to come by _ nobody at the National Tourism
Institute, Intur, would talk to an American reporter.
   But Intur's vice president, Orosman Quintero, recently told
Cuban reporters that in 1987, about 123,000 people from Canada,
Spain, Italy, West Germany and Mexico visited Cuba. That was an
increase of 15 percent over 1986.
   According to the magazine Bohemia, Intur figures from 1986
indicate that 155,795 tourists visited Cuba, bringing in about
$97.3 million.
   Before the revolution, tourism brought in about $400 million
annually.
   The Canadian tourism season runs from December through the end
of March. But a few could still be found lounging in the 85 degree
sun last week at Santa Maria del Mar, a seaside resort 20 miles
outside Havana.
   Adelaide and Tony Aloi of Toronto said they paid $1,000 each for
two weeks in Santa Maria, including breakfast and dinner in their
hotel and round-trip airfare. Like others interviewed, they praised
beaches, weather, Cuban hospitality and the feeling of security.
   ``Mexico's cheap, but you have to bargain your way through it,''
said Aloi. ``Here, there's nobody coming up to you on the street
trying to sell things or get money.''
   But they agreed with other tourists who complained about bad
hotel food, the poor quality of consumer goods and hotel service
that is not up to par with other vacation spots.
   At the high-rise Havana Libre in the capital, the plumbing was
iffy and there was rarely hot water. It wasn't unusual to wait 10
minutes for an elevator, and no one was there to offer assistance
when the small refrigerator in one reporter's room started burning
one night.
   ``I personally wouldn't come back because I like to shop, and
there's nothing much to buy,'' said Susan McNulty of Toronto,
interviewed at the Hotel Atlantico in Santa Maria. ``But this is
the place to come if you just want a nice, relaxing vacation.''
   Intur says it is trying to improve things for tourists by
renovating older hotels, such as the 30-year-old Havana Libre, and
putting up new ones in areas such as Santa Maria, Santiago and
Varadero, the island's most popular tourist spot.
   An airport is being built at Varadero so visitors won't have to
drive the two hours north from Havana's airport, and 10 more hotels
are scheduled for completion by 1990. In the capital, 11 hotels are
under some form of renovation, according to the Intur magazine Sol
de Cuba.
   The Sun Channel, the television station for tourists, offers
news, movies and a morning aerobics program in English and Spanish.
Last week's feature films included ``Love at First Bite,'' ``A Man
and a Woman,'' and ``Sahara.''
   Intur also is offering prizes to lure foreigners. Sol de Cuba
heralded the arrival of a Silvia Proehl, the 100,000th West German
to visit Cuba over the past four years. She won a free week in Cuba
next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
