<1ST_LINE>u p AM-UtahCaucuses 2ndLd-Writethru a0460 04-26 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Utah Caucuses, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0460,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to update with Dukakis victory on fresh
returns; picks up 7th graf pvs, While Democrats ...; Should stand
for AMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis won the Utah presidential
caucuses on Monday, overwhelming rival Jesse Jackson and capturing
most of the state's 23 delegates to the Democratic National
Convention.
   With 46 percent of the state's 75 legislative districts
reporting, Dukakis had 4,104 votes for 71 percent to Jackson's
1,080 or 19 percent, while 538 voters, or 9 percent, were
uncommitted.
   Based on these returns, Dukakis would win 18 national convention
delegates and Jackson would win five.
   The combined votes for Democrats Paul Simon, Richard Gephardt
and Albert Gore Jr. totaled 1 percent.
   The percentage of votes determines how many of the state's 23
delegates each candidate receives. The delegates will not be
elected until the state convention in June.
   Complete statewide returns were not expected until early Tuesday
from the balloting in separate caucus meetings held in nearly all
of the state's 1,807 voting districts.
   Although a victory here would reap only a handful of delegates,
Dukakis aides said it would give the Massachusetts governor
momentum heading into Tuesday's Pennsylvania primary.
   While Democrats declared their presidential preference,
Republicans were attending their own caucus meetings to vote their
preference for vice president and to say whether they want a
western states regional primary similar to the South's Super
Tuesday contests on March 8.
   Republicans had planned a non-binding presidential preference
vote, but scrapped the idea after Vice President George Bush
virtually wrapped up the nomination.
   Utah will send 28 delegates to the Democratic national
convention, including five ``super delegates'' chosen as a result
of present or past party office.
   Three of the superdelegates _ national committeewoman Norma
Matheson, Rep. Wayne Owens and state party chairman Randy Horiuchi
_ have endorsed Dukakis. The other two are uncommitted.
   Dukakis also has the endorsement of Matheson's husband, former
Democratic Gov. Scott Matheson.
   None of the candidates has visited Utah personally, but the
Dukakis campaign has maintained the strongest presence with a
full-time staff.
   Support for Jackson is more difficult to gauge. Two es here are picking
up momentum. Jackson will
pick up some delegates,'' Horiuchi predicted.
   Traditionally between 8 percent and 12 percent of registered
voters attend the Utah caucuses.
</TEXT>
