<DOCNO> AP880426-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0328EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APMeeting     04-26 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Meeting,0780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Holds Annual Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Associated Press will speed its DataStream
news delivery service to about 9,000 words a minute and increase
its domestic news staff to deal with what its president calls the
``the new world of news.''
   The increase to 9,000 words a minute begins in June, and the AP
also will offer new photo and graphic services, AP President Louis
D. Boccardi told publishers and newspaper editors Monday at the
annual AP meeting.
   The news cooperative also will add 10 to 15 domestic news
staffers in 1988 to better serve the AP's 1,423 newspaper members,
he said.
   ``The bulk of these will go to our line bureaus, whose state and
regional news coverage is so important to you,'' he told the
members. ``With membership increasing as it has, the demands on our
state bureaus are increasing. And we must meet those needs.''
   The worldwide news cooperative is about to move from a speed of
about 1,050 words a minute to about 9,000 on its DataStream and
DataFeature wires. DataStream is the AP high-speed news wire.
DataFeature is a separate service that delivers supplemental and
syndicate copy to member newspapers throughout the system.
   For newspapers with systems that need slower speeds, the
delivery can be reduced, but the higher capacity will avoid
crowding that can slow the delivery of copy, much like traffic
clogs a highway.
   ``We are raising the speed limit from 55 miles per hour to 440
miles per hour, and, if that weren't enough, we're widening the AP
interstate from four lanes to eight,'' Boccardi said.
   A new AP electronic darkroom for large newspapers already is
serving three members. In June the AP will unveil a PC-based
electronic darkroom designed for smaller newspapers, Boccardi said.
   After the meeting, the AP held its annual luncheon with Texas
billionaire H. Ross Perot as the keynote speaker. Perot, 57, is the
founder of Electronic Data Systems and financed the rescue of two
of his employees who were held hostage in Iran in 1978.
   The luncheon was held on the first day of the three-day 102nd
Annual Convention of the American Newspaper Publishers Association.
   The financier and philanthropist told the more than 1,500 people
at the luncheon that business leaders, not politicians, hold much
of the blame for the United States' declining status in the world.
   Since the U.S. economy depends on tax-paying workers, business
leaders should work harder to create more jobs, Perot said.
   Perot said other countries, especially in the Asia-Pacific
region, are outpacing the United States in education, trade and
technology.
   He said that before the federal government can cure the huge
budget deficit, individual Americans must learn not to spend more
than they earn.
   ``The greatest nation in the history of civilization has given
up trying to live within its means,'' he said. ``We and not the
elected officials are the dwarfs and the wimps.''
   Before the luncheon, five AP correspondents shared their
experiences in a panel discussion called ``The World's Hotspots: A
Firsthand View.''
   Also at the meeting, Donald E. Newhouse of The (Newark, N.J.)
Star-Ledger, and Katherine W. Fanning of The Christian Science
Monitor were elected to the board of directors of The Associated
Press, and four incumbent directors were re-elected.
   James H. Ottaway Jr. of The Times Herald-Record of Middletown,
N.Y.; Robert C. Maynard of The Tribune of Oakland, Calif.; James E.
Burgess of the Wisconsin State Journal in Madison; and Edwin L.
Heminger of The Courier in Findlay, Ohio, were elected to new
three-year terms on the board.
   Directors were elected from among 12 nominees at the AP annual
meeting.
   Newhouse and Ms. Fanning were chosen to succeed retiring
directors John F. McGee of the Charleston (W. Va.) Daily Mail and
Robert G. Marbut of the Corpus Christi (Texas) Caller-Times, who
had served the maximum of three three-year terms on the board.
   Newhouse is president of The Star-Ledger, and of Advance
Publications Inc. and Newhouse Broadcasting Co. He is a director of
the American Newspaper Publishers Association.
   Ms. Fanning is editor of the Monitor, published in Boston, and
is immediate past president of the American Society of Newspaper
Editors.
   The voting for directors was based on membership bonds held by
the newspapers that make up the cooperative news agency.
   Heminger was re-elected to the board to represent a city of
under 50,000 population.
   AP bylaws require that there be at least three directors
representing newspapers published in cities of less than 50,000
population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
