<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSChild Bjt   04-26 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Child, Bjt,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>5-Year-Old AIDS' Victim Tells Classmates Of His `Bad Blood'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DX1</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Shiela is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-year-old boy has realized his dream
of attending school before he dies of AIDS. He began his first day
of preschool by telling his classmates about his fatal disease and
his ``bad blood.''
   The boy, whose breathing is aided by an oxygen tank, surprised
his mother by volunteering the information as his seven classmates
introduced themselves, his mother said Monday.
   ``He said `This is my oxygen, and I have a disease. My bad blood
could kill you,''' said the mother, Shiela, who took her son
Jonathan on Monday to the special education class at Patterson
Elementary School.
   ``He didn't wait for anything. And the kids responded really
well,'' the mother said at a news conference outside her
condominium in this Denver suburb.
   ``He broke the ice right off and from then on it was just normal
kid stuff,'' said Shiela, a divorced mother of three other sons.
   She has asked that her last name not be published because she
fears retaliation against her family.
   ``They listened and they played with me,'' Jonathan said of the
hour he spent in the classroom. Asked whether his first day was as
much fun as he expected, he replied, ``Yeah.''
   Shiela said her son's biggest dream has been to attend school
before he dies.
   ``He used to talk about dying all the time and he said he wanted
to die,'' she said as Jonathan watched ants inching along the
sidewalk. ``But he hasn't addressed it since he found out he would
get to go to school. He hasn't mentioned it in the last couple of
weeks.''
   As his mother talked with reporters, Jonathan showed off a
Polaroid picture of himself at school. At one point, he walked away
to play on the sidewalk, unhooking the tube that connected him with
the oxygen tank.
   Jonathan's hopes of going to school were blocked several times
in the past year by one delay after another. Earlier this month, a
tutor assigned by the school district to teach him at home demanded
to be reassigned, threatening to file a lawsuit if forced to
continue the tutoring. The request was granted.
   School officials decided April 19 to allow Jonathan to attend
class.
   Jonathan is Colorado's first recorded child victim of the fatal
disease, said his mother. The youngster contracted AIDS from
tainted blood he received in a transfusion shortly after birth and
was diagnosed in June 1985.
   ``One thing that sticks in my mind, he used to say `Jesus
doesn't listen to me. ... I told Him to come and get me, and He
didn't.' It really rips your heart out, but I think in a way he's
comforting me by telling me it's all right with him. He was
diagnosed three years ago, and it's just a matter of time.''
   Pam Mills, executive director of exceptional students' services
for Jefferson County Schools, also attended the news conference and
said she was unaware of any parents who had kept their children at
home because of Jonathan. There were no protesters or parents
outside the school Monday.
   Mills said parents of the other students had prepared their
children.
   ``We have met with the parents a couple of times,'' she said.
``It's basically a health and hygiene type of issue with them.''
   Jonathan eventually will attend class 10 hours a week and his
progress will be evaluated in May and in August.
   Shiela also plans to enroll Jonathan in summer classes. ``He has
such a limited time in school.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APMeeting-Hotspots     04-26 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Meeting-Hotspots,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AP Correspondents Discuss Covering the World's `Hotspots'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON STATON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   News coverage of the Soviet Union is more
difficult now because there is more activity and thus more news to
report, according to Michael Putzel, The Associated Press bureau
chief in Moscow.
   ``Now we cover dissident news conferences, official news
conferences, and demonstrations,'' he said. ``We are getting a lot
more information.
   ``For Soviet reporters, it's a whole new ballgame,'' Putzel
said. ``They now have to firgure out what's expected of them and
how far they can and want to go.''
   Putzel and four other AP correspondents and news executives
discussed reporting conditions and press freedoms, among other
topics, during a conversation with AP President Louis D. Boccardi
at The Associated Press annual meeting here Monday.
   The press is one of the most distinct areas of liberalization in
South Korea, said Barry Renfrew, AP chief of bureau in Seoul.
   ``The press is able to moderately criticize the government
now,'' he said.
   ``There has been a change from direct intimidation to more
subtle influence,'' he said.
   ``Current riots in the West Bank and Gaza Strip have posed
difficult problems for the Israeli government, which is a democracy
and prides itself on being one,'' said Nick Tatro, the wire
service's bureau chief in Jerusalem.
   The government has not used military censorship but has tried to
close off stories by putting curfews on towns or declaring military
areas closed, he said.
   Bryna Brennan, Central America correspondent for the AP, noted
the reopening of La Prensa, a newspaper in Managua, Nicaragua, last
fall.
   ``La Prensa has published consistently since October except for
a brief week at Easter when they ran out of newsprint,'' she said.
   ``It is a very strong opposition newspaper.''
   Terence Hunt, the AP's chief White House correspondent, said he
has the same difficulties in getting access to people he needs to
talk with as the foreign correspondents do.
   ``We only have access to our own booth and to (White House Press
Secretary) Marlin Fitzwater's office, where the door is usually
closed,'' Hunt said.
   ``We can't get to the oval office, or (White House Chief of
Staff) Howard Baker's office or the senior staff without an
appointment,'' he said.
   ``It's almost impossible on a spot story to get a call through
for comment,'' he said. ``We have better luck talking to people on
Capitol Hill because (the) White House staff briefs congressional
leaders on major issues.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AP-Directors     04-26 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP-Directors,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0476, deleting extraneous matter from heading.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Elects Directors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald E. Newhouse of The Star-Ledger of Newark,
N.J., and Katherine W. Fanning of The Christian Science Monitor
were elected to the board of directors of The Associated Press, and
four incumbent directors were re-elected.
   James H. Ottaway Jr. of The Times Herald-Record of Middletown,
N.Y.; Robert C. Maynard of The Tribune of Oakland, Calif.; James E.
Burgess of the Wisconsin State Journal in Madison; and Edwin L.
Heminger of The Courier in Findlay, Ohio, were elected to new
three-year terms on the board.
   Directors were elected Monday from among 12 nominees at the AP
annual meeting.
   Newhouse and Ms. Fanning were chosen to succeed retiring
directors John F. McGee of the Charleston (W. Va.) Daily Mail and
Robert G. Marbut of the Corpus Christi (Texas) Caller-Times, who
had served the maximum of three three-year terms on the board.
   Newhouse is president of The Star-Ledger, and of Advance
Publications Inc. and Newhouse Broadcasting Co. He is a director of
the American Newspaper Publishers Association.
   Ms. Fanning is editor of the Monitor, published in Boston, and
is immediate past president of the American Society of Newspaper
Editors.
   The voting for directors was based on membership bonds held by
the newspapers that make up the cooperative news agency.
   The results:
   Ottaway, 16,813 bond votes.
   Newhouse 16,674.
   Maynard 13,647.
   Burgess 12,988.
   Ms. Fanning 11,531.
   William M. Boyd, The Central New Jersey Home News, of New
Brunswick, 7,787.
   Ted M. Natt, The Daily News, Longview, Wash., 6,046.
   F. Al Totter, San Gabriel Valley Tribune, West Covina, Calif.,
5,836.
   Stanley H. Stauffer, Topeka (Kan.) Capital-Journal, 5,745.
   Paul J. O'Brien, The Salt Lake Tribune, Salt Lake City, Utah,
2,235.
   Heminger was re-elected to the board to represent a city of
under 50,000 population. In that separate contest, he received
16,682 votes. John Grey Montgomery of The Daily Union in Junction
City, Kan., had 4,538.
   AP bylaws require that there be at least three directors
representing newspapers published in cities of less than 50,000
population.
</TEXT>
