<DOCNO> AP880426-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0426EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     04-26 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0753</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Issue Surfaces During Discussion On U.S. Bases In Philippines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Filipino negotiators today
discussed AIDS and procedures for trying American troops in
criminal cases.
   The discussion occurred during talks on U.S. military bases
which sources described as difficult and emotional. The Senate is
debating a bill to ban nuclear weapons in the Philippines and to
prohibit nuclear-capable military ships from making port calls. The
measure is directed at U.S. military bases.
   In another development, at least seven people were killed today
on Mactan island during a gun battle between government troops and
Scout Rangers who deserted their unit. Three of the dead were Scout
Rangers and four were government soldiers, officials said. Radio
stations said a civilian also died.
   Also today, officials said communist rebels were suspected in
the killings of a police captain and an anti-communist vigilante in
two separate attacks near the U.S.-run Clark Air Base.
   After their discussion today, the U.S. and Filipino negotiators
released a joint statement saying they had discussed ``the criminal
jurisdiction issue'' and that the Philippine side presented its
proposal on purchases of locally manufactured products ``and
socio-economic issues.''
   There was no elaboration, but sources familiar with the talks
said the ``socio-economic issues'' referred to allegations that
U.S. troops had brought the deadly AIDS virus into the country.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the talks
were ``difficult'' and ``emotional.''
   At least 50 Filipino prostitutes have been found carrying the
AIDS virus but none has developed symptoms of the disease, which is
transmitted primarily through sexual intercourse or contaminated
needles and blood products.
   Most of those found with the virus work in bars near the
U.S.-run Clark Air Base and the Subic Bay naval base. U.S.
authorities have promised not to transfer troops carrying the virus
to the Philippines.
   Filipino officials have suggested that the United States finance
health and rehabilitation programs for AIDS-infected prostitutes
working near the bases.
   The current bases agreement exempts American servicemen from
trial by Filipino courts if they allegedly commit crimes while on
duty. Sources said Filipino negotiators believe American commanders
issue duty certificates to their troops too freely in a bid to
exempt them from trial by local courts.
   On April 5, the two sides began a periodic review of the 1947
agreement under which the United States maintains six military
bases in the Philippines.
   The outcome is expected to influence Manila's decision whether
to allow the bases to remain after their lease expires in 1991. But
the talks are taking place amid growing calls for closing the
bases, which many Filipinos see as a vestige of U.S. colonial rule.
President Corazon Aquino has promised to honor the agreement but
refuses to say whether she will support an extension.
   Under the new Filipino constitution, any extension must be
approved by two-thirds of the 23-member Senate, where opposition to
the bases is strong.
   On Monday, the Senate began debate on a bill to ban nuclear
weapons and nuclear-powered ships from the Philippines. U.S.
officials say about 40 percent of the warships that call at Subic
Bay are nuclear powered.
   The bill's sponsors say it is directed at the American bases.
U.S. officials refuse to say whether nuclear weapons are stored in
the Phillipines.
   Officials said the battle between government troops and Scout
Rangers began when the rangers attacked a checkpoint set up to
prevent them from moving from their hideout.
   About 30 members of the army's elite Scout Rangers deserted in
1986 and moved to Mactan, a small island where Cebu City's
international airport is located. The renegade rangers, who the
military claims have been involved in smuggling, formed a religious
cult that forbids bathing and cutting hair.
   In the Clark Air Base incidents, police said two men armed with
.45-caliber pistols shot and killed Capt. Francisco Medina, 41,
deputy police commander of Mabalacat, as he drove late Monday near
the base.
   Hours later, a lone gunman killed Francisco Sabile, 48, while he
played cards with friends in Angeles City. Sabile was a member of
the Angelino Simbulan Brigade, an anti-communist vigilante group.
   Clark Air Base, a sprawling military facility 50 miles north of
Manila, straddles the towns of Mabalacat and Angeles City. In
October rebels killed three Americans and a Filipino of U.S.
extraction in attacks outside the base.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
