<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0426EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Saudi-Nuclear     04-26 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Saudi-Nuclear,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudi Arabia To Sign Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Fahd of Saudi Arabia today decided
to sign an international treaty limiting the spread of nuclear
arms, apparently responding to Israeli fears that the kingdom might
arm its missiles with nuclear warheads.
   Information Minister Ali al-Shaer said the decision was made
during a Cabinet meeting in the Saudi capital of Riyahd where other
issues also were discussed, the official Saudi Press Agency
reported.
   It appeared the announcement was designed primarily to reassure
the United States that Saudi Arabia will not try to put nuclear
warheads on CSS-2 intermediate-range missiles the kingdom acquired
from China.
   King Fahd wrote President Reagan recently reportedly assuring
him that the warheads on the surface-to-surface missiles are not
nuclear.
   Israel has alleged that the missiles constitute a threat to its
safety and indicated it might deal a preemptive strike to destroy
them.
   The news agency, monitored in Bahrain, said Prince Saud Faisal,
the Saudi foreign minister, recommended that the kingdom join the
International Nuclear Weapons Non-proliferation Treaty.
   Saudi Arabia, the world's largest exporter of crude oil, was
reported to have obtained from Beijing an undisclosed number of
CSS-2 missiles capable of reaching virtually any point in the
Middle East, including Israel.
   Western diplomatic sources have said that China, which arms its
own CSS-2s with atomic warheads, has told Washington it will not
export nuclear arms.
   The sources said the Saudis refused a request by the United
States to inspect the missiles, which they said were deployed in
the Rub al-Khali desert south of Riyadh.
   Saudi sources said Prince Sultan, the defense minister,
approached Beijing for the CSS-2s mainly because of U.S.
congressional obstruction of Reagan's approval of the sale of
certain types of weapons to the kingdom. They complained that
Congress has been bending to powerful Israeli lobbying against U.S.
arms sale to Saudi Arabia.
   The Saudis feel threatened by Iran, which in 1984 began using
intermediate-range missiles against its Persian Gulf war foe, Iraq.
   Saudi-Iranian relations hit their lowest point in July, when
hundreds of Iranian pilgrims tried to defy a ban on political
rallies and were killed in clashes with Saudi riot police in Mecca
during the annual pilgrimage season.
   Gulf-based Arab diplomatic sources have said the Saudis want the
CSS-2s as a potential deterrent to Iran, whose leadership has urged
the overthrow of the Saudi royal family.
   The United States, the Soviet Union and Britain were the major
signers when the nuclear non-proliferation treaty was adopted in
1968. In subsequent years the treaty was signed by scores of other
nations.
   The treaty is aimed at restricting the spread of military
nuclear technology. It calls for nuclear powers to abstain from
assisting non-nuclear nations in obtaining or making nuclear
weapons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0059 </DOCNO>
