<HEAD>Networks Plan Slim Prime-Time Coverage for Primary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The major networks planned only brief
interruptions during prime time to cover today's Pennsylvania
primary.
   Only CBS planned a special report, for a half-hour at 11:30 p.m.
EDT.
   ABC said it would update as needed and have an expanded
newsbrief at 9:57 p.m. NBC planned to interrupt at 9 p.m. and 9:55
p.m., and CBS said it would do so at 8 p.m.
   CNN planned to update all evening but had no plans for extended
coverage.
   ABC's ``Nightline'' normally covers primary results at 11:30
p.m., but the program is being broadcast live from Israel this week.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Wright: Jackson Has `Earned Right' to Vice Presidential
Consideration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker James Wright thinks Jesse
Jackson has ``earned the right'' to be considered as a vice
presidential candidate should he lose the presidential nomination
to Michael Dukakis.
   The Texas Democrat, on the Kansas State University campus to
deliver an Alf Landon Lecture, said at a news conference Monday he
remains neutral in the race for the party's presidential nomination.
   But he said Jackson has demonstrated his ``very broad appeal''
with voters and has matured since he tried for the Democratic
presidential nomination in 1984.
   ``I just think he's earned a right to be considered for some of
our highest offices,'' Wright said.
   He declined to predict the outcome of the Dukakis-Jackson race,
but said the Democrats probably won't have a brokered convention
when they meet this July in Atlanta.
   ``I think somebody will get a majority on the first ballot,''
Wright said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Kostmayer Endorses Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANGHORNE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Peter Kostmayer, D-Pa., endorsed
Michael Dukakis' bid for the Democratic presidential nomination on
the eve of Pennsylvania's primary.
   ``I believe Mike Dukakis has a proven record of creating jobs
and revitalizing an economy,'' Kostmayer said.
   ``Pete and I share a deep commitment toward working for peace in
Central America and a deep concern for protecting our park and
wilderness regions that are our country's national treasures,''
Dukakis said.
