<DOCNO> AP880426-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0447EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     04-26 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stock Market Closes At Record High; Dollar Falls Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo stock market had a record high closing
today for the third consecutive day, while the U.S. dollar inched
down against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, the market's main index,
reached the all time high of 27,339.14 points immediately after
Tuesday's opening at 27,323.54. Then profit-taking thwarted the
early morning rally causing share prices dip at the close of the
morning session.
   Bullish sentiment in the market, however, drove the shares back
up to the day's opening level immediately after the start of the
afternoon session, and the market closed the day's trading at
27,246.77, or 33.32 points higher than Monday's close, another
record high.
   ``It was a typical first-day-of-the-month pattern,'' said a
trader for a Japanese securities firm, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   ``Major securities firms customerily push their sales on the
first day of the month,'' he added. ``So share prices usually jump
up in early morning and then profit-taking usually press it down a
bit.''
   Shares traded Tuesday will go into the May account.
   The trader added that the general trend is still upward, but
investors took ``wait-and-see attitude'' Tuesday ahead of the
release of gross national product figures in the United States for
the first quarter of 1988. This made the recovery of share prices
slower than usual.
   The American gross national product figures will be announced
today in Washington.
   Volume traded in the first section today was estimated at 1
billion shares.
   Meanwhile, the dollar opened at 124.65 yen in Tokyo and closed
at 124.57 yen, down 0.35 yen from Monday's close. It traded in a
narrow range of 124.55 yen to 124.70 yen throughout the day.
   ``The dollar sold in the 125's Monday, so it went back to a
comfortable level at around 124.60 yen. Now, it can not seem to be
able to go anywhere from there unless some influencing factors
emerge,'' said Hiroaki Shukuzawa of Sumitomo Bank. ``At this point,
124.55 - 124.70 yen seems to be the neutral range.''
   Shukuzawa, a currency dealer at one of the largest bank in
Japan, added that he expects no major effects from the U.S. gross
national product figures on exchange rates in Japan.
   ``GNP is not like a trade figure that has immediate effects on
exchange rates,'' he said. ``Its effects show up in a much longer
term.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
