<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CyanideDeaths     04-26 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyanide Deaths,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendant's Daughter Says Mother Discussed Killing Cyanide Victim</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Trial resumes at 12:30 p.m. EDT; lead prospects unlikely.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman accused of killing her husband and
another person discussed killing him with drug overdoses months
before he died from cyanide-tainted aspirin, her daughter testified
at the product-tampering trial.
   Cindy Hamilton, 28, told a federal court jury Monday that a
``discontented'' Stella Nickell briefly mentioned divorcing Bruce
Nickell but ``she said she was not going to lose half of everything
she had fought so hard to get.
   ``Based on what my mother had told me prior to my dad's death, I
believed that she did it,'' Ms. Hamilton said in a packed U.S.
District Court courtroom.
   Her testimony was to continue today in the trial, now in its
second week.
   On Monday, Ms. Hamilton said her mother had questioned her about
such drugs as heroin, cocaine and amphetamines; where they could be
obtained and how much would cause an overdose.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Joanne Maida asked Ms. Hamilton whether
her mother ever discussed specific people in the conversations.
   ``My dad, Bruce Nickell,'' she replied, referring to her
stepfather.
   Prosecutors say Mrs. Nickell, the first person in the United
States to be tried on charges of causing death by tampering with
over-the-counter capsules, plotted to kill Nickell to collect
insurance.
   But prosecutors said the plot unraveled when Ms. Hamilton
challenged her mother's attempt to make his June 1986 death and
that of Susan Katherine Snow a few weeks later look like random
murders. Prosecutors have suggested there were no links between the
victims other than the way they died.
   Government investigators also found Mrs. Nickell's fingerprints
in library books about poisons and that at least one insurance
policy had been forged, prosecutors say.
   ``She was very discontent with him,'' Ms. Hamilton said. ``She
was grateful he stopped drinking ... but she was discontent they
never did anything.'' Nickell was a reformed alcoholic, she said.
   Ms. Hamilton spoke softly but occasionally was choked by tears.
She never looked at her mother; Mrs. Nickell rarely took her eyes
from her daughter.
   When Mrs. Nickell told her daughter in June 1986 that Nickell
was dead, ``She looked at me and said, `I know what you are
thinking and the answer's no,''' Ms. Hamilton testified.
   Ms. Hamilton failed to reveal her suspicions to FBI agents in
interviews shortly after the deaths, saying she was ``scared for
her and I guess to protect her.''
   Ms. Hamilton finally went to officials in January 1987.
   Mrs. Nickell is charged in the deaths of Nickell, 52, and of Ms.
Snow, 40, who died after ingesting poisoned capsules of
Extra-Strength Excedrin.
   Mrs. Nickell also faces three counts of tampering with a product
involved in interstate commerce in the tainting of capsules in two
Extra-Strength Excedrin bottles and an Anacin-3 bottle recovered
from stores in two Seattle suburbs.
   The defense earlier challenged Ms. Hamilton's credibility,
saying she had a history of drug abuse and was motivated to contact
the FBI by a $300,000 reward established by a pharmaceutical group.
   A niece, Wilma Stewart, testified earlier Monday that Mrs.
Nickell ``seemed irked at everything'' a month before the cyanide
deaths but never mentioned harming her husband.
   Asked whether Mrs. Nickell had indicated an intent to kill, Ms.
Stewart replied, ``Absolutely not. Not ever.''
   Prosecutors say the Nickells' marriage was unhappy, and that
Mrs. Nickell was determined not to lose her trailer home in a
divorce. Witnesses have testified that the Nickells were several
thousand dollars in debt when Nickell died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
