<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0534EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Voters     04-26 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Voters,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voters Express Disappointment Over `Corrupt' Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Korea, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Koreans expressed hope that
today's legislative elections would help promote democracy, but
many also said violent protests could result if widespread vote
fraud occurs.
   ``A lot of problems have surfaced but from a long-term point of
view, I think the elections would be a step forward toward
democracy,'' Kim Soon-im, 43, a housewife in Seoul, said.
   Many voters interviewed shared that view but expressed concern
that ``widespread corruption'' would heighten political instability
before the Olympic Games, opening Sept. 17 in Seoul.
   ``I am afraid the elections would cause new problems rather than
solve them,'' Kang Han-ik, 21, a college student, said. Kang and
many others predicted a flood of lawsuits disputing results of this
election, which follows the first direct presidential election in
16 years.
   In the presidential voting in December, Roh Tae-woo of the
governing Democratic Justice Party won with 36 percent of the vote.
But opposition charges of rigging in that election won little
support from the public, irritated by the opposition's inability to
unite.
   Violence, corrupt campaigning and the alleged use of government
influence to help governing party candidates became issues again in
this campaign.
   Since the official 18-day campaign began, no day passed without
reports of scuffles among rival party supporters, firebomb attacks
on candidates or party offices and other violence. Scores were
injured, although exact figures were not available, and 150 people
were reported detained by police.
   Many people interviewed said they were most concerned by reports
of widespread efforts to buy votes with meals, gifts and cash. The
governing Democratic Justice Party announced it was expelling one
candidate after authorities reported finding thousands of
envelopes, each stuffed with the equivalent of $30 in cash, ready
for mailing at a post office.
   ``I did not receive cash but got a case of soap,'' Lee
Chung-kil, 34, a taxidriver said. ``People say that only fools
would not get gifts. In that sense, I am not a fool.''
   A housewife in a relatively wealthy residential area in Seoul
said it was difficult to reject offers of free lunches or dinners,
made through personal friends associated with certain candidates.
   ``I had received at least 10 offers of free sumptuous meals. I
have a guilty feeling for not voting for any of the candidates who
provided the meals,'' she said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
