<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Contras-Meeting     04-26 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contras-Meeting,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Threaten Talks Cutoff if Aid Not Delivered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leaders met secretly with a top Sandinista
official to plan this week's round of peace talks in Nicaragua, but
one rebel threatened to scrap the talks unless U.S. aid is allowed
to reach the guerrillas.
   Contra leader Adolfo Calero said Monday the truce arrangement
reached last month in Sapoa, Nicaragua, would be in danger if the
leftist Sandinista government continued to block food and medical
supplies to rebel troops inside the Central American country.
   The question of humanitarian aid to the troops will have to be a
top issue at high-level talks planned Thursday in Managua, Calero
said.
   ``We must reach an agreement on that,'' he said. ``If that is
not done, the whole Sapoa agreement will collapse.''
   Sandinista Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Tinoco met with a
Contra official to set ``the agenda and arrangments'' for the
talks, Calero confirmed Monday.
   Tinoco previously accused the Contras of engaging in political
maneuvering to avoid a definitive cease-fire while they freely
receive U.S. humanitarian aid.
   The Contras have three private U.S. companies available to rush
the supplies to Nicaragua as soon as the Sandinistas agree, Calero
said. Some of the aid approved by Congress already was on its way
to refugee camps on the Honduran-Nicaraguan border, he added.
   The plight of the troops has been a contributing cause to a
reported rift among the Contra leaders, but Calero minimized the
differences among the five directors of the Nicaraguan Resistance,
insisting they were united.
</TEXT>
