<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AntiUgly     04-26 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Anti Ugly,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Council Eases Anti-Ugly Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council has eased its
``anti-ugly'' law _ an ordinance aimed at eliminating suburban
eyesores _ and will allow residents to air their dirty laundry in
public, provided it's not in the front yard.
   The council on Monday scrapped some provisions of the new law
and changed others, bowing to citizen complaints about the
ordinance.
   Among other things, it altered the law to make it enforceable
upon citizen complaint and not merely at the whim of someone in
City Hall.
   Laundry still can't be aired in the front yard, but is
permissible in side yards and on porches and balconies.
   The council in this San Francisco Bay area community also
eliminated its ban on garbage cans in side yards.
   The revised law contains most of its original provisions
intended to rid neighborhoods of discarded furniture, automobile
bodies and other unsightly junk. It bans graffiti, dirt piles,
overgrown vegetation or other debris on residential and
non-residential property, if such messes can be seen from the
street.
   Violators face fines up to $500, and those convicted of breaking
the law more than three times within a year could face both a fine
and a jail sentence.
</TEXT>
