<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0517 04-26 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0517,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Moves Into Upper Midwest After Blanketing South Dakota</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf pvs, `Temperatures around ...,' to CORRECT to
``EDT'' sted ``CDT.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A spring snowstorm whitened parts of South Dakota, Nebraska and
Minnesota today, as severe thunderstorms swept through sections of
the South, unleashing at least two tornadoes in Georgia.
   The heaviest snowfall was reported in the Black Hills of South
Dakota. As of late Monday, 7-8 inches blanketed Deerfield.
   Early this morning, Rapid City, S.D., was covered by 4 inches of
snow. Brisk northerly winds produced a wind chill of between zero
and 15 degrees above zero in western South Dakota.
   In Wyoming, wind gusted to 60 mph at Cheyenne, and 3-6 inches of
snow fell in the northeast part of the state. Three inches fell on
Valentine, Neb.
   A winter storm watch was in effect for southwest Minnesota
today, where several inches of snow was expected.
   Ahead of the snow, showers and thunderstorms extended from
eastern and central Nebraska to western Kansas early today.
   A severe thunderstorm struck Pleasanton, Neb., late Monday and
produced golfball-size hail.
   Severe thunderstorms also developed over Georgia and Alabama on
Monday evening, producing high winds, twisters and large hail. A
number of downed trees blocked streets in Columbus, Ga.
   The Lowndes County, Ga., communities of Naylor and Bemiss caught
the worst of the winds.
   ``I laid the baby on the floor and got over him and prayed for
God to save him even if he didn't save me,'' said Ilia Morgan, 61.
   She and her husband, Jack, lost their roof, porch, pump house
and garden, but no one was injured.
   The Naylor Volunteer Fire Department was heavily damaged, with
fire trucks holding up what was left of the station. Near Bemiss,
an unoccupied mobile home was blown off its moorings and dropped on
an empty truck 10 yards away, authorities said.
   Clear skies prevailed this morning from the lower Mississippi
Valley across much of Texas to the desert Southwest. It also was
clear from New England to Pennsylvania and over the West Coast.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
southern Virginia across the Carolinas and Georgia to Florida, and
in southeast Iowa, Illinois, Missouri and eastern Kansas; rain or
snow from Wisconsin across Minnesota and northwest Iowa to South
Dakota and Nebraska; and scattered showers over Vermont and
northeastern New York.
   Highs will be in the 40s or 50s over New England and
northeastern New York, and from the upper Great Lakes across the
upper Mississippi Valley, the northern and central Plains and the
northern and central Rockies to eastern Washington; and the 80s and
lower 90s in Florida, the Gulf Coast region, and much of Texas and
the desert Southwest. Elsewhere, highs will be in the 60s or 70s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 3 above
zero at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 80 at Key West Naval Air
Station, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 55 foggy; Boston 46 fair; Buffalo 38 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 59 rain; Cincinnati 42 partly cloudy; Cleveland 42
fair; Detroit 44 fair; Miami 77 partly cloudy; New York 47 fair;
Philadelphia 44 fair; Pittsburgh 42 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine
39 fair; Washington 50 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 41 showers; Chicago 52 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 58 fair; Denver 40 windy; Des Moines 52 cloudy;
Indianapolis 47 fair; Kansas City 51 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 38
fair; Nashville 47 fair; New Orleans 71 foggy; St. Louis 54 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 58 fair; Anchorage 42 cloudy; Las Vegas 65
fair; Los Angeles 58 fair; Phoenix 73 fair; Salt Lake City 35 fair;
San Diego 60 cloudy; San Francisco 54 partly cloudy; Seattle 44
fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 39 fair; Toronto 45 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
