<1ST_LINE>d a PM-Parrot     04-26 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Parrot,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Offers Student Replacement Parrot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A university student whose African gray
parrot died after warning him of a kitchen fire will get another
bird, courtesy of a sympathetic couple that breeds parrots as a
hobby.
   ``I feel sorry for the guy,'' said Patti Martinson of Arvada
who, with her husband, Glenn, agreed to replace the parrot. ``I
know how it feels to lose a pet.''
   Chris Barnes' 7-year-old parrot, Coco, died Saturday morning
from fumes from a burning Teflon-coated pot.
   Barnes' roommate had fallen asleep after leaving a pot of
boiling water on the stove. When the water evaporated, the Teflon
coating began to burn.
   Barnes was asleep when Coco called out his name and awakened him.
   Barnes, a student at the University of Colorado, doused the
flame and aired out the room, but Coco died minutes later from
respiratory arrest, a veterinarian said.
   After reading of Barnes' misfortune, the Martinsons offered him
one of their 22 baby African parrots.
   ``That's the best news I've had in a long time,'' Barnes said.
   The parrots live 70 to 80 years, Martinson said.
</TEXT>
