<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ElbeGathering     04-26 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Elbe Gathering,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>After Wreath Laying, Soviets Greeted With Music And Cheering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strains of bluegrass music and
cheerleaders' chants of ``go Soviets, go'' filled the air as a
Soviet delegation and 150 Americans commemorated the linkup of
Soviet and American troops in World War II.
   To greet three retired Soviet military officers, all veterans of
the linkup of the two armies at the Elbe River on April 25, 1945,
junior high school cheerleaders yelled ``Let's go, red and gold, go
Soviets, go Soviets, big and bold!'' Two dozen schoolchildren sang
``Let There Be Peace on Earth.''
   The Soviets exchanged hugs and handshakes during the ceremony
Monday with four American World War II veterans from Lawrence.
   Earlier in the day, the three-member Soviet delegation laid a
wreath at the grave of Dwight D. Eisenhower, in Abilene, Kan., to
honor the leader of Allied forces in Europe during the war.
   Vladimir Orlov, a retired lieutenant general and the head of the
Soviet delegation, said the former president is well remembered in
the Soviet Union.
   The meeting of Soviet and U.S. troops at the Elbe River signaled
an end to the war. Nazi leader Adolf Hitler committed suicide three
days later, and the Germans surrendered on May 7, 1945.
   In Lawrence, Orlov told reporters he was trying to ``consolidate
friendship'' with Americans during his visit, his first to the
United States.
   American veteran E. Jackson Baur, 75, said that although the
ceremonies will not have any great impact on U.S.-Soviet relations,
``It's one small step in the right direction.''
   The four American veterans who greeted the Soviets in Lawrence
were not at the Elbe when the two Allied armies joined up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
