<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan-Fighting     04-26 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan-Fighting,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diplomats: Soviets Withdrawing From Eastern Afghanistan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One name for Najib cq.
^By BRYAN WILDER</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet forces are beginning to
withdraw from eastern Afghanistan, where anti-communist guerrillas
have taken several posts since the Geneva accord was signed,
Western diplomatic sources said today.
   The sources, speaking in Islamabad on condition of anonymity,
said the Red Army also has begun transporting wrecked vehicles back
to the Soviet Union, apparently to prevent them from being salvaged
by the insurgents.
   Under the Geneva agreement signed April 14, the estimated
115,000 Soviet troops are to start leaving Afghanistan on May 15.
   Diplomats, quoting reports from their Kabul missions, said
evidence of the impending pullout is seen in heavy Soviet air
traffic in and out of Kabul airport and the movement of massive
Soviet convoys near the capital.
   One source quoted an unidentified Soviet diplomat in Kabul as
saying Soviet troops are being ``consolidated'' in Nangarhar,
Paktia and Paktika provinces, all of which border Pakistan.
   Afghanistan's communist president, Najib, also offered on Monday
to withdraw his own troops from posts near the Pakistan border. He
told three small parties loyal to his government that creation of
``a non-military line'' was contingent on agreement with Pakistan
and the guerrillas.
   Pakistan, where the insurgents are based, is a conduit for U.S.
military aid to the guerrillas. It also houses 3 million refugees
of the civil war.
   Soviet troops intervened in Afghanistan in late 1979 when they
replaced one Marxist government with another.
   Diplomatic sources said the Soviets are resupplying the Afghan
army as they prepare to hand the war over to them.
   However, government troops are reported to have fled several
posts in eastern Afghanistan in the past 10 days, including a
strategic garrison at Barikot on the Pakistan border in
northeastern Kunar province.
   The insurgents also reportedly have overrun six Soviet and
Afghan posts in Logar province, just south of Kabul, and Kandahar
in the southeast.
   Western diplomats disagree on the Kabul government's ability to
survive once the Soviets leave.
   Some diplomats say the insurgents recent successes in the east
signalled the beginning of the end of the Kabul government. Others
predict that heavy fortifications in the capital might keep it
secure after the Soviet pullout.
</TEXT>
