<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SovietMagazine     04-26 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Magazine,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Publishers Sign Agreement For Computer Magazine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For two rubles, Soviet personal computer users
soon will be able to access information probably beyond the
capabilities of their present systems.
   In the first joint publishing venture between the United States
and Soviet Union, officials signed an agreement Monday to publish a
Russian-language edition of a major personal computing magazine.
   ``No magazines of any kind in the USSR are based on the concept
of a joint venture with another firm, for personal computers or
anything else,'' Eugene N. Salnicov, director of Radio i Sviaz
Publishers, said of the business agreement with International Data
Group Communications Inc.
   About 50,000 copies of PC World USSR will hit Soviet bookstores
and newsstands in late June priced at two rubles, or $3.20 at the
official exchange rate, said IDG president Alex Leblois. The
magazine will contain about one-third original copy written by a
staff of seven Soviet editors and writers.
   Personal computing is in its infancy in the Soviet Union, which
officials said has had trouble manufacturing computers. There are
fewer than 100,000 personal computers in the country, but Soviet
and American officials tout a potential market of 30 million.
   The liberalization of foreign investment laws, Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost and the recent easing of
Western technology export laws are critical to the publication of
the new magazine.
   Leblois said that U.S. high-tech export regulations were eased
in January to allow 16-bit personal computers to be sold to the
Soviet Union. He predicted that American, Western European and
Japanese computer makers will rush to secure joint production
agreements.
   In keeping with Soviet guidelines on joint ventures adopted in
January 1987, the Soviet partner will own 51 percent of the project
to IDG's 49 percent.
   Salnicov and Michael Volodarsky, chief advisor to the chairman
of Goskomizdat, the Soviet state committee on publishing, printing
and book trade, signed the agreement at IDG headquarters in
Framingham, Mass.
   Leblois said IDG has invested $250,000 in the project but
expects to recoup that almost immediately through advertising from
Western computer makers seeking a foothold in the Soviet Union.
   Marshall Goldman, associate director of the Russian Research
Center at Harvard University, said the principle problem with about
30 joint ventures between the Soviets and foreign companies to date
has been the repatriation of hard currency.
   But IDG said PC World USSR's sales will cover all production
costs and that its revenues will come from advertising paid for in
Western currencies. Foreign firms typically have had problems
getting ruble earnings out of the Soviet Union.
   Salnicov said some foreign language computer journals are
available in Moscow libraries but that Soviet PC users have no
information about developments within the country.
   IDG publishes PC World, the second largest U.S. publication on
personal computers with a monthly circulation of about 475,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0080 </DOCNO>
