<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Laos-Elections     04-26 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Laos-Elections,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Laos To Hold First Nationwide Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laos in June will hold its first
national elections since the communist takeover in December 1975, a
spokesman of the Laotian Embassy in Bangkok said today.
   The official Laotian news agency KPL said district
representatives would be elected in the June 26 elections. Dates
for elections at the central, provincial and prefectural levels
will be determined later, said the report, dated Monday.
   The report quoted an April 21 decree signed by Prime Minister
Kaysone Phomvihane.
   No details were made public on whether there would be more than
one candidate for each post.
   The decree said the election was aimed at ``enabling all
citizens to widely participate in the election of their
representatives to the supreme power institutions at all levels.''
   Ly Bounkham, spokesman for the Laotian Embassy in Bangkok, said
the election would be the first nationwide balloting since the
Pathet Lao seized power 13 years ago.
   ``Stable circumstances prevailing in Laos have suggested that
this would be a right time to have the elections,'' Ly said. ``Laos
has progressed over these years and the country, to a degree, must
adapt to many changes.''
   Laos, a largely isolated nation that is also one of the world's
poorest countries, has been following ``democratization'' reforms
undertaken by its closest allies, Vietnam and the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
