<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Panama     04-26 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Panama,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Embattled Panamanian Ambassador Blames Troubles On Israeli</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's embattled ambassador to Israel
blames his troubles with his own government on an Israeli adviser
to Panamanian military strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Ambassador Eduardo Herrera told a news conference Monday his
dismissal from Panama's army after 22 years service followed an
argument with the Israeli, Mike Harare, a security adviser to
Noriega.
   Herrera, who denied reports he also had been dismissed as
ambassador, said his disagreements with Harare arose after he
accused the Israeli of using his position to charge large
commissions to Israelis trying to do business in Panama.
   ``He blocked commercial ties and potential investments,''
Herrera told reporters at his home outside Tel Aviv. ``He demanded
commissions before anyone could even set foot in Panama.''
   Harare is reportedly in Israel, but efforts to locate him for
comment were unsuccessful.
   A three-page, unsigned flyer issued in Panama last year accused
Harare of making huge profits from business deals, including arms
sales, Morton Rosenthal of the B'nai B'rith Anti-Defamation League
in New York said in a telephone interview.
   The league issued a report linking anti-Semitic threats in
Panama to the allegations against Harare, Rosenthal said.
   Herrera said that in January he ``went to Panama and told the
government everything I knew about Harare. I tore the mask off his
face.''
   He said the two quarreled in April after the ambassador sold an
embassy car driven by Harare. The ambassador said he sold the car
to save money.
   Harare sent the ambassador a threatening letter warning him not
to sell the car. Herrera wrote back saying he was not afraid.
   ``The letter arrived on April 18. That evening, the (Panamanian)
radio reported that I was dismissed from the army,'' Herrera said.
   No reason was given for Herrera's dismissal in reports from
Panama, but sources told reporters there that Herrera had twice
refused instructions to return home.
   Herrara said Monday an order for him to return home had been
rescinded. He also denied reports from Panama that he was fired as
ambassador.
   An Israeli Foreign Ministry official in Jerusalem said the
Israeli government has not received any notification from Panama
that Herrera has been dismissed.
   Noriega is the head of Panama's Defense Force and holds the
power in Panama. Opposition groups in Panama want him to step down.
The United States is supporting the opposition campaign and has
imposed economic sanctions on Panama in an attempt to force Noriega
to leave his post.
</TEXT>
