<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0837EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Demjanjuk-USReax     04-26 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Demjanjuk-US Reax,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family To Continue Fight To Clear Demjanjuk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Demjanjuk's family intends to continue its
fight to vindicate the retired Cleveland autoworker who was
sentenced to hang after an Israeli court determined he was the Nazi
death-camp guard ``Ivan the Terrible.''
   An Israeli panel of judges Monday sentenced Demjanjuk, 68, to
death. The three judges ruled a week ago that the former Ohio
autoworker was responsible for the deaths of thousands of Jews at
the Treblinka concentration camp in Poland during World War II.
   Ed Nishnic, Demjanjuk's son-in-law, said Demjanjuk ``has been
railroaded through the Israeli court system.''
   Nishnic said the family still believes that Demjanjuk is
innocent and would ``fight all the way to the end.''
   ``I spoke to Mr. Demjanjuk yesterday. He believes half the world
already knows he is not `Ivan the Terrible' and the rest of the
world will learn it soon,'' Nishnic said.
   Demjanjuk claimed a case of mistaken identity, but some
concentration camp survivors identified Demjanjuk as the prison
guard who would beat Jews on the way to the gas chamber. The judges
ruled that his alibi, that he was a prisoner of war who never was
in Treblinka, did not stand up to scrutiny.
   In Cleveland, lawyer John J. Horrigan, who as an assistant U.S.
attorney represented the government in Demjanjuk's 1981
denaturalization trial, said the death sentence came as no surprise.
   ``In the end, they, like every other court or tribunal who
looked at the case, were left with little alternative but to find
him guilty and impose the only sentence consistent with that
finding,'' Horrigan said. ``His alibi was a joke.''
   But members of Cleveland's Ukrainian community still believed
Demjanjuk.
   ``It has been the unanimous opinion of this parish that
Demjanjuk is innocent. That has been the opinion since the
beginning,'' said the Rev. John Nakonachny, a priest at St.
Vladimir's Ukrainian Orthodox Church, the Demjanjuk family's parish.
   After the verdict, vandals painted purple circles on St.
Vladimir's, and Jewish organizations in Akron, about 40 miles south
of Cleveland, asked for additional police protection because
callers were threatening local Jews.
   Police said a priest at St. Vladimir's told them the purple
paint might signify blood on the church.
   In Buffalo, N.Y., Demjanjuk's former attorney said he does not
think Demjanjuk will be executed.
   ``The Israeli people are the real jury,'' said Mark O'Connor,
who represented Demjanjuk for five years during deportation
proceedings and during the beginning of trial. ``While they have
doubts I don't see how the court can go through with it.''
   O'Connor said he was fired last year because Demjanjuk's family
thought he was being ``pro-Jewish'' by refraining from attacking
witnesses and using the Talmud to make his points.
   Martin Plax, Cleveland-area director for the American Jewish
Committee, said the sentencing represented ``a sense of relief and
closure that the sort of behavior exhibited by `Ivan the Terrible'
has been adjudicated.''
   Mary Dackiewicz, operating the John Demjanjuk Defense Fund, said
donations to the fund had slackened recently, but calls picked up
again Monday.
   ``The phone calls are from people who have been totally outraged
at what happened over there,'' she said. ``They're people from all
different backgrounds wanting to donate money and asking what they
can do to help.''
</TEXT>
