<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AsbestosFire     04-26 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Asbestos Fire,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Sweeps NATO Warehouse, Sending Asbestos Into The Air</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DONNINGTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire at a NATO storage depot gave
off a huge cloud of smoke that dusted nearby communities with
dangerous asbestos, authorities said.
   Officials used bullhorns to warn people living just west of
Monday's fire to stay inside and avoid stirring up the asbestos
powder.
   The asbestos came from the roof of the burning 10-acre warehouse
at the depot in Donnington in western England.
   A team of 120 local workers put on masks and protective clothing
to clean up the worst contaminated areas.
   Asbestos is a fibrous material used to fireproof and insulate.
It has been linked to lung cancer and other diseases, and other
building materials have increasingly replaced it.
   In dust form, asbestos can cause an often fatal lung disease
called pneumoconiosis.
   The warehouse that caught fire is part of a North Atlantic
Treaty Organization depot employing several thousand people. It is
one of the Western defense alliance's biggest storage areas for
technical equipment and spare parts for military vehicles.
   The army said the warehouse contained no ammunition. No cause of
the fire was given.
   The 190 civilian and British army personnel working in the
warehouse were evacuated, and there were no reports of injury.
   The Army said damage was expected to run into millions of
dollars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
