<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Madonna'sBrother     04-26 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Madonna's Brother,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rock Star's Brother Faces Assault Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock star Madonna's 18-year-old brother
has pleaded innocent to charges that he injured a police officer
checking out loud noises at a downtown home.
   Mario Ciccone allegedly ``shoved, or slammed, or shut, or kicked
without warning the door in the officer's face, knocking him down,
breaking his glasses and cutting his forehead,'' Police Chief
Theodore Glynn said.
   Ciccone, youngest of Madonna's seven brothers and sisters and
listed in court documents as living with his parents in the
northern Detroit suburb of Rochester Hills, pleaded innocent Monday
to a charge of resisting and obstructing a police officer.
   District Court Judge Robert Shipper released him on personal
bond pending a preliminary examination May 5. The misdemeanor
charge carries a maximum penalty of two years in prison.
   Police officer Michael Weidner, 31, and another police officer
went to the house April 16 when they heard what sounded like shots
or firecrackers, according to Glynn and police reports.
   They found a loud party in progress and were asking questions at
the door when ``Mr. Ciccone kicked it from the other side into
Weidner's face,'' the police report said.
   Weidner sustainted a cut that required more than 30 stitches and
has not returned to full duty, officials said.
</TEXT>
