<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0549 04-26 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0549,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Two Israelis, Three Guerrilas Die In Clash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines previous. Adds day in lead.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Israeli soldiers and three Arab
guerrillas died today in a predawn clash near the border with
Israel, police reported.
   A police spokesman said the clash began at 3:30 a.m. near the
southern village of Kfar Shouba when Israeli troops opened fire on
a seven-man guerrilla group. The spokesman said the guerrillas were
made up of two pro-Soviet groups _ the Lebanese Communist Party and
the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine of George Habash.
   A ``fierce clash'' raged for about three hours, said the police
spokesman, who cannot be named in line with standing regulations.
   The Israelis ``fired flares at the rate of 20 every five minutes
as their helicopter gunships chased the guerrillas in the region,''
he said.
   The police spokesman said the guerrillas ``apparently (were)
ambushed before launching a cross-border raid into northern
Israel.''
   Kfar Chuba is a small village about one mile from the Israeli
border on the slopes of biblical Mt. Hermon that towers over the
region where the borders of Lebanon, Israel and Syria converge.
   The village is inside Israel's self-designated ``security zone''
that was established when Israel withdrew the bulk of its troops
from Lebanon in 1985.
</TEXT>
