<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0854EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Carter-Jackson     04-26 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carter-Jackson,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former President Says Party Ticket With Jackson `Amazingly
Attractive'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter said today that
a Democratic presidential ticket with Jesse Jackson would be
``amazingly attractive'' and enable the party to carry the South.
   ``Six months ago, to be blunt about it, I would have said
`no','' Carter said on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America.'' ``But
Jackson has fooled everyone.''
   The former president said Jackson's ``attractiveness and the
quality of his campaign has been amazing'' and ``it's much easier
to say very honestly that Jackson would be amazingly attractive on
the ticket compared to what everybody thought he would do before
this campaign started.''
   Carter said he thought a ticket with Jackson on it would win in
the South and carry his home state of Georgia.
   ``As you know, Jackson came in first in Georgia as it was,'' he
said.
   Carter did not specify whether he envisioned Jackson in the
presidential or vice presidential slot.
   Carter, who will attend the Democratic National Convention as a
``super delegate,'' has refused to endorse any of the party's
candidates, but said if someone ``had to bet one way or another,''
Michael Dukakis would be the most likely nominee.
   Asked if Jackson should be the party's vice presidential choice,
Carter said it would be improper for him to presume that Dukakis _
not Jackson _ would win the nomination.
   He added that if Dukakis wins the nomination, ``Jackson has
exhibited in the last year or so a remarkable element of
substantiality and common sense and loyalty to the party and
attractiveness to a wide range of people and I guess then, in the
convention, that whatever happens, Jackson's support will be
constructive whether he's on the ticket or not.''
</TEXT>
