<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0856EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WorstNukes     04-26 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Worst Nukes,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nader Group Issues List of `Worst' Reactors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-nuclear group's choices for the
nation's worst nuclear power plants are largely identical to a list
compiled by government regulators in 1986.
   The group, Public Citizen, on Monday named 16 plants as the
nation's worst. Thirteen of those plants were also on the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission's list.
   Of the 16, Public Citizen named two as worst than the rest.
   Those plants were Pilgrim, near Plymouth, Mass., operated by
Boston Edison Co., and Rancho Seco at Sacramento, Calif., operated
by the Sacramento Municipal Utility District.
   Both were closed throughout 1987 at the insistence of the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission to correct operational and management
problems. Local authorities are discussing the sale of Rancho Seco,
now operating at 30 percent of full power under recent restart
approval granted by the commission, and Sacramento voters will
decide next month whether to keep it open.
   ``The similarity between Public Citizen's list and the NRC's
list strongly suggests that these plants are indeed the worst in
the United States,'' Public Citizen's ``Critical Mass'' project
said in its Monday report entitled ``Nuclear Lemons.''
   Public Citizen is an advocacy organization founded by consumer
activist Ralph Nader.
   Responding, the Committee for Energy Awareness, a pro-nuclear
trade group, said industry performance is improving, as shown by
reductions in unplanned automatic shutdowns of reactors, radiation
exposure and lost-time accidents.
   Spokesman Don Winston said the committee had not had a chance to
study the Pulic Citizen report in detail.
   Public Citizen ranked the nation's 105 operating civilian
nuclear power reactors according to 10 criteria such as downtime,
operation and maintenance expense and exposure of the workforce to
radiation.
   A reactor was awarded 15 points if it was the worst in a
category, 14 if the second worst and so forth. Rankings were made
by the number of ``15 worst'' lists the reactor appeared on, with
points used as a tiebreaker.
   The 16 plants named by Public Citizen are:
   Rancho Seco, Sacramento, Calif.; Pilgrim, Plymouth, Mass.; Peach
Bottom No. 3, Delta, Pa.; Peach Bottom No. 2, Delta, Pa.; Fermi No.
2, Monroe, Mich.; Oyster Creek, Forked River, N.J.; Sequoyah No. 1,
Chattanooga, Tenn.; Browns Ferry No. 2, Decatur, Ala.; Browns Ferry
No. 3, Decatur, Ala.; Browns Ferry No. 1, Decatur, Ala.;
Davis-Besse, Toledo; Dresden No. 2, Morris, Ill.; LaSalle No. 1,
Seneca, Ill.; Fort St. Vrain, Denver; Sequoyah No. 2, Chattanooga,
Tenn., and Byron No. 1, Rockford, Ill.
   The Ranch Seco, Pilgrim, Sequoyah and Browns Ferry plants were
all closed throughout 1987.
   A similar list compiled by the Nuclear Regulatory Commission in
1986 originally included Oyster Creek and the two Cook plant
reactors at Benton Harbor, Mich. These three were deleted and
replaced by the two Peach Bottom reactors. The commission also
included the LaSalle No. 2 plant and the Turkey Point No. 3 and No.
4 plants near Miami, and did not include the Dresden No. 2 and
Byron No. 1 plants that appeared on Public Citizen's list.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
