<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Amerasians-MIA     04-26 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amerasians-MIA,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Officials Begin Talks On Amerasians, Prepare For MIA Search
In Laos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Vietnamese officials began
talks today on ways to speed up America's resettlement of
Vietnamese, including children fathered by American servicemen
during the Vietnam War.
   Ross Petzing, spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok, said
the American team at the talks was headed by Bruce Beardsley,
director of the embassy's Refugee and Migration Affairs unit.
   The Vietnamese delegation is headed by Hoang Quoc Tin, deputy
director of the Foreign Ministry's consular department, said a
Vietnamese embassy official.
   The talks, the latest of the regularly scheduled sessions on
technical issues, are scheduled to last two days.
   U.S. military experts, meanwhile, are completing a survey of a
warplane crash site in southern Laos and will soon excavate it to
search for remains of missing Americans, a U.S. official said today.
   The excavation in Savannakhet province will be the third such
U.S.-Laotian effort to account for Americans listed as missing in
action in Laos during the Vietnam War. Savannakhet is in the
southern panhandle area between Thailand and Vietnam.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
American team was being led by Lt. Col. Joe Harvey, commander of
the U.S. Joint Casualty Resolution Center headquartered in Honolulu.
   More than 500 Americans still are listed as missing in Laos from
the war in Indochina.
   In the negotiations with Vietnam, the two sides are to discuss
the processing of Vietnamese under the Orderly Departure Program.
   More than 64,000 Vietnamese have been resettled in America under
the program, established in 1980 as an alternative to the tragic
boat exodus.
   U.S. officials will also discuss America's proposal to resettle
within two years up to 12,000 Amerasians, or half-American
children, and their immediate families.
   The United States thus far has resettled more than 4,000
Amerasians.
</TEXT>
