<HEAD>Police: Robbery Victim Wanted to Punish Transvestites</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city worker has been accused of
setting a series of fires to punish narcotics-dealing transvestites
who had robbed him of $50, officials said.
   Robert Bergeron, 31, of Baker, is charged with setting fire to
16 vacant houses in the last four days because they were a haven
for the transvestites, according to police.
   Bergeron, an employee in the Department of Public Works, was
still being held today after being booked early Monday on 16 counts
of simple arson. He is being held on $10,000 bond.
   Police reports quoted Bergeron as saying he was robbed of $50 by
transvestites and felt the only way he could get even was to ``burn
their houses.''
   Two firefighters were injured in the fires, which caused up to a
half-million dollars in damage.
