<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Fighting     04-26 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Fighting,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Killed As Military Battles Renegades</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CEBU CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deserters from an elite military
unit battled government soldiers today, and at least seven people
were killed, the military said.
   Four government troops and three deserters from the military's
elite Scout Rangers were killed during the predawn clash near here
on the small island of Mactan, where Cebu's international airport
is located.
   Local radio stations said one civilian also died.
   The deserters, who took refuge on the island in 1986 and formed
a religious cult, attacked a military checkpoint set up to prevent
them from leaving their hideout, military officials said.
   Maxim Patalinhug, mayor of nearby Lapu-Lapu City, met with the
leader of the renegades to try to convince him to give up. He told
reporters Sgt. Jose Sabandeja promised to ask his men to surrender,
but the renegade leader said he needed time to do so.
   Patalinhug said about 600 civilians were holed up with the
deserters and that they maintained they were willing to die with
the rangers.
   Brig. Gen. Jesus Hermosa, regional military commander, said in a
statement that he called off a planned attack on the deserters
today to allow officials time to negotiate.
   ``The outlaws have many conditions which are not acceptable,''
Hermosa said. ``Their surrender would be unconditional. They should
face the consequences. We have to hold operations due to nightfall
and we don't want to hurt civilians. Operations will continue
tomorrow by daybreak.''
   Hermosa has vowed to capture the 30 to 50 renegades, who moved
to Mactan after deserting their unit on Mindanao island.
   The military claims the renegades have been involved in
smuggling operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
