<DOCNO> AP880426-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0942EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PresserRuling     04-26 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presser Ruling,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Doesn't Have To Share Evidence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has decided that
attorneys for indicted Teamsters union President Jackie Presser
don't have a right to secret documents the federal government is
protecting.
   A three-judge panel of the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
ruled unanimously Monday that a lower court was incorrect in
ordering government prosecutors to share the documents.
   Federal prosecutors want to keep the documents confidential
until the July 12 trial of Presser and co-defendants Harold
Friedman and Anthony Hughes, fellow officers of Cleveland's
Teamsters Local 507.
   The appeals court reversed U.S. District Judge George White in
Cleveland, who had ruled in favor of defense attorneys.
   ``In essence, the district court concluded ... that the defense
has a constitutional right to know the tactical strengths and
weaknesses of the government's case against it. The Supreme Court
has never held that the Constitution creates such a right and we do
not believe that it exists,'' Judge Danny Boggs wrote in the 6th
Circuit's decision.
   Defense attorney John Climaco said Monday he was unaware of the
appellate ruling. He declined to comment until he had a chance to
see the opinion.
   White is scheduled to preside over the July 12 trial. The three
defendants are charged in a May 1986 federal indictment with having
perpetrated a $700,000 payroll-padding scheme in which ``ghost
employees'' were put on the union payroll of Local 507.
   Presser, 60, is secretary-treasurer of Local 507, as well as
president of the 1.6 million-member Teamsters union.
   The defense argued that Presser and the other defendants were
serving as government informants at the time and that the FBI had
authorized them to go ahead with the payroll-padding scheme.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
