<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shultz     04-26 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Briefing Reagan on Moscow Trip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, back from
Moscow, is reporting to President Reagan on the slow progress in
arms control negotiations with the Soviet Union.
   Schultz was briefing Reagan at mid-afternoon.
   Unless there is an unexpected breakthrough, or a shift in
policy, a treaty to halve U.S. and Soviet strategic nuclear weapons
is unlikely to be ready for Reagan and General Secretary Mikhail S.
Gorbachev to sign when they meet in Moscow May 29 through June 2.
   The two sides are far apart on methods to verify cutbacks in
mobile missiles and cruise missiles carried on fighter planes and
warships.
   Another obstacle is Reagan's Strategic Defense Initiative.
   The Soviets are refusing to sign the treaty unless they have the
right to suspend reductions if they conclude that U.S. anti-missile
tests in space violate the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
   Shultz was unable to bridge the differences in his talks in
Moscow last week with Gorbachev and Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze. He will see Shevardnadze again May 11-12.
</TEXT>
