<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Cars-Hails     04-26 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cars-Hails,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hail Damages Cars, But Tornado Passes Over</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms peppered 10 Alabama
counties with hail the size of tennis balls, leaving thousands of
car owners and car dealerships sizing up dents and cracked
windshields.
   ``It looks horrible,'' Frank McGough said Monday as he surveyed
the lot at Capitol Chevrolet in Montgomery.
   ``We've got close to 2,000 vehicles on our lot, and I would say
99 percent of them have some damage,'' McGough said. ``Hail is the
worst thing that can happen to an automobile dealership because it
dents all your vehicles up.''
   McGough said one employee estimated damages at close to $500,000.
   Meanwhile, officials at the Alabama Emergency Management Center
were relieved that even worse damage was avoided as tornadoes swept
across three counties without touching down.
   Tornado warnings, which mean a tornado has been spotted on
radar, were issued in Montgomery, Macon and Lee counties during the
late afternoon. By 7:30 p.m., however, the warnings had been lifted.
   Robin Hearn, a spokesman at the Montgomery-based AEMC, said
officials received numerous reports of heavy thunderstorms and
hailstorms, but that there were no reports of a tornado touching
down.
   In Lee County, an ambulance driver called emergency officials to
report winds gusting so hard that he couldn't control his vehicle.
   State troopers reported no fatalities or serious injuries
related to the storms.
   Wade Hilton, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service,
said the tornado warnings were issued after radar showed several
funnel clouds moving toward Montgomery at about 60 mph.
   ``It's like a tornado aloft, but not touching the ground,''
Hilton said.
   Hilton said hail from an inch and a half to three inches in
diameter is often produced in such a storm.
   Hearn said the emergency office had heard several descriptions
of the size of the hail. ``We've heard anything from tennis-ball
sized up to baseball-sized.''
   In Eufaula, Hearn said, officials reported ``pigeon egg-sized
hail.''
   ``I think somebody sits around and tries to think up this
terminology,'' he said.
</TEXT>
