<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HedgecockAppeal     04-26 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hedgecock Appeal,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ruling Sets Dangerous Precedent, Says District Attorney</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors who convicted former Mayor Roger
Hedgecock on perjury and conspiracy charges could be put on trial
themselves under an appeals court ruling on jury tampering
allegations, a dissenting judge said.
   Deputy Attorney General Bob Foster said Monday he will appeal a
ruling by the 4th District Court of Appeal, which ordered a lower
court to hold an evidentiary hearing on jury misconduct and jury
tampering allegations.
   Compelling former Hedgecock jurors to testify in the hearing
could create a ``colossal discouragement'' towards jury duty among
citizens, said Steve Casey, spokesman for the San Diego County
district attorney.
   ``It used to be that jurors were protected from that. The law
wanted to protect them from that kind of intimidation and
harassment,'' Casey said. ``This certainly transcends the Hedgecock
case and we're concerned about it.''
   Foster said Monday's ruling was a dangerous precedent because
the evidentiary hearing could expose jurors to subpoenas under new
trial motions.
   ``Until now, it seemed fairly clear that you could not bring a
juror (on subpoena) into a motion for a new trial in a criminal
case,'' said Foster, who litigated the appeal for the district
attorney's office. ``That's a change in the law and creates a
conflict of authority amongst published cases.''
   The dissenting judge in the 2-1 ruling agreed. Justice Edward
Butler said the decision ``authorizes a trial of jurors who return
a guilty verdict in a criminal case.''
   In the majority opinion, justices said the trial judge failed to
properly consider jury misconduct complaints by Hedgecock, who
resigned as a convicted felon on Dec. 10, 1985, two months after
his conviction.
   However, the majority opinion added: ``In our view, the evidence
fully supports the jury's conclusion that Hedgecock was part of a
conspiracy to violate the disclosure requirements of the Political
Reform Act and the local campaign finance laws.''
   Hedgecock's conviction stemmed from a campaign finance
conspiracy and coverup attempt in which hundreds of thousands of
dollars in illegal contributions went unreported on state-mandated
disclosure forms.
   Hedgecock's lawyer, Charles Sevilla, alleged in his appeal that
a bailiff made derogatory remarks within earshot of the sequestered
jurors, telling one person the former mayor was guilty and that
prosecutors would win the case ``hands down.''
   The allegations against the bailiff were cited in affidavits by
two jurors. The remaining 10 jurors and the bailiff denied the
allegations.
   The justices rejected 23 other issues raised in Sevilla's appeal.
   Hedgecock, who now works as a local radio talk show host, was
convicted in October 1985 on one count of conspiracy and 12 counts
of perjury in his second trial. His first trial ended in a mistrial
when the jury hung 11-1 in favor of conviction.
   The charges stemmed from a plot to illegally finance his
successful 1983 mayoral campaign with more than $350,000 from the
now-defunct J. David & Co. investment firm.
   Hedgecock was sentenced to a year in jail and three years
probation and fined $1,000, but has remained free pending his
appeal. He is vacationing in Brazil this week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1023EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mofford 1stLd-Writethru a0550 04-26 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mofford, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0550,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mofford Says She'll Amend Forms</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 9th pvs, ``I'm not trying xxx, to add
info on Mofford's husband</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Rose Mofford says she will file
amended financial disclosure statements listing land, loans and
partnerships to avoid ``additional doubts and nitpicking.''
   But former Gov. Evan Mecham, who faces criminal charges over
alleged omissions on his statements, notes that amending his
statements didn't help him.
   A top aide to Attorney General Bob Corbin said meanwhile that
his office was looking into Mrs. Mofford's original filings and
that ``under the circumstances now'' it could not give Mrs. Mofford
advice.
   Lawmakers said they would prefer to leave matters in Corbin's
hands, but some left open the possibility of another legislative
investigation, similar to the one that led to Mecham's impeachment.
   ``We'll just have to wait until the A.G. says,'' said House
Speaker Joe Lane, who initiated the Mecham investigation after
Corbin confirmed that Mecham's activities were being scrutinized by
a grand jury. ``I just hope she gets everything fixed up.''
   Mrs. Mofford's office, in a written statement, said she hoped to
file the changes by the end of the week but needed more time to
research them.
   The Associated Press reported last week that Mrs. Mofford had
not listed land, loan and partnership transactions on the public
officer reporting forms that she was in charge of during her 10
years as Secretary of State.
   Mrs. Mofford said that many of the transactions stemmed from
arrangements made by her former husband and that she had not
profited from them.
   ``I'm not trying to hide anything,'' she said at the time,
adding that everything was reported on her income-tax forms. She
declined to make the returns public.
   Mrs. Mofford married T.R. Mofford in 1957. They were divorced 10
years later, but the governor says they remained good friends until
T.R. died in 1983.
   On Monday, the governor reiterated her position.
   ``I still question whether the law requires that these items be
disclosed, but I wish to avoid even the appearance of
impropriety,'' she said. ``Arizona has been through enough without
additional doubts and nitpicking.''
   But Mecham, read Mrs. Mofford's statement, laughed and said ``I
love it'' when he got to the passage about doubts and nitpicking.
   ``I don't see any place in the (reporting) law where it says you
have to make any profit,'' he added, saying that the transaction he
is accused of concealing _ a $350,000 campaign loan _ did not
involve any profit to him.
   Mrs. Mofford said she would ask Corbin to determine whether the
items should have been included on her disclosure forms ``so that
his advice can be available to her and to other public officials
faced with questions,'' her office said.
   Corbin was out of town Monday, but chief assistant Attorney
General Steve Twist said his agency planned to review records of
the transactions.
   ``Under the circumstances now, it would not be appropriate for
us to give any personal advice to the governor,'' Twist said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
