<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Earnings-Glance,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exxon, Mobil, Other Companies Report Strong Quarterly Earnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-OPEC Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five major U.S. oil companies posted strong
gains in first-quarter performance as the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries met to seek ways to raise crude oil prices by
controlling supplies.
   Here are the companies' results, reported Monday, compared with
1987's first quarter:
   _Exxon Corp. earned $1.46 billion, or $1.06 per share, up 36
percent from $1.07 billion, or 75 cents a share. Sales were $22.0
billion vs. $19.4 billion.
   _Mobil Corp. earned $505 million, or $1.23 a share, up 49.9
percent from $252 million, or 62 cents a share. Revenue from
continuing operations totaled $13.8 billion vs. $11.7 billion.
   _Amoco Corp. earned $469 million, or $1.82 a share, up 80.4
percent from $260 million, or $1.02 per share. Sales totaled $5.8
billion vs. $5.2 billion.
   _Occidental Petroleum Corp., earned $113 million, or 52 cents a
share, up 16.5 percent from $97 million, or 50 cents per share.
Sales totaled $4.48 billion vs. $4.16 billion.
   _Unocal Corp. earned $178.4 million, or $1.53 a share, up 66
percent from $60.7 million, or 52 cents a share. Sales were $2.3
billion vs. $2.06 billion.
</TEXT>
