<DOCNO> AP880426-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-WorldCourt-PLO     04-26 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-World Court-PLO,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Court Rules Against U.S. Attempt To Shut PLO Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Court today ruled
against the United States' attempt to shut down the Palestine
Liberation Organization's mission in New York.
   The ruling implicitly condemned the U.S. move to close the PLO
mission to the United Nations by supporting the U.N. position that
the dispute must be submitted to independent arbitration.
   The ruling was the court's second decision against the United
States in two years.
   In 1986, the U.N.'s judicial arm condemned as a violation of
international law the Reagan administration's support for the
rebels fighting Nicaragua's Sandinista government.
   The World Court, officially known as the International Court of
Justice, has no enforcement powers and depends on voluntary
adherence to its rulings.
   The PLO office dispute emanates from American anti-terrorist
legislation signed into law by President Reagan last December. The
legislation aims at closing the PLO's 14-year-old observer mission
to the United Nations in New York.
   The law classifies the PLO as a ``terrorist organization,'' and
bars it from operating on U.S. territory. The PLO's information
office in Washington, D.C. was closed down prior to the passage of
the legislation.
   The attempt to shut down the PLO Mission in New York has been
condemned by all U.N. member nations except the United States and
Israel, as well as by the U.N. administration. The U.S. State
Department also opposed the law.
   Briefs on the case have been filed by the United Nations and the
U.S. government, as well as by Syria and East Germany. Although
their contents are confidential, the East German and Syrian briefs
are widely considered to support the PLO position.
   Because only sovereign states and U.N. bodies are entitled to
bring cases before the court, the PLO was unable to plead its case
before the 15-judge panel.
   At the request of the U.N. General Assembly, Secretary General
Javier Perez de Cuellar filed the court case March 9 in the form of
a request for a legal opinion on whether the dispute is subject to
arbitration.
   The so-called Headquarters Agreement, a 1947 pact between the
Truman Administration and the U.N., specifies that disputes are
subject to arbitration by a three-member panel.
   Under that treaty, diplomats of U.N. member nations and
organizations with observer status are guaranteed the right to
operate in New York.
   The Reagan administration has rejected independent arbitration
in the case as premature, noting the PLO case is under review by a
federal court in the United States.
   But in its submissions to the court, the Reagan administration
has also said that the anti-terrorist law calls for closing the PLO
Mission ``irrespective of any international legal obligations that
the United States may have under the Headquarters Agreement.''
   The PLO was accorded permanent observer status at the United
Nations in 1974 and has maintained an office in Manhattan since
then.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
