<DOCNO> AP880426-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1128EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bullet-Appeal     04-26 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bullet-Appeal,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Says He Will Raise Bullet Issue In New Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bullet lodged in Paul Rougeau's buttocks since
a robbery a decade ago is expected to surface again as an issue in
attempts to keep Rougeau from being executed.
   The U.S. Supreme Court on Monday refused to consider a death row
appeal based on prosecutors' remarks about the bullet during
Rougeau's 1978 murder trial, but lawyer Steven Thorpe says he will
raise the issue again in a different form.
   Rougeau refused to let doctors remove the slug after the robbery
and shooting death. Prosecutors told the jury trying him for
capital murder in the death of Deputy Constable A.C. Wilkins that
Rougeau probably feared the bullet would be identified as having
come from the dead officer's gun.
   Thorpe contended in his appeal that state District Judge Jon N.
Hughes violated the defendant's Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination by permitting the remarks.
   The Supreme Court declined to hear those arguments, but Thorpe
said he will file a new appeal claiming that the mention of the
bullet violated Rougeau's Fourth Amendment right against
unreasonable search and seizure.
   A 1985 Supreme Court ruling held that suspects have a
constitutional right to refuse to have a bullet surgically removed,
and in general, prosecutors ``may not use against you the fact that
you invoked your constitutional rights,'' Thorpe said.
   He noted that prosecutors may not tell jurors that a defendant
refused to talk to police.
   The Supreme Court has tried to strike a balance between
protecting suspects against deeply intrusive acts such as forced
surgery while still allowing police to get the evidence they need
by such lesser measures as taking fingerprints or samples of hair,
blood or skin, all of which are permitted, Thorpe said.
   But state Assistant Attorney General Robert Walt said federal
courts generally will not rehear cases in which appeal is based on
search and seizure issues that the defense has had a previous
opportunity to raise.
   Wilkins was working as a security guard at Houston's Stock
Exchange Club Jan. 6, 1978, when it was held up by three men.
   Rougeau's brother Joseph, 30, was killed in a shoot-out with
police. The third man, Gillis Guillory, 27, later pleaded guilty to
murder and testified against Rougeau in return for a 40-year
sentence.
   Guillory testified he saw Rougeau standing over Wilkins.
   ``The officer asked Paul not to shoot him again,'' Guillory
said, but Rougeau replied, ``Die like you should'' and pulled the
trigger again.
</TEXT>
