<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Amnesty-Centenarian 1stLd-Writethru a0506 04-26 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty-Centenarian, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0506,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>102-Year-Old Woman To Be Granted Amnesty</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs the 4th graf with 2 grafs to show that Mrs. Martinez was
granted citizenship</NOTE>
<DATELINE>QUEMADO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration officials have a unique 103rd
birthday gift for an elderly alien who once helped Mexican forces
hunt outlaw Pancho Villa.
   Officials from the Immigration and Naturalization Office will be
in this border city 90 miles north of Laredo this afternoon to
present Francisca Rivera de Chavez with legal residence in the
United States.
   ``She's still very alert, but she can't get to a legalization
office,'' said John Armistad, spokesman for the agency's Dallas
office.
   In February, the INS restored legal status to Clara Escobedo
Martinez, 98, whose green card was canceled by immigration
officials in 1962. The INS reduced the number of years normally
necessary to get citizenship in her case and Mrs. Escobedo became
the first amnesty applicant granted citizenship on April 8.
   Mrs. Escobedo has been making television commercials for the INS
to urge other aliens who qualify to apply for amnesty.
   Under new immigration laws, aliens who have lived continuously
in the United States since 1982 are eligible for amnesty and later
citizenship.
   Mrs. Chavez was born May 8, 1885, in Concepcion del Oro in
Jalisco, Mexico, and is the widow of Maj. Rafael Chavez, a soldier
in the Mexican forces during the Mexican Revolution. Mrs. Chavez
provided information to her husband's troops on Villa's activities
in the Piedras Negras area, Armistad said.
   After her husband died in 1937, Mrs. Chavez moved to the United
States to work in restaurants in Houston and Los Angeles, the INS
said.
   Usually, amnesty applicants must wait six years before receiving
an application for citizenship, but officials speeded up the
process for Mrs. Escobedo. Armistad said he expects the same will
be done for Mrs. Chavez.
   Mrs. Chavez is the mother of 12 children and has 55
grandchildren, 112 great-grandchildren and four
great-great-grandchildren.
   She lives with a daughter in this South Texas town.
</TEXT>
