<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EastStLouis-Woes     04-26 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-East St Louis-Woes,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Struggles As Coffers Near Empty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Layoffs have forced the temporary
closing of the city's treasurer's office because the city's primary
bank account held only $884, officials said.
   Twenty-five layoffs took effect Monday and included all of
Treasurer Charlotte R. Moore's regular workers.
   ``They laid off my administrative assistant and two
accountants,'' as well as four other workers, Ms. Moore said.
``They didn't leave anyone in here.''
   Three workers from other departments were transferred into the
treasurer's office, but Ms. Moore said accountants and account
clerks were replaced with clerk-typists and reference clerks.
   Ms. Moore said a city payroll of about $230,000 is scheduled to
be paid Friday. But even with an expected infusion of state
sales-tax receipts during the week, the city could still not have
enough to pay its workers, she said.
   East St. Louis is plagued by a dwindling industrial base, high
unemployment, crime and a growing municipal debt.
   The city also faces a $4 million judgment awarded last year to a
man who suffered brain damage when he was beaten by a cellmate in
the city jail. The company that had handled municipal trash
collection filed suit last fall over $262,000 in unpaid bills. And
last month the city pleaded innocent to charges that it is
endangering its police officers with inadequate equipment.
   Layoffs were recommended two weeks ago by the city's Government
Operations Committee in an effort to cut costs to meet payroll and
pay city debts, including a $29,000 monthly garbage contract and a
monthly $20,000 payment on the lawsuit judgment.
   Officials have said they must trim about $144,000 a month from
the budget to keep the municipality from going bankrupt.
</TEXT>
