<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TenantVerdict     04-26 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tenant Verdict,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tenant Who Was Harassed by Landlord Wins $2.9 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tenant whose rent-controlled apartment was
demolished around him will get $2.9 million from the landlord for
damages and harassment, a Manhattan jury has decided.
   The jury made the award Monday to Emilio Bellitti, a retired
garment industry worker who has lived in a $350-a-month,
two-bedroom apartment for 35 years.
   Bellitti's lawyer, Stuart Gruskin, said his client and the
building's six other tenants were asked in 1983 to leave so the
house could be gutted and renovated. Bellitti and his now-dead
roommate, Victor Rizika, refused.
   Gruskin said that in the summer of 1984, the landlords, Suzanne
and Robert Lavanant, gutted the building with Bellitti still there.
   ``During demolition, the ceilings and walls in my client's
apartment collapsed,'' Gruskin said. ``Fortunately, he was not
physically injured.''
   ``They couldn't get him out legally so they decided to just try
to drive him out by going ahead with work,'' the lawyer said.
   Gruskin said that in April 1985 he reached agreement with the
Lavanants, owners of about eight buildings in Manhattan, to rebuild
Bellitti's apartment, but proceeded with the suit anyhow ``because
of the way the landlord ignored my client's rights.''
   After a six-day trial and two days of deliberations, the jury of
three men and three women awarded Bellitti $400,000 in compensatory
damages, a rent abatement worth about $6,000, and $2.5 million in
punitive damages for the landlord's ``reckless disregard of the
tenants' safety,'' Gruskin said.
   The lawyer said Rizika, also a retired garment industry worker,
died in October 1986. He said his legal status regarding the award
is not clear yet.
</TEXT>
