<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonCommode     04-26 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Commode,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmate's Broken Toilet Complaint Revived</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court said today that a
State Penitentiary inmate whose cell toilet was broken for 37 days
may have grounds for a claim of cruel and unusual punishment.
   A three-judge panel of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
returned inmate Melvin C. Wilson's complaint to U.S. District Court
in Norfolk for further review.
   Judge Richard B. Kellam had ruled in favor of Warden Michael C.
Samberg on the commode claim, as well as other issues raised by
Wilson.
   Wilson alleged, in addition to the toilet and other complaints,
that a lockdown at the downtown Richmond prison was unlawful, that
he was denied food, that he was illegally put in punitive
confinement and that meals were unsanitary and insufficient.
   The appeals panel upheld Kellam on all points but the broken
toilet, which Wilson said caused sewage to flood his cell. Wilson
also said he was denied cleaning materials and that his meals
during a lockdown were slid under his cell bars through raw sewage.
   Samberg, in an affidavit, said he was not aware of any waste in
Wilson's cell and that the delay in fixing the toilet was caused by
having to wait for ordered parts.
   ``Wilson's description of his broken commode, if taken as true,
may well state a claim for cruel and unusual punishment,'' the
appeals panel said in returning the case to the lower court for a
determination of the facts.
   Wilson, 44, is serving two life sentences plus 46 years for
murder, robbery and other convictions. His sentence began in April
1970.
</TEXT>
