<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Strke, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0606,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strikes Reported At Steel Plant in Southern Poland</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with reported work stoppages in Nowa Huta
near Krakow, Urban and Walesa comments.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 4,000 workers at the Lenin steel
mill near Krakow in southern Poland refused to work today because
they want higher wages, opposition spokesmen said.
   Workers at a big heavy machinery plant in southeast Poland,
meanwhile, threatened a strike today after two Solidarity leaders
were fired for leading a protest rally there last week, members of
the banned trade union federation said.
   According to Ryszard Bocian, a Solidarity activist in Krakow,
the strike at the Lenin mill in the Krakow suburb of Nowa Huta
began this morning in three departments of the plant and spread
later to a fourth.
   A spokesman at the office of government spokesman Jerzy Urban
said only 900 workers went on strike.
   A spokeswoman at the plant office told The Associated Press that
no one authorized to comment was available.
   The reported job action came one day after an 11-hour strike by
2,800 transit workers in the western Polish city of Bydgoszcz
achieved a wage increase for bus and tram drivers. The strike was
reported in Polish newspapers and on television.
   The Nowa Huta steel workers seek pay increases of $30 a month,
Bocian said. He said the strike was launched by Maciej Mach, a
Solidarity activist.
   One worker reached at the plant by telephone, who identified
himself only as an electronics engineer, said workshops were idle
and talks with management representatives continued.
   ``The situation in Poland is getting hotter and hotter. Anything
can happen anyplace,'' Solidarity chairman Lech Walesa told
reporters today in an impromptu news conference at the Norwegian
embassy in Warsaw. He met there privately with visiting Foreign
Minister Thorvald Stoltenberg of Norway.
   Asked about the Bydgoszcz strike, which was led by members of
the officially sanctioned trade union and not by Solidarity, he
said: ``It doesn't matter what you are a member of. People are
fighting to improve their lives.''
   Solidarity was declared illegal after the 1981 martial-law
crackdown in Poland, although its leadership has managed to remain
active. The government later organized an officially sanctioned
trade union alliance, whose unions now claim 7 million members.
   Urban, at his weekly news conference, said that under Poland's
program of economic reform, decisions on pay no longer will be made
by the central government. He said factory managers themselves will
have to decide how much their enterprises can afford to pay.
   The government says prices in Poland rose 42 percent in the
first three months of 1988, and wages climbed by 45 percent in the
same period. Government officials have expressed concern that wages
are growing too quickly and will spur even more inflation.
   At the Stalowa Wola heavy machinery plant in southeast Poland,
Wieslaw Wojtas, chairman of the founding committee of that plant's
Solidarity local, and Wieslaw Turasz, a committee member, were
fired Monday afternoon, said Ewa Kaberna, a Solidarity activist in
the city.
   She said workers ``announced a strike alert and are preparing a
general strike'' to protest the firings. She said she did not know
when the job action would take place.
   Opposition spokesmen said Wojtas and Turasz led about 5,000
workers in a rally before the start of the afternoon shift Thursday
at the sprawling plant in Stalowa Wola, about 95 miles southeast of
Warsaw. The plant employs 18,000 workers.
   Ms. Kaberna said Wojtas read a speech at the rally listing the
Solidarity committee's demands, including across-the-board pay
raises of $50 a month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
