<1ST_LINE>r a PM-River-Sewage     04-26 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-River-Sewage,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sewage Continues Pouring Into River, Officials Track Its Movement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raw sewage is pouring into the Chattahoochee
River from an Atlanta treatment plant and Georgia officials have
warned municipalities downstream in both Georgia and Alabama.
   Ruptured pipes at the R.M. Clayton Water Pollution Control Plant
forced officials to start dumping untreated sewage into the
Chattahoochee on Sunday.
   By midday today, the total spill was expected to exceed 180
million gallons.
   State officials took water samples at several locations Monday
in an effort to determine how quickly the sewage was moving
downstream and how serious the environmental damage might be.
   ``I would certainly not want to fall in the water,'' said Gib
Johnston, a spokesman for the state Department of Natural Resources.
   In three cities downstream _ LaGrange, West Point and Columbus _
officials have been warned to take precautions to ensure that their
drinking water is safe. Officials in Alabama, which borders the
west bank of the Chattahoochee, also were advised of the situation.
   Untreated sewage may contain large quantities of disease-causing
bacteria and other microorganisms. The waste also can rob the river
water of dissolved oxygen, which is necessary to fish and other
aquatic organisms.
   Pumps were moved into the treatment plant Monday to remove 30
feet of water from the basement and sub-basement, where the
ruptured pipes were located. The plant's own pumps were flooded and
unable to function.
   City officials said it might take three or four days to fix the
broken pipes and halt the spill.
</TEXT>
