<1ST_LINE>u p PM-NewJerseyBallot     04-26 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Jersey Ballot,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Alters Primary Balloting System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson has won a court victory
in New Jersey that will allow primary voters to pull one lever to
choose both a presidential candidate and the delegates assigned to
him.
   Hudson County Superior Court Judge Burrell Ives Humphreys
decided Monday on a compromise to address a request by Jackson's
Democratic presidential campaign, which had challenged the
balloting system that required voters to vote for a candidate and
again for the candidate's delegate slate.
   The Jackson campaign said it would be easier for voters to pull
just one lever, rather than two, to choose a candidate and
delegates.
   But the Democratic Party, the campaign of Gov. Michael Dukakis
of Massachusetts and New Jersey's county clerks opposed the plan,
saying it was contrary to party rules, would limit a voter's
choices and would be expensive.
   On Monday, Humphreys decided to permit voters who wish to do so
to pull one lever to select their candidate and his delegates.
   In areas with machines that can accommodate both single- and
multi-lever voting, Humphreys said voters would be given a choice.
In areas without such equipment, write-in ballots would be
available to those voters wishing to make separate selections for a
candidate and delegates.
   ``We should not lose sight of the purpose of the ballot, which
is to allow voters to ma gross
national product was propelled by a strong increase in consumer
spending and the biggest surge in business investment in more than
four years.
   Economists said the balanced growth was good news for
Republicans in an election year and should bury lingering fears
that the 508-point drop in the stock market on Oct. 19 would topple
the country into a recession.
   ``This report presents a good, healthy picture of the U.S.
economy in the first quarter, nothing near a recession despite all
the earlier worries,'' said Allen Sinai, chief economist of the
Boston Co. ``This is good political reading for the Republicans.''
   The administration wasted no time in boasting about the GNP
report.
   ``So much for the recession that was supposed to occur in the
first quarter,'' Commerce Under Secretary Robert Ortner said at a
briefing for reporters. ``Today's report shows the economy entering
its sixth year of expansion with inflation remaining moderate.''
   In further good news, the growth was accompanied by a slowdown
in the rate of inflation, with a price measure tied to the GNP
rising at an annual rate of 2.4 percent, down from a 2.7 percent
increase in the fourth quarter.
   Beryl Sprinkel, the president's chief economic adviser, said
that the GNP report should allay fears that have cropped up
recently in financial markets that growing inflationary pressures
would force the Federal Reserve Board to raise interest rates in
coming months.
   ``The economy is on track for moderate further expansion and
restrained inflation in 1988,'' Sprinkel said at a White House
briefing.
   The GNP grew at a much faster 4.8 percent rate in the
October-December quarter, but analysts said that growth masked some
dangerous imbalances that were not present in the first quarter
report.
   Almost all of the fourth quarter increase in GNP wound up as
unsold inventory sitting on shelves. At the same time, consumer
spending was taking a rare nose dive, falling by 2.5 percent, the
biggest drop in seven years. This combination has in the past been
a harbinger of a recession.
   This pattern was reversed in the first quarter with business
inventories, which had risen by $39.4 billion in the fourth
quarter, falling by $13.2 billion in the first quarter, indicating
a success by businesses in reducing swollen inventories.
   Much of the success in working down the inventory bulge occurred
in auto showrooms, as dealers were aided by a new round of sales
incentives.
   This helped boost consumer spending by $23.6 billion in the
first quarter, a 3.8 percent annual rate of increase. The report
said more than half of that growth came in auto sales.
   Business investment for capital equipment shot up at an annual
rate of 32.5 percent in the first quarter, the fastest advance
since a 39.5 percent increase in the fourth quarter of 1983.
   In other good news, the country's trade deficit, after removing
the effects of inflation, narrowed by $3.6 billion in the first
quarter, continuing the trend of improvement that began in mid-1986.
   The administration, which is forecasting that GNP will grow 2.9
percent for the full year, is counting on further improvements in
the trade deficit to supply almost half of GNP growth this year.
   Much of the rest of the increase is expected to come from higher
business capital spending as companies expand production facilities
to meet a growing export demand.
   Both of those trends were evident in today's GNP report,
providing good news for the Reagan administration, which is
counting on a sixth straight year of economic growth to boost
chances for a Republican presidential win in November.
   In another report, the government said that after-tax corporate
profits rose an even faster 2.6 percent in the final three months
of 1987. This was an upward revision from a month ago, when the
government put the increase in business profits at 1.6 percent.
   Two factors that held back GNP growth in the first quarter were
a 9.4 percent drop in residential construction spending and a 22.3
percent drop in spending by the federal government, reflecting in
large part a swing in farm subsidy payments.
   The various changes pushed the GNP, after adjusting for
inflation, up by $21.8 billion, to a new annual rate of $3.90
trillion.
   The first quarter growth was welcome news when compared to
forecasts being made at the beginning of the year. At the time,
some analysts were actually predicting that the GNP would decline
in the first quarter, signalling the start of a new recession.
   The pessimists believed that a combination of the shock to
consumer confidence from the stock market collapse and the huge
overhang of business inventories would severely depress economic
activity in the early part of this year.
   The fear was that after a loss of a trillion dollars in wealth,
nervous consumers would stop spending and manufacturers, caught
with huge inventories of unsold goods, would cut back on production
and lay off workers.
   But, those events did not occur. Instead of cutting back after
the market turmoil, employers actually boosted hiring. Since
October, an average of 362,000 new jobs have been added to the
economy each month, more than twice the size of the monthly gains
before the crash.
   The big gains in employment helped restore consumer confidence,
considered critical for the economy's health since consumer
spending accounts for two-thirds of economic activity.
   The Reagan administration is predicting that the GNP will expand
at a 2.9 percent annual rate this year, marking the third
consecutive year the economy has grown at this rate.
   This view is in line with the outlook of many private
forecasters as well. Blue Chip Economic Indicators, a Sedona, Ariz.
newsletter, said that its latest survey of 51 top economists found
a consensus forecast for growth of 2.7 percent this year, up
significantly from a 1.9 percent GNP estimate made in the month
following the market crash.
</TEXT>
