<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Jackson-Africa     04-26 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Africa,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says South Africa Deserves Terrorist Label</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential candidate Jesse Jackson told top
State Department officials today that South Africa should be
treated as a terrorist nation because it backs Mozambique rebels
who have allegedly killed 100,000 civilians.
   The Democrat was briefed at the State Department on a recent
study describing ``systematic abuse'' and murder by the Renamo
rebels. He told reporters that the sponsorship of the rebels by
South Africa ``defines state-sponsored terrorism.''
   Chester Crocker, assistant secretary of state for African
affairs, joining Jackson at a news conference outside the State
Department, acknowledged South Africa's ties to the rebels. But he
declined to characterize South Africa as a terrorist state, saying
only that its involvement with Renamo goes against a previous
commitment made by Pretoria.
   Both Crocker and Jackson described the session this morning,
which included Deputy Secretary of State John Whitehead, as a
briefing session for the candidate.
   The study was conducted by State Department consultant Robert
Gersony and released a week ago. Jackson siezed on it to underscore
his call for a change in U.S. policy toward South Africa and the
so-called frontline states around it.
   The report was based on Gersony's interviews with 196 Mozambique
refugees and numerous relief workers who told of random murders,
rapes, burning of villages, forced labor, mutilation, looting and
beatings by Renamo, which is trying to bring down Mozambique's
Marxist-led government.
   ``It is conservatively estimated that 100,000 civilians may have
been murdered by Renamo in this manner,'' the report concluded.
   Jackson challenged his Democratic opponent, Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis, and Vice President George Bush to also
characterize South Africa as a terrorist state.
   He also called for an increase in humanitarian aid to the
frontline states and for a congressional delegation to visit
Mozambique and report to President Reagan on conditions there.
   Jackson has sought to make South Africa and African affairs part
of the presidential campaign debate, but other candidates have not
made it an issue.
   Earlier today, Jackson met at Capitol Hill with Congress members
and ambassadors of the frontline states on the issue.
   Some conservative members of Congress have called for U.S. aid
to Renamo, but the United States officially supports the Mozambican
government.
</TEXT>
