<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ClimbingDeath     04-26 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Climbing Death,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Expedition Leader Says Colleague Fell or Froze to Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BINAYA GURUACHARYA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of an American expedition in
the Himalayas said Tuesday his missing colleague had fallen or
frozen to death after reaching the top of 23,488-foot Mount Pumori.
   Chris Leibindgut, 27, of Wasilla, Alaska, has been missing since
April 18, the day he and expedition leader John Tuckey reached the
top of the mountain.
   ``Either Chris fell to death or froze or both,'' said Tuckey, of
Girdwood, Alaska. ``We could not find his body. So we presume ...
he has got to be dead right now.''
   According to Tuckey, Leibindgut disappeared at 6:40 p.m., two
hours after the two had reached the summit, at a place about 148
feet below the highest point.
   ``At the summit, Chris complained of dizziness and was acting
confused,'' he said. ``So we descended a short way below the
summit.''
   ``It became dark ... (and) very windy,'' he continued. ``So, I
started to dig a snow cave for us in preparation for spending the
night there. While I was digging, Chris wandered off and walked
away. I have not seen him since then.''
   Tuckey, 37, said he spent the night alone in the snow cave and
the next day descended the east ridge of the mountain.
   On April 11, the two had started climbing the southern ridge of
the peak, accompanied by Doug White, 27, of Walnut Creek, Calif.,
and Randy Kopal, 38, of Eldorado Springs, Colo. The group left
their base camp at the 17,318-foot level without the help of Sherpa
guides, setting up their first camp the same day and a second camp
the following day. White and Kopal then returned to base camp.
   ``They were moving slowly,'' Tuckey said. ``We thought we would
have a better chance of success if we moved faster. So, Chris and I
continued. We went in Alpine style _ no fixed ropes even. That is
why we had to go fast.''
   During the climb, Tuckey and Leigindgut spent some nights in
snow caves and one night in the open without shelter.
   Tuckey said the toes on his right foot became frostbitten during
the climb but he believed they would be OK.
</TEXT>
