<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ParalyzedDog     04-26 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paralyzed Dog,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paralyzed Labrador Raises $108 For March Of Dimes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAMESTOWN, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black Labrador retriever whose hind
legs are paralyzed won a bicycle as the top fund-raiser in a March
of Dimes walk-a-thon.
   The dog, named Remy, raised $108 in pledges by completing an
eight-mile route as part of the local March of Dimes chapter's Walk
America fund-raising effort. A specially built cart holds the dog's
crippled hind legs so that he can propel himself with his front
legs.
   ``It's amazing how fast he is,'' said Julianne Lee, a veterinary
technician at the Prairie Veterinary Hospital in Jamestown.
   Remy was an inspiration for the 34 participants in Sunday's
walk, some of whom were in wheelchairs, said Yvonne Hanzal, a state
human services worker.
   The hospital has cared for Remy since a hunter accidentally shot
him in the spine nearly a year ago.
   ``He got his cart last summer, and he learned quickly how to use
it,'' Ms. Lee said. ``He doesn't scratch the woodwork anymore, and
pulls himself up when he comes to a sidewalk or door sill. If he
gets stuck in a corner or a deep pile of snow, he just backs
himself out.''
   Officials are still discussing what to do with the 10-speed
bicycle that was offered as a prize for the top fund-raiser, Ms.
Lee said. It may be traded for another model that would be better
suited for a handicapped person, or auctioned to raise money for
the March of Dimes, she said.
   While Remy won't get the bike, the dog thoroughly enjoyed the
walk, Ms. Lee said.
   ``He has an extremely pleasant personality,'' she said. ``This
was a big day for him. He really enjoys being around people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
