<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PornoBankruptcy     04-26 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Porno Bankruptcy,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Of Big Three In Porno Flicks Goes Under</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Essex Video, once one of the nation's biggest
makers of hard-core adult films, has filed for bankruptcy while its
president faces federal charges.
   Essex, based in the suburban San Fernando Valley, claimed in an
April 5 bankruptcy filing that it has no assets and more than 100
creditors, including film director John Derek, husband of actress
Bo Derek. Essex owes Derek $6,500 in royalties from a film titled
``Love You'' that he made in the mid 1970s.
   What happened to Essex's films and licenses is a mystery.
   Former Essex salesman Eugene Marino has started a new adult
video company called Essex West, which took over Essex's
headquarters and has thousands of videocassettes in its warehouse.
   But Marino insists Essex West has no connection to Essex.
   ``I have a silent partner,'' he said, refusing to identify that
person.
   Essex, along with Caballero Home Video and Video Company of
America, also both based in the San Fernando Valley, were at one
time considered the Big Three in the pornographic film industry,
said Sgt. Don Smith of the police department's vice unit.
   The adult film industry generated $750 million in sales in the
Los Angeles area alone last year, Smith said.
   But Essex, which reportedly had annual sales of $40 million just
a few years ago, was driven into financial trouble by high
production costs, said Jared Rutter, editor of the trade
publication Film World Reports.
   ``Essex put too much money into production,'' said Rutter,
adding that it also had its share of flop movies.
   The company's president, Jeff Steinman, is to appear Thursday in
federal court in Memphis, Tenn., on 16 counts of shipping obscene
materials through United Parcel Service.
   The Justice Department alleges that since 1982 Steinman was
shipping what the agency described as obscene videos across state
lines, a federal offense.
   Steinman, 30, was quoted in Tuesday's editions of the Los
Angeles Times as saying he would plead guilty to the charges.
However, he denied that Essex produced pornographic films, a
violation of California's pandering laws if the movies are made in
the state.
   Essex was founded in Hollywood in the late 1960s by Colombian
immigrant Joe Steinman, who bought the rights to adult films and
sold copies to theaters nationwide. He retired in 1979, turning
over the business to his son Jeff.
   The company quickly expanded into the home video market in the
late 1970s when videocasette recorders became popular, transferring
its huge film library to tape.
   But intense competition drove the price of videos down, Marino
said.
   ``Today there are tapes selling for $5 that were selling for $42
two years ago,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
