<2ND_LINE>AM-Anderson Brawl,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Chief Says Newspaper Editor Slugged Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POINT ARENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities are investigating
allegations that a newspaper editor decked Mendocino County's top
school official with a single punch during a meeting of the school
board.
   Bruce Anderson, editor and publisher of the Anderson Valley
Advertiser, left Monday night's meeting 20 minutes before sheriff's
deputies arrived to take a complaint from School Superintendent Jim
Spence.
   Anderson, reached later by the Santa Rosa Press Democrat,
conceded he punched Spence and said he ``felt very stupid and very
embarrassed.''
   Witnesses told the newspaper the blow came after Spence called
Anderson ``a third-rate McCarthyite.''
   Spence, 46, signed an assault and battery complaint and the case
will be submitted to the district attorney, said Sheriff's Lt.
Larry Gander.
   Anderson, 48, was recently in the news over a hoax interview he
printed in his 2,500-circulation weekly, published in Boonville.
   The fake interview published earlier this year quoted Rep.
Douglas Bosco as calling his constituents ``a bunch of easily
stirred-up know-nothing malcontents who couldn't care less about
anything other than their beautiful ocean and where their next
joint is coming from.''
