<DOCNO> AP880426-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Demjanjuk-Europe     04-26 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Demjanjuk-Europe,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Papers Comment on Demjanjuk Death Sentence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Demjanjuk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of Britain's leading newspapers on Tuesday
appealed to Israel to spare the life of John Demjanjuk, sentenced
to hang for war crimes committed as concentration camp guard ``Ivan
the Terrible.''
   But two Swiss papers took the opposite line, saying the sentence
was justified given the thousands of Jewish deaths ascribed to
Demjanjuk.
   Some European papers highlighted the cheers and singing that
broke out in the public gallery when the judges announced the
sentence.
   ``Singing and insults greet Demjanjuk death sentence,''
headlined the Independent in London. Its competitor, The Times,
said: ``Cheers and dancing at end of `Ivan' trial.''
   The conservative Times editorialized that the death penalty
``arouses misgivings,'' but said that since ``the sentence appeared
to be little more than a formality, it is to the credit of the
judges that they deliberated for three hours before pronouncing
sentence.''
   It added: ``If the Israeli authorities could see their way to
commuting the death sentence, this would further mark the emergence
of Israel as the civilized state it aspires to be. There could be
few more appropriate ways in which Israel could mark the 40th
anniversary of its foundation.''
   The conservative Daily Telegraph commented that in Israel ``the
trials of war criminals assist an explicitly political and
propagandist purpose: to remind the world until the end of time of
the nature of the Holocaust, and what was done to the Jewish
people.''
   It added: ``Yet even for Israel, in this 40th year of its
existence, there must come a moment when it is time to look
forward; not to forget the Holocaust, but to cauterize its terrible
wounds.''
   The Telegraph said: ``If Israel is convinced of his guilt then
let him rot in his cell.'' But it claimed the evidence against
Demjanjuk was flawed, and executing him ``could conceivably do as
much harm to the Jewish nation today as `Ivan the Terrible' did to
individual Jews.''
   In Switzerland, the independent Basler Zeitung commented:
``Given the atrocities he has been convicted of, the sentence is of
secondary importance. No punishment can render justice in his
case.''
   The conservative Neue Zurcher Zeitung agreed, saying: ``One
could argue that it would be wiser to sentence a person, whose
identity is only 99 percent sure, to life imprisonment instead of
to death. But there is no third between guilt and innocence ... and
the crimes committed ... justify the sentence imposed according to
Israeli law.''
   Alfred Emmerlich, a legal expert with West Germany's opposition
Social Democratic Party, told the General Anzeiger newspaper in
Bonn that his party condemns the death penalty in general,
including in Israel.
   ``There is always the possibility of a mistake, and there is no
way to correct such a mistake when the death penalty has been
carried out.''
   In the Netherlands, Rabbi Avraham Soetendorp said he welcomed
the death sentence as a symbol but did not want it carried out.
   ``I face a certain conflict of conscience because I am opposed
to capital punishment,'' he told The Associated Press.
   Soetendorp, a prominent Dutch lobbyist for Jewish causes, said
Demjanjuk should be jailed for life.
   ``It's a good thing the trial's finally over ... and that it's
become clear that he (Demjanjuk) really is Ivan the Terrible,'' he
said.
   Reporting from Jerusalem for Le Figaro of Paris, Rene Bauduc
wrote that if Demjanjuk lost his appeal to the Israeli Supreme
Court, he would hang, ``carrying away with him the memory of the
horrors of an epoch, but also the doubts of all those who, looking
at this man of peaceful appearance, have difficulty believing he
could have committed such crimes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
