<DOCNO> AP880426-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-UtahCaucuses 1stLd-Writethru a0518 04-26 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Utah Caucuses, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0518,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Sweeps to Utah Victory With 71 Percent Of Vote</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with later figures in 2nd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis swept to an easy victory
over Jesse Jackson in the Utah presidential caucuses, preparing for
today's delegate-rich Pennsylvania primary by collecting a large
majority of Utah's 23 Democratic delegates.
   Unofficial results with 94 percent of the vote counted in Monday
night's caucuses showed Dukakis with 7,550 votes, or 71 percent,
compared with 1,682, or 16 percent, for Jackson. Some 1,231 voters,
or 11 percent, were uncommitted.
   Those percentages would leave Dukakis with 19 Utah delegates to
the Democratic National Convention and Jackson with four.
   ``We're really happy,'' said Dukakis state campaign coordinator
Gary Knoblock. ``It's a long way from home to be winning by this
kind of margin. We've been slowly climbing in the West, but this
took a quantum leap.''
   Complete statewide returns were not expected until late today.
   Campaign aides touted the victory as another sign that Dukakis
had momentum going into today's Pennsylvania primary, where 178
delegates are at stake and the Massachusetts governor has been
heavily favored in polls.
   Jackson supporters, meanwhile, said they were pleased to have
come away with any delegates from a state where 93 percent of the
population is white and less than 1 percent is black. A candidate
must get at least 15 percent of the vote to qualify for a share of
the delegates.
   ``The votes that came in for Jackson were certainly not
all-inclusive minority votes. I feel very good about what we've
done,'' said Jackson state chairman Marvin Davis.
   In 1984, Jackson won only 4 percent of the vote here.
   Counting the three ``super delegates'' who have endorsed him,
Dukakis' total Utah count would be 22 delegates. National
Committeewoman Norma Matheson, Rep. Wayne Owens and state party
Chairman Randy Horiuchi have endorsed Dukakis, while National
Committeeman and former Gov. Calvin Rampton and Elizabeth Willey
remain uncommitted.
   Dukakis also had the endorsement in the caucuses of former
Democratic Gov. Scott Matheson.
   Of the 23 delegates apportioned in Monday night's binding
balloting, 20 will be elected at the state convention in June, and
three will be elected separately by the state party's central
committee.
   In addition to the presidential poll, those attending the
caucuses elected delegates to county conventions next month and
voted for precinct captains.
   Republicans had planned a non-binding presidential preference
vote, but abandoned the idea after Vice President George Bush
virtually locked up the GOP nomination. Instead, Republicans voted
on their preference for vice president and whether they favor
holding a western regional primary in 1992 similar to the South's
``Super Tuesday'' this year.
   Results of the Republican balloting will not be available for
several days.
   Horiuchi said the turnout, estimated at more than 10,000, was
considerably better than 1984, when only 6,000 to 7,000 attended
what were then called mass meetings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
