<DOCNO> AP880426-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-OnToOhio Bjt   04-26 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-On To Ohio, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Leads in Ohio and Indiana; Jackson Counts on District of
Columbia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALE LEACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic presidential candidates
have left behind Pennsylvania but the big industry problems that
plague that state follow the campaign into the next round of
primaries in Ohio and Indiana.
   Front-runner Michael Dukakis held solid leads over Jesse Jackson
in polls of voter sentiment leading up to next Tuesday's primaries
in those Midwestern states.
   However, the Jackson forces were hoping their candidate would be
helped in Ohio by the efforts of Gerald Austin, his campaign
manager who helped steer the successful campaigns of Gov. Richard
Celeste in 1982 and 1986.
   The District of Columbia also holds its primary next Tuesday,
and Mayor Marion Barry Jr. predicts Jackson could win as much as 70
percent of the Democratic vote in the city that gave Jackson one of
his few 1984 victories.
   In Ohio, Dukakis and Jackson were expected to keep hitting hard
at such issues as plant closings and a need for government to help
create new jobs. Jackson's first appearance in the state was at a
steel plant.
   Dukakis, already well ahead of Jackson in the delegate count,
could add to the increasing sense of inevitability about his
nomination if he could win the lion's share of the 159 Democratic
delegates at stake in Ohio and the 79 in Indiana.
   But Jackson was beginning a full week of campaigning in Ohio on
Tuesday, and Dukakis' aides were speaking as if they were taking
nothing for granted.
   ``We've got a tough job cut out for us in Ohio,'' said Anne
Drake, director of Dukakis' Ohio campaign. ``I don't think there is
any way to possibly downplay the effect that Jerry Austin will have
on Ohio's primary.''
   Linda Brown, a Jackson spokeswoman, agreed, saying, ``It's
certainly an asset for us because of Jerry's visibility here in the
Ohio area and his track record with past Ohio campaigns.''
   Still, state Rep. C.J. McLin of Dayton, Jackson's Ohio campaign
chairman, said, ``I'm not fooling myself. It's going to be
difficult. But I still think we have a chance.''
   A Gallup Poll conducted April 8-10 showed Dukakis leading
Jackson in Ohio, 50 percent to 23 percent.
   Dukakis also holds a comfortable lead in most recent polls in
Indiana. An Indianapolis Star survey taken April 17-19 showed him
favored by 49 percent to 21 percent for Jackson.
   Ohio Democratic leaders have generally taken no stands on the
race _ unlike four years ago when most endorsed Walter Mondale,
only to see Gary Hart win a narrow victory in the primary.
   Dukakis' name will appear on ballots throughout Ohio. But
Jackson failed to qualify delegate slates in three of the state's
21 congressional districts: two largely rural districts with few
black voters and a district west of Cleveland.
   Although Democrats hold both U.S. Senate seats and virtually
every statewide office in Ohio, the state has been friendly
territory for Ronald Reagan. In 1984, Reagan won the state with 59
percent of the vote.
   Herbert B. Asher, an Ohio State University political science
professor, said, ``I think two major things the candidates need to
keep in mind are that the state really has eight major media
markets. It is a difficult state to campaign in because there is no
single dominant area.
   ``I think the other thing that really is new to the Democrats is
that it finally is down to a two-person contest. ... That means,
then, that Dukakis and Jackson are campaigning against each other.''
   In the Republican primary, 88 delegates are up for grabs in Ohio
and 30 in Indiana, most of them expected to move into Vice
President George Bush's column as he smoothly sails toward the GOP
convention.
   In the District of Columbia, 11 delegates will be directly
chosen in the Democratic primary, a contest that Jackson has
virtually nailed down in the heavily black city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
