<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief 1stLd-Writethru a0478 04-26 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0478,570</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf last item to CORRECT ``800'' numbers, which
were transposed by company.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brother of a U.S. serviceman who died
eight years ago in Iran in a mission to rescue 52 American hostages
remembered the failed attempt with pride, not pain.
   ``Time is a great healer of pain,'' Air Force Capt. Richard
Holmes said Monday at a ceremony honoring the eight men who died in
the Iranian desert during the abortive rescue mission on April 25,
1980.
   ``Those feeling of sorrow have been replaced with feelings of
pride,'' said Holmes, the brother of Cpl. George Holmes Jr. of Pine
Bluff, Ark.
   The eight died when a helicopter collided with a transport plane
after officials decided to abandon the mission before entering
Tehran. The hostages were freed in January 1981 after 444 days in
captivity.
   Army Secretary John O. Marsh Jr., former hostages Bruce Laingen
and Air Force Col. David Roeder were among those attending the
30-minute ceremony, held at Arlington National Cemetery.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional watchdog agency says the Air
Force has provided billions of dollars worth of parts and supplies
to defense contractors without adequate control over how the
material is used.
   The General Accounting Office, in a report issued Monday,
estimated Air Force contractors were given more than $6 billion in
``government furnished material'' during 1986, the most recent year
for which complete statistics are available.
   That material covers an enormous range of items, from major
parts for airplanes and other equipment down to such items as
brooms, paint and bolts.
   Normally, the materials are supposed to be provided by
contractors, but the Pentagon has the option of supplying the
materials when it is in the government's best interest.
   The GAO said the service should tighten up its administrative
procedures to avoid the problem.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven years after it was signed as a teaty, a
bill providing for the prompt return of children abducted from a
parent and taken to another country has won final approval by the
House.
   The measure, approved on Monday by voice vote, would implement
an international treaty on child abduction that the United States
signed in 1981 and the Senate approved five years later.
   The House, which had passed an almost identical bill March 28,
approved on Monday a slightly different Senate version giving
jurisdiction over international child abduction cases to both state
and federal courts.
   The measure is intended to remove difficult, time-consuming
legal issues involved in returning children abducted to another
country, often by the other parent, or helping foreign parents
recover children wrongfully taken to the United States.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Baby Swing Replacements Being Offered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The manufacturer of baby swings that could
collapse is offering free replacements.
   Involved are 6,562 wooden baby swings sold under the Sears and
Hedstrom brand names. They were manufactured by Hedstrom Corp. of
Bedford, Pa., between April and December 1987, the Consumer Product
Safety Commission announced Monday.
   According to the agency, four incidents have been reported in
which the swings collapsed because the glue failed to hold the
joints between the slats and frame.
   The models being replaced are Hedstrom brand 4-798 and Sears
brand 512.70907, the commission said.
   Consumers should stop using the swing and return it to the place
of purchase for replacement. Those needing more information can
call Hedstrom at 1-800-233-3271. Pennsylvania residents should call
1-800-424-9034.
