<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Philippines     04-26 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Philippines,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Protests Proposed Philippine Anti-Nuclear Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has expressed concern to the
Philippine government and its congress regarding proposed
legislation that would ban nuclear weapons in the Philippines, the
State Department said Tuesday.
   The legislation, on which debate began in Manila this week,
would prohibit nuclear weapons at the two major U.S. military bases
in the Philippines and would ban port calls by U.S. warships and
planes carrying such arms.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the United States
had told the Philippines that the bill ``would permit no
flexibility on nuclear matters and would be incompatible'' with
U.S. policy.
   That policy prohibits the United States from revealing whether
its ships and planes are carrying nuclear weapons.
   Redman declined to further discuss the Philippine legislation,
saying it was still in its early stages. The bill is expected to
pass the 23-member Senate, but would face strong opposition in the
200-member lower house.
   The United States has expressed strong opposition to such bans
in other countries. It expelled New Zealand from a Pacific defense
alliance with Australia after New Zealand adopted a nuclear ban,
and has protested similar action being considered in Denmark.
</TEXT>
