<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PrimaryRdp Bjt 2Takes 04-26 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primary Rdp, Bjt, 2 Takes, 470-1,020</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Ready To Go Over The Top; Dukakis Hopes to Bolster
Front-Runner Status</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Polls close at 8 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis met Jesse Jackson in the
peaceful Pennsylvania primary on Tuesday as he bid to lengthen his
lead in convention delegates and certify his status as Democratic
presidential front-runner. George Bush sought the final delegates
needed to clinch the Republican nomination.
   Dukakis led Jackson by far in the pre-election polls after a
week-long campaign that looked and sounded more like a mutual
admiration society than the typical 1988 Democratic primary brawl.
   Aides hoped the Massachusetts governor would win the popular
vote impressively and claim as many as 150 of the 178 Democratic
National Convention delegates at stake.
   Jackson had scant hopes for a popular vote victory in
Pennsylvania, and already was looking ahead to next week's
primaries in the District of Columbia, Indiana and Ohio. His
chances in the delegate hunt were little better, since his campaign
failed to file a complete slate of delegate candidates around the
state.
   Dukakis looked to the Pennsylvania returns as the final count
was tallied from his victory in Utah's Monday night caucuses. The
New Englander was ahead for 19 of 23 delegates at stake.
   Dukakis began the day with 1,095.15 delegates, to 840.1 for
Jackson. It takes 2,081 to gain the nomination at the Democratic
National Convention in July in Atlanta.
   Bush had 1,081 of the 1,139 needed to nominate. Former
television evangelist Pat Robertson, who has ceased active
campaigning, had 31.
   ``We're putting Bush over the top,'' Pennsylvania State Chairman
Earl Baker said even before the polls closed. ``We're going to do
the same thing in November,'' he added.
   Bush's nomination has been all but assurred since he routed his
Republican rivals across the South on Super Tuesday last month, and
his aides have been working for weeks on their strategy for the GOP
convention in New Orleans and for the fall campaign against the
Democrats.
   The vice president has been running virtually uncontested for
weeks, winning primaries and caucuses as they rolled by on the
calendar and methodically claiming virtually all of the delegates
available.
   He needed to win only 58 of the 78 Pennsylvania delegates at
stake to amass a nominating majority in The Associated Press count.
   In contrast, Dukakis didn't take on the air of prohibitive
front-runner until a week ago, when he scored a decisive victory in
the New York primary and knocked Sen. Albert Gore Jr. from the race.
   That left only himself and Jackson as active candidates in the
once-crowded Democratic race, and his aides said they hoped for a
string of victories that would yield enough delegates to claim the
nomination by the time the primary season ends on June 7.
</TEXT>
