<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PrimaryRdp 1stAdd a0671 04-26 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primary Rdp, 1st Add, a0671,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PHILADELPHIA: June 7.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis and Jackson debated twice in their Pennsylvania primary
campaign, treating one another with exceptional good humor while
attacking Bush and the Reagan administration.
   The Democratic rivals held their hands aloft like prizefighters
in a gesture of unity at one debate and proceeded to joke about the
vice presidential slot on the ticket _ the No. 1 topic on the minds
of Democrats everywhere.
   ``Are you interested?'' Dukakis asked Jackson in a soft,
back-stage voice.
   Dukakis even held a private meeting during the week with some of
Jackson's black supporters in Pennsylvania _ with his rival's
advance knowledge and approval.
   Said Jackson: ``However it goes, when it's all said and done ...
we will come out (of the convention) as a unit to send the
Reagan-Bush forces back to private life.''
   Dukakis also began pointing his attack toward the Republicans
during the week, saying it would be a ``tragedy'' if Reagan vetoed
a trade bill over a provision requiring companies to give notice
before closing manufacturing facilities.
   Jackson got entangled the last two days of the campaign in a
flap over how to deal with terrorists, particularly in situations
where they were holding Americans hostage.
   In a speech Sunday in Washington, D.C., Jackson took issue with
Dukakis' hard-line statements opposed to negotiations with
terrorists.
   ``I disagree with that,'' said Jackson. ``If I could get the
hostages out, I'd do it.''
   The next day he was peppered with questions about whether he was
implying he would make concessions to hostage-takers.
   He rejected what he called ``material concessions,'' such as
selling arms. But he added, ``I choose negotiation over blind
bloody confrontation'' and said he would consider allowing
terrorists safe passage in exchange for release of hostages.
   He also said, ``If we are going to deter terrorism we are going
to have to address the underlying caucses of terrorism. Terrorism
does not emerge out of the blue.''
   Bush promised to continue ``showing the flag'' in the remainder
of the primary season, despite his certain nonmination, and he had
a feisty rejoinder when hecklers dogged him at one stop in
Pennsylvania.
   ``I'm glad to see the Jackson supporters here, or maybe the Mike
Dukakis supporters,'' he said. ``I welcome then in debate, and I
will welcome taking on their ticket and we will beat them in the
fall.''
   Bush's aides said the vice president might soon begin focusing
his criticism more specifically on Dukakis and less on Democrats in
general. Campaign manager Lee Atwater provided a preview when he
described the Democratic front-runner as a ``Northern fried Jimmy
Carter,'' the man turned out of office in 1980 by the Reagan-Bush
ticket.
   Bush's spokesman also said the vice president intends to summon
Republican governors and experts to his home in Kennebunkport,
Maine for a week-long brainstorming session in June to help shape
the foreign policy and economic issues for the fall campaign.
</TEXT>
