<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1424EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SatellitesLaunch     04-26 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Satellites Launch,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Satellites Launched in Brilliant Display Reach Polar Orbit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Navy navigational
satellites that put on a spectacular light show after launch
reached their planned circular polar orbit Tuesday, officials at
this coastal base said.
   A NASA consultant at Vandenberg, Don Forney, said the launch
aboard a Scout rocket Monday evening went ``by the numbers.''
   Forney said solar panels that charge the batteries powering the
satellite were deployed on one of the satellites shortly after it
reached orbit. The spare satellite will be stored in orbit until
needed. The functional satellite will be operational in 10 days.
   The OSCAR satellites, each weighing 131 pounds, are used as a
navigational system for submarines and commercial shipping, as well
as in oil and mineral deposit work.
   Their 6:57 p.m. launch left an exhaust contrail clearly visible
from Malibu, about 100 miles to the south.
   The contrail was the result of a ``twilight phenomenon,'' said
Master Sgt. Bruce Zielsdorf, a Vandenberg spokesman.
   ``It is the result of spent fuel from the booster rocket as it
travels through the upper atmosphere. The fuel combines with water
droplets that crystallize,'' he said.
   ``Those crystals are struck by high-altitude sunlight,'' he
added. ``It may be dark on Earth, but there's still sunlight above.
It causes an aurora borealis effect and is usually visible for 15
to 20 minutes.''
   The contrail, which reflected shades of blue and green over
Orange County, resembled a giant pretzel in that area after it was
blown by high-altitude winds.
</TEXT>
