<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LehderTrial     04-26 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Trial,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arguments Continue Over Tapes Of Colombian Interview</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Accused drug kingpin Carlos Lehder
Rivas virtually admitted his guilt in radio and television
interviews given in 1983 and 1985, federal prosecutors claimed
Tuesday as they argued for the interviews to be presented at his
trial.
   But defense attorney Jose Quinon, arguing against allowing the
jury to see and hear the tapes, claimed that Lehder, 38, was being
tried for his political views instead of the 11-count indictment.
   The indictment alleges Lehder and co-defendant Jack Reed
conspired to smuggle some 3.3 tons of cocaine into the United
States from Colombia.
   Defense and prosecution attorneys went line-by-line over
transcripts of a radio interview and a television interview Lehder
gave in late June 1983, before he was indicted in U.S. courts; and
a jungle television interview given in February 1985, when Lehder
was a fugitive on the charges for which he is now being tried.
   The jury was excused during the arguments.
   ``The entire statement amounts to a confession,'' said U.S.
Attorney Robert W. Merkle, when discussing a section of the radio
transcript that dealt with Lehder's activities on the island of
Norman's Cay in the Bahamas.
   ``This is his manifesto,'' said Merkle, who added that Lehder
equated his cocaine smuggling with the liquor smuggling in the
United States during the Prohibition era.
   ``This is a very eloquent statement ... that Mr. Lehder is in
fact guilty,'' said Merkle, after reviewing the transcript of the
audio tape.
   Quinon charged that certain parts of the tapes are highly
prejudicial and should not be admitted into evidence.
   ``This has become a political trial, nothing more, nothing
less,'' said Quinon.
   ``This is not a political trial. This is not a political
crime,'' answered Merkle, who added that Lehder smuggled drugs to
further his political views.
   It now appears that the prosecution may rest its case on
Thursday. U.S. District Judge Howell W. Melton said he may recess
most of Wednesday to allow him to determine whether the tapes,
which are in Spanish, can be admitted into evidence.
   Lehder is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a
continuing criminal enterprise. Reed, 57, of San Pedro, Calif., is
charged only with being a member of the smuggling conspiracy.
</TEXT>
