<DOCNO> AP880426-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Denmark     04-26 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Denmark,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Danes Told to Choose Between Nuclear Ban and NATO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY GERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political leaders are telling Danes
to choose in upcoming elections between NATO allies and the
country's longstanding ban on nuclear weapons.
   Prime Minister Poul Schlueter, a NATO backer, called the
parliamentary elections for May 10, urging voters to ``take a
stand'' in favor of the Western military alliance.
   The sudden storm over Denmark's role in the 16-nation alliance
came as a surprise to many voters. The peacetime ban on nuclear
weapons has been in effect for three decades, and a shaky coalition
government has been struggling with economic, not military issues.
   Indeed, some voters say economic troubles remain the chief issue.
   ``It's not just a question about nuclear weapons but about the
way the government runs society,'' said Susane Nielsen, a
conservative voter who works in a health insurance office. ``We
have to face these economic problems.''
   The unexpected showdown began April 14 when the leftist
opposition pushed through a parliamentary resolution intended to
strengthen the country's ban on peacetime nuclear weapons.
   The move, which has been delayed pending the election, requires
the government to notify individual warships of the country's ban.
Parliamentary negotiators have not decided if the ships would then
have to respond.
   Until now, Denmark has simply stated its policy to one and all.
   Some allies reacted sharply to the latest proposal, warning it
jeopardizes Denmark's participation in NATO. A meeting of NATO's
Nuclear Planning Group was rescheduled from Denmark to Belgium.
Britain called off naval maneuvers in Denmark.
   Some Danes have reacted with resentment to the foreign
pressures. ``Has the Danes' national pride deteriorated so much
that we will bow to pressure from abroad?'' the left-leaning
newspaper Information asked in a front-page editorial.
   ``The question is the central one in the current debate, and in
that sense, the election is the most important since World War II.''
   Of course, it did not help matters when Reagan administration
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater joked to reporters that ``Danish means
breakfast to me.''
   National radio played the English-language tape on the air, an
unusual step. ``Reagan Staff Demonstrates its Knowledge of
Denmark,'' said a sarcastic headline in the liberal Politiken
newspaper. Fitzwater later apologized.
   The confrontation comes at a politically unstable time for this
country of 5 million people. The last general election in September
left Schlueter's center-right coalition in command of just 70 of
parliament's 179 votes _ just enough to command a majority on
economic matters.
   Polls suggest that Danes favor NATO membership. A recently
published poll by the Observa organization showed that 66 percent
of Danes favor staying in NATO and just 16 percent oppose it, the
most lopsided margin in years. A Gallup poll said Danes favor
membership 59 percent to 16 percent.
   Another survey, published in the Boersen business newspaper,
showed that 46 percent of Danes believed it was reasonable to ask
NATO ships to guarantee they carry no nuclear arms, 36 percent did
not and 18 percent were undecided. The responses crossed political
lines.
   Further strains in relations between Denmark and its allies
could carry strategic implications. Denmark's low-lying peninsula
and islands command approaches to the Baltic Sea, and NATO
strategists envision it as a key supply point in case of invasion
from the east.
   The dispute follows years of contention over Denmark's declining
defense spending, which amounts to 2 percent of its gross national
product, among the lowest in the alliance.
   However, random interviews with window shoppers along Stroeget,
a pedestrian street in Copenhagen, suggest many people are more
worried about the country's weak economy than its military role.
   Unemployment is running at 9.7 percent, and the national debt
has reached $43 billion.
   Joergen Thy, editor and writer for a computer magazine, said he
planned to vote against the government because ``I don't think they
have achieved much.''
   He calls the nuclear question `` a joke.'' ``That's not the
issue,'' he says.
   Indeed, Danish elections have focused mainly on economic issues
since World War II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
