<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Bulgaria     04-26 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Bulgaria,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Discusses Human Rights, Economy With Bulgarian Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, who has
sought to improve relations with Eastern Europe, discussed human
rights and economic issues Tuesday with the highest-ranking
Bulgarian official to visit Washington since World War II.
   Andrei Lukanov, minister of foreign economic relations, outlined
Bulgarian plans to improve its economy and told Shultz his country
was eager to increase trade with the United States through joint
ventures, a State Department official said.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the talks
were ``cordial, relaxed and businesslike.''
   Shultz reminded Lukanov of the U.S. concerns about Bulgarian
treatment of its Turkish minority, the official said. The State
Department, Amnesty International and others have accused Bulgaria
of seeking to force assimilation on 900,000 people of Turkish
origin.
   Under a 1975 law, Bulgaria and other Soviet allies remain
ineligible for special U.S. tariff reductions _ most favored nation
status _ as long as their emigration policies are deemed by the
United States to be restrictive.
   In practice, a nation's entire human rights policies are
scrutinized before a decision is made on most favored nation status.
   Bulgaria has sought to join Poland, Hungary and Romania as
Soviet-bloc countries eligible for the benefits, but the request
has been denied. The State Department official said the issue was
not raised with Lukanov, who is the first Bulgarian politburo
member to visit Washington since Bulgaria became a communist
country following World War II.
   ``This was basically an overview of relations, rather than a
detailed discussion of economic issues,'' the official said.
   Bulgaria traditionally has taken its economic and foreign policy
cues from the Soviet Union and its recent moves to improve
efficiency and add marketplace approaches to the economy have
mirrored similar efforts by Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Like the Soviet Union, Bulgaria also has sought to increase the
amount of high technology it is permitted to buy in the United
States.
   Lukanov's visit to the United States will include a trip to the
northern California region known as Silicon Valley because of its
numerous high-tech industries and to Los Angeles, Chicago and New
York.
   In recent years, the Reagan administration has sought to improve
its diplomatic relations with Soviet bloc coun the past three years.
</TEXT>
