<2ND_LINE>PM-Jagger, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0681,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jury Clears Mick Jagger Of Stealing Reggae Musician's Song</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with details, reax, and editing to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal court jury found today that
Mick Jagger did not steal an unknown reggae musician's song and
turn it into his 1985 hit, ``Just Another Night.''
   Fans in the courtroom broke into applause after the verdict, and
Jagger said he planned to celebrate by having a beer with his
lawyers.
   ``My reputation is really cleared. If you're well-known, people
stand up and take shots at you. It's one of those things in a
litigious society,'' Jagger told reporters.
   The six-person civil panel had listened to tapes of both
Jagger's song and one written in 1979 by Patrick Alley, 36, which
is also named ``Just Another Night.''
   ``I still believe and I know that's my song,'' said Alley, 36,
who had accused Jagger of copyright infringement.
   Shortly before issuing the verdict, jurors asked for a rereading
of the law on access. They were apparently trying to determine
whether Jagger could have heard or known about Alley's song prior
to writing his own.
   Alley's lawyers said Jagger made $6 million from the song, which
appeared on an album called ``She's the Boss.''
   Jagger, looking weary, had testified Monday, rebutting a
statement by Alley's attorneys that longtime collaborator Keith
Richards tended to write the music while Jagger handled the lyrics.
   Jagger was gracious to fans throughout the trial, but pushed
angrily through a mob as he left the courthouse Monday night.
Crowds waiting to see the rock legend broke a door at the small
courthouse, according to security officials.
   Two alternate jurors, dismissed when the jury began
deliberations, said they also would have found for Jagger.
   ``I think he did it independently,'' said Barbara Carroll of
Pelham, who found Jagger to be a ``gentleman. . . He's completely
different than what I thought from his videos.'' Her children,
ranging from 16 to 25, are fans.
</TEXT>
