<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WaterRationing     04-26 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Water Rationing,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>San Francisco Rationing Plan Would Limit Use And Raise Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An emergency water rationing plan under
consideration in the city would close down decorative public
fountains and prohibit restaurants from giving water to customers
unless they ask for it.
   The second phase of the proposal by the city's Water Department
would require each resident and business to pay a higher rate for
less water by the end of May.
   The conservation plan, which will be considered Thursday by the
Public Utilities Commission, would begin Sunday. It would allow
each home or business a water allocation based on a 25 percent
reduction of the amount of water it used in 1987.
   Washing down sidewalks or patios with drinking water would be
prohibited under the plan. Fountains, including those in Civic
Center, United Nations Plaza and the Villiancourt Fountain near the
Ferry Building, would be shut off.
   Washing a car with a hose would be prohibited unless the hose
has a shut-off valve.
   The increase, which has not yet been determined, would accompany
penalties for using more water than the allocation. The city will
also consider placing flow restrictors on water lines in homes or
businesses that do not cut use.
   Water rationing is necessary because of two dry years in a row,
water officials said. Last week's rains did little to increase
runoff from melting snow in the Tuolumne River watershed, where the
San Francisco area gets most of its drinking water. Runoff was 34
percent of normal as of Monday, officials said.
   San Francisco would be the second water system in the area to
impose rationing. The East Bay Municipal Utility District last week
adopted a flat daily allocation of 400 gallons for its 1.1 million
customers.
</TEXT>
