<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     04-26 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf Convoy Turns Back, Apparently Due to Bad Weather</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convoy of U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tankers
moved into the Persian Gulf on Tuesday for the first time since
last week's clash with Iran, but the vessels turned back,
reportedly because of bad weather.
   One source, an official close to the Kuwait Oil Tanker Co. which
owns the tankers, said another attempt to move the ships might come
within 24 hours.
   Shipping executives said a sandstorm reduced visibility in the
central gulf to less than two miles, thereby limiting the ability
of mine-hunting helicopters and Navy vessels to detect mines.
   They said that although two ``mine danger areas'' had been
cleared by American and other mine sweepers in recent days, there
still was too much risk in sending ships into the area without
adequate mine-hunting protection.
   A spokesman for the U.S. Central Command said he could provide
no information on any convoy activity. The United States
customarily does not confirm the movements until they have passed
specific danger points in the gulf.
   U.S. officials, speaking privately, earlier had conceded there
was growing concern over the freeze in convoy movements that
followed the mining of a U.S. navy frigate and the subsequent
U.S.-Iran skirmishes.
   The 3,700-ton guided missile frigate Samuel B. Roberts ran into
a mine on April 14. Ten crewmen were injured in the blast.
   The United States retaliated four days later with a series of
attacks on Iranian targets in the gulf. During the day, the U.S.
Navy sank or damaged six Iranian naval craft.
   After the Roberts incident, more than a dozen mines were found
and destroyed by U.S., British, Dutch, Belgian and Italian mine
hunters in that area. French warships destroyed mines in another
area 70 miles away.
   U.S. officials said they still were trying to identify the type
of missiles fired at the U.S. warships during the April 18 battles.
Officers aboard the ships identified them as Chinese-made
Silkworms, but military officials in Washington said that had not
been confirmed.
   British and French convoys were reported to have passed through
the ``mine danger area,'' but the source close to the Kuwaiti oil
firm said the Kuwaiti convoys would not move until U.S. and Kuwaiti
officials were satisfied that the mine and missile threat was under
control.
   The 11 Kuwaiti tankers, reflagged by the United States last year
for protection from Iranian attack, operate on a fairly tight
schedule in delivering petroleum cargoes to Kuwait's long-term
contract customers, mainly in Japan and Europe.
   A two-tanker convoy that had been scheduled to enter the gulf
April 15 was canceled, and four more ships arrived within days at
the convoy staging area off the United Arab Emirates port of Khor
Fakkan.
   One U.S. offcer called it an ``unprecedented traffic jam.''
   U.S. officials in Washington had denied last week that the
escort operations had been suspended.
   The ships at Khor Fakkan included the 401,283-ton supertanker
Bridgeton, which had been slated to make one of its infrequent
trips into the gulf since it was hit by a mine on the first convoy
last July 24.
   The others were the 46,723-ton Gas Queen, scheduled to move with
the Bridgeton, and the oil products carriers Townsend, 294,739
tons, the 81,283-ton Sea Isle City and the Chesapeake City and
Ocean City, both 79,999 tons.
   A seventh tanker, the 46,723-ton liquefied gas carrier Gas King,
was stranded at Kuwait, awaiting clearance to sail south.
</TEXT>
