<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Arafat     04-26 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arafat,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Departs, Leaving Aides to Work Out Alliance Against Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO leader Yasser Arafat left Syria on
Tuesday after agreeing with President Hafez Assad to work for a
strategic alliance against Israel and a U.S. Middle East peace plan.
   Arafat met with Assad on Monday to try to end a five-year feud
between two of the Arab world's most influential figures.
   Farouk Kaddoumi, head of the Palestine Liberation Organization's
political department, said Arafat would return to Damascus soon,
after ``the foundations for a common action'' had been laid in the
3{-hourt meeting with Assad.
   Kaddoumi also said that a summit meeting grouping Assad, Arafat,
Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid and Libyan leader Col. Moammar
Gadhafi probably would be held next month in either the Libyan or
Algerian capital.
   Arafat also met for one hour Tuesday with Vice President
Abdul-Halim Khaddam before leaving for Libya aboard a special
plane. He later told reporters his talks in Damascus were ``useful
and will have positive results on the Palestinian and Arab levels.''
   Arafat arrived in Syria on Sunday and visited the grave of
Khalil Wazir, Arafat's deputy who was gunned down April 16.
   The PLO chief was accompanied on Tuesday's flight to Libya by
Salah Khalaf, better known as Abu Iyad, his No. 2 man in Fatah, the
PLO's mainstream faction and Arafat's power base.
   Arafat left Kaddoumi and other aides behind to work out the
details of a new Syrian-PLO alliance.
   In an interview after Arafat's departure, Kaddoumi said Syria
and the PLO ``have agreed to work together in a joint struggle
against Israel and U.S. (Middle East peace) plans.''
   That was a reference to a peace plan presented by U.S. Secretary
of State George P. Shultz last March. Under the peace plan,
Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza Strip would be granted
limited self-rule.
   Palestinians in those territories have been rioting against the
Israeli occupation since Dec. 8.
   Both Syria and the PLO rejected the plan and insist on settling
the Middle East problem through an international peace conference
that would lead to the creation of a Palestinian state.
   Kaddoumi said there was ``complete harmony'' in the stands of
the PLO and Syria on this issue.
   He said ``the uprising in the occupied West Bank is our (Syrian
and PLO) first concern. We agree that all our efforts should focus
on bolstering the uprising and rallying support for it.''
   Kaddoumi, the PLO's chief diplomat, said Syria and the PLO have
worked out details of their new alliance before an extraordinary
Arab summit meeting tentatively set for early June in Algiers.
   He said both leaders hope they will go to the summit ``with
identical views on all issues, if not a common working paper.''
   Rafik al-Natsheh, another Fatah central committee member who
attended the talks in Damascus, said Syria and the PLO had solved
most of their problems.
</TEXT>
