<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CashMachine 1stLd-Writethru a0701 04-26 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cash Machine, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0701,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cash Machine Declares Bank Holiday _ Christmas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 13th pvs bgng `The most'' to estimate overall loss of
less than $5,000; adds new graf with industry estimate of how often
machines malfunction.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Your bank cash machine has gone berserk, giving
out $20 bills as if they were fivers, yet your receipt shows no
sign of overpayment.
   Do you:
   a.) Use the emergency telephone to alert the bank.
   b.) Take the money and run.
   c.) Call your friends to get down there, too.
   If you chose the first option, you are a rare breed of cat,
judging from an unintentional ethics experiment staged Sunday at a
Manhattan bank branch.
   Because some hapless employee loaded a canister of $20 bills
into the slot for $5 bills, the First Federal Savings and Loan
Association of Rochester's branch at First Avenue and 14th Street
launched an accidental exercise in income redistribution.
   Although the cash machine panel has a 24-hour telephone for
reporting problems outside bank hours, the response was not
overwhelming _ ``one or two calls,'' according to bank spokesman
Robert Nolan.
   Instead, a line of eager card holders quickly formed at the
machine.
   ``I called everybody I knew,'' a writer, who asked not to be
identified for fear of prosecution, told New York Newsday.
   An actor named Chris, who asked for $40 and received $160, was
amused by the range of reactions: ``One person let out a holler of
joy. Another barely raised his eyebrows and sneaked out. One woman
went into a tirade about how she's getting back at the bank for
money it owed her.''
   Nor did guilt apparently set in later. The bank received only
one call on Monday reporting Sunday's malfunction. ``I was really
surprised the gentleman called,'' admitted Amelia Saavedra, the
branch manager.
   The most a customer could ask for was $200 _ and get $800. Nolan
said that although the bank's audit was not finished, it appeared
the automated teller overpaid a total ``somewhat less than $5,000.''
   Nolan said the bank was not dismayed by its customers' eagerness
to profit from the foul-up. ``I wouldn't want to characterize them
all,'' he said of the customers. ``I think some individuals were
innocent recipients of the machine.''
   He said First Federal would learn the identities of those who
reaped windfalls, once it determined how much was lost and who was
making withdrawals during the time the machine was in the giving
mood.
   ``We'll be able to determine who requested what, and what they
really got,''' Nolan said, adding that customer accounts would be
automatically charged for the amount overpaid.
   The Manhattan district attorney's office said bank customers
might be subject to prosecution for larceny. But it was unclear
whether the bank would be able to prove that all the bills in the
$5 slot were really $20s.
   Bank cash machines in the city typically hold about $100,000,
according to banking industry experts. Overpayments like Sunday's
are said to be extremely rare.
   ``It's much more common for the reverse to happen _ a customer
is shortchanged,'' said John Love of Bank Network News, an industry
newsletter. ``But we estimate these kinds of problems only occur in
about one-twentieth of 1 percent of all (automated teller)
transactions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1705EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SovietVisitors     04-26 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Visitors,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Leave Mobile Without Sister-City Certificate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet delegation that came to Mobile
seeking a sister-city bond departed in frustration Tuesday after
their weeklong visit to the port city turned diplomatically chilly.
   Jay Higginbotham, who spearheaded the sister-city proposal after
a trip to the Soviet Union last year, said the Soviet mayor and two
city council members from Rostov-on-Don were ``hurt and
distraught'' by their rejection.
   But the visitors enjoyed their tour of the Gulf coast, said
Higginbotham, a librarian and archivist for the city who has
written a book on his travels in the Soviet Union titled ``Fast
train Russia.''
   Mobile Mayor Arthur Outlaw said at the outset he disapproved of
the proposed sister-city agreement and the proposal never received
a City Council vote. Thus, the proposal died without official
consideration Tuesday.
   ``I don't see what can be gained by relations between an
appointed government and an elected government that responds to the
will of the people,'' Outlaw said while attending a welcome
reception for the group last week.
   The visitors included Alexander Balashov, Mikhail Tupchenko,
Gennadi Zorenko, and translator Svetlana Khokhlova.
   In Washington, Quentin Crommelin Jr., the chief Republican
counsel of the U.S. Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said
members of the Rostov group were likely Soviet agents.
   ``It is well known to be standard operating procedure for all
Soviet delegations, of whatever type, to have at least one-third
KGB or GRU agents as members, both to prevent defection and to
gather intelligence,'' Crommelin told The Mobile Register.
   He also suggested that the sister-city link could be proposed to
gather military intelligence on the proposed Navy base at Mobile
and nearby Ingalls Shipyard at Pascagoula, Miss.
   ``That sounds absurd,'' Higginbotham said Tuesday.
   Higgenbotham was a member of a group of residents from Mobile
that visited the Soviet city last year and arranged for the
exchange. He said the Rostov officials ``came over trying to make a
good impression.''
   Higginbotham said Gov. Guy Hunt had declared the visitors
honorary citizens of Alabama. But he said they left thinking
something they had said or wore provoked the rejection by Mobile
officials.
   ``It was a little pitiful,'' Higginbotham said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
