<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Africa     04-26 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Africa,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Seeks to Focus New Attention on South Africa</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, seeking to spotlight southern
Africa in the presidential campaign, went to the State Department
Tuesday to discuss Mozambican rebel atrocities and to say South
Africa should be treated as a terrorist state.
   Jackson pointed to a new report by a State Department consultant
that said the rebels in Mozambique have killed 100,000 civilians
and engaged in systematic murder, beating, mutilation, rape,
looting, burnings and abductions.
   The Democratic presidential contender said South African support
for the rebels amounts to ``state-sponsored terrorism'' and the
United States should provide security to South Africa's neighbors.
   He met with top State Department officials, including Deputy
Secretary of State John Whitehead, for a briefing on the report,
which was compiled by a department consultant, Robert Gersony.
   Chester Crocker, assistant secretary of state for African
affairs, joined Jackson at a news conference afterward.
   Crocker said there is ``a pattern of continuing contact between
South Africa and Renamo,'' the rebel group, and he said South
Africa's involvement goes against a 1984 treaty it entered with
Mozambique.
   South Africa denies having supported the rebels since that time.
   Jackson used the Gersony report to underscore his call for a
change in U.S. policy toward South Africa and the ``frontline
states'' around it.
   He called on Democratic rival Michael Dukakis and Republican
George Bush to join him in calling South Africa a terrorist state.
   Jackson said Congress should pass legislation ``clarifying its
meaning of state-sponsored terrorism to specifically include South
Africa.''
   He also called for an increase in humanitarian aid to the
frontline states and for a congressional delegation to visit
Mozambique on a fact-finding mission.
   Jackson has repeatedly tried to make South Africa and the
frontline states a campaign issue, but other candidates have not
focused on it. He met Tuesday morning with some members of Congress
and frontline states' ambassadors to discuss the issue.
   Some conservative members of Congress have called for U.S. aid
to Renamo, which is trying to bring down Mozambique's Marxist-led
government, but the United States officially supports the
government.
