<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Grapefruit     04-26 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Grapefruit,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poison-Laced Grapefruit Spurs Nationwide Seizure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health officials on Tuesday began seizing all
grapefruit on sale in Italy after some pieces of fruit believed
imported from Israel were found laced with a powerful poison.
   The Health Ministry ordered the nationwide seizure of all
grapefruit on sale and and in warehouses after health officials in
the Lazio region, which includes Rome, reported that poisoned
grapefruit was found in a Rome supermarket.
   Italian news media said the grapefruit apparently was imported
from Israel, but officials said they could not immediately confirm
where the fruit originated.
   Last week, an organization that said it supported the
Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip claimed to have poisoned Israeli grapefruit on sale in Milan.
It called for a boycott of Israeli products.
   Laboratory checks at the time found no trace of poison.
   The claim was made by a caller to a Rome newspaper who said he
was speaking on behalf of the ``Organization of Metropolitan
Proletarians and Oppressed People,'' a group that was not known to
have existed.
   Of the 12 grapefruit on sale at the Rome supermarket, six were
found to have been injected by syringe with a bluish poison. The
substance, which was not identified, was so powerful that it killed
laboratory mice instantly.
   The University of Rome's poison center reported receiving calls
from three Rome residents who said they had eaten grapefruit with
blue marks on Monday or Tuesday.
   ``So far none of them has reported any ill effects,'' said
Professor Enrico Malizia, head of the department.
   Israeli-grown ``Jaffa'' grapefruit in cellophane wrappers is
sold widely in Italy.
   Israeli Embassy spokesman Avi Granot promised to cooperate with
Italian authorities to determine whether the grapefruit poisoning
was ``an isolated case, a gesture of a madman or a terrorist act.''
   ``It is certainly a criminal act,'' he said.
   Granot said an expert from Israel's Agriculture Ministry was on
his way to Rome to help in the investigations.
   The Italian news agency ANSA said there was at least one
precedent for the poisoning. It reported that oranges and
grapefruits from Israel were poisoned with mercury in several
Western European nations in 1978. There was no claim of
responsibility.
   The news agency reported that Italy imports about 23,000 tons of
grapefruit from Israel annually.
   The figure represents about half of Italy's total import of
grapefruit. In 1987, grapefruit imports from Israel were valued at
an estimated $13.2 million.
   Owners of the Rome supermarket where the poisoned grapefruit was
found said they had sold about 36 Jaffa grapefruit the day before
the contaminated ones were taken for testing on April 20.
   Supermarket clients said two or three youths were distributing
pamphlets near the store last week urging customers to boycott
Israeli goods, ANSA reported. They said a poster affixed on a wall
outside the supermarket said, ``Don't buy Jaffa grapefruit. Boycott
Israel.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
