<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Rebels     04-26 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Rebels,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Troops Battle Deserter Cult Members, 7 Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CEBU CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops on Tuesday fought military
deserters who have formed a religious cult on a small island, and
seven people were killed, the military said.
   After the battle, dozens of former elite Scout Rangers remained
holed up with about 600 civilians in a standoff on Mactan Island
about 300 miles south of Manila. A renegade leader said he needed
more time to convince his men to surrender, according to a mayor
involved in the negotiations.
   Four government troops and three deserters were killed in
Tuesday's predawn clash. Local radio stations said one civilian
also died.
   The fight broke out when deserters, who took refuge on the
island in 1986 and formed their religious cult, attacked a military
checkpoint set up to prevent them from leaving their hideout,
military officials said.
   Maxim Patalinhug, mayor of nearby Lapu-Lapu City, met with the
leader of the renegades to tell him to give up. Sgt. Jose Sabandeja
promised to ask his men to surrender but said he needed more time,
the mayor said.
   About 600 civilians were staying with the deserters, maintaining
they were willing to die with them, the mayor said.
   Brig. Gen. Jesus Hermosa, regional military commander, said he
called off a planned attack on the deserters Tuesday to allow
officials more time to negotiate.
   ``The outlaws have many conditions which are not acceptable,''
Hermosa said. ``Their surrender would be unconditional. They should
face the consequences.''
   He said military operations would resume Wednesday. Hermosa has
vowed to capture the 30 to 50 renegades, who moved to Mactan after
deserting their unit on Mindanao island.
   The military claims the renegades have been involved in
smuggling.
   Also on Tuesday, suspected communist rebels gunned down a police
captain and an anti-communist vigilante in two separate attacks
outside the U.S.-run Clark Air Base 50 miles northwest of Manila,
officials said.
   Police said two men armed with .45-caliber pistols shot and
killed Capt. Francisco Medina, deputy police commander of Mabalacat
town, as he drove late Monday near the sprawling military base.
   Hours later, a lone gunman killed Francisco Sabile, a member of
a vigilante group, while he played cards with friends in
neighboring Angeles City, officials said.
   The military also said 17 communist rebels were killed when
government troops stormed a hideout in the northern province of
Kalinga-Apayao on Saturday.
</TEXT>
