<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NATO     04-26 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Defense Chiefs to Meet on Nuclear Arms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO defense ministers open a two-day
conference Wednesday to keep their policies in line with superpower
efforts to cut nuclear weapons.
   The meeting comes amid internal strains between much of the
Western military alliance and Denmark, which has moved to
strengthen its longstanding ban on peacetime nuclear weapons. This
week's talks were originally supposed to take place in Denmark, but
they were moved to NATO headquarters in Brussels in reaction to the
Danish initiative.
   In addition, the ministers will grapple with West German fears
about NATO's plan to modernize short-range nuclear arms. The
Germans think such a move could make them a more likely target for
Soviet aggression.
   However, this week's NATO meeting is not likely to yield major
decisions, alliance officials say. It is instead intended to review
long-range nuclear arms planning.
   It will be the first defense ministers' session since the Dec. 8
signing of the U.S.-Soviet accord to eliminate two classes of
ground-launched medium- and shorter-range nuclear missiles. The
U.S. Senate is reviewing the treaty.
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci was expected to brief
ministers at the meeting on preparations in the United States and
the Soviet Union for an elaborate, 13-year inspection system to
check compliance with the treaty.
   However, ministers will likely discuss the whole range of arms
control negotiations, said a NATO official who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   That would include reviewing superpower efforts to sign another
accord to cut their strategic nuclear arms by 50 percent, or 6,000
on each side. Hopes have faded of completing such a treaty by May
29 when President Reagan meets Mikhail Gorbachev in Moscow.
   The defense ministers will review their long-term nuclear arms
planning in light of the goals NATO has set for itself in recent
years, said allied officials.
   NATO has 4,600 nuclear warheads in Europe, down 2,400 since
1983. The stockpile is at its lowest in 20 years, said one NATO
official.
   The alliance is studying adjustments to its nuclear deterrent
through modernization and redeployment of arms without raising the
total number of warheads. The studies deal with developing a new
short-range Lance ground-to-ground missile, a battlefield
air-to-ground missile, and improved nuclear artillery shells.
   The issue of modernizing short-range nuclear arms, most of which
are based in West Germany, has also caused internal NATO friction.
Bonn fears that as medium-range missiles disappear under the
intermediate-range treaty, improved short-range arms would make its
soil a greater target for Soviet attack.
   It prefers short-range nuclear arms talks in tandem with
conventional talks, due to start in Vienna this fall. But its
allies say the short-range arms must still be modernized by the
mid-1990s.
   Ministers will also probably discuss Denmark's proposal to
notify individual warships of its longstanding ban on nuclear
weapons.
   NATO ministers have warned that such a move could threaten
Danish participation in the alliance.
   The Danes will vote on a new parliament May 10 in what Prime
Minister Poul Schlueter has called a referendum on NATO.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
