<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Visas     04-26 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Visas,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets to Ease Visa Procedures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will put new visa procedures into
place to make it faster and easier for foreign entrepreneurs,
scientists and technicians to visit the Soviet Union, an official
said Tuesday.
   The streamlined rules beginning Sunday are part of broader
reform of Soviet economic and foreign policy, Oleg V. Avramenko,
first deputy chief of the Foreign Ministry's consular directorate,
told a news briefing.
   ``The new procedure for entry into this country reflects the
logic of the course of Soviet foreign policy, which is oriented
toward active development of economic, scientific and technical
contacts with Western and developing countries,'' he said.
   Under leader Mikhail Gorbachev, the Soviets have been wooing
foreign investors, proposing joint projects with firms abroad and
seeking to use Western capital and expertise to revitalize the
state-run economy.
   For years, securing an entry visa to the Soviet Union has been a
time-consuming affair, with delays that often stretched into months.
   Starting Sunday, however, it will be the practice of Soviet
consulates abroad to issue visas within 48 hours to foreign
business people, technicians and scientists who already have
established contacts with the Soviet Union, Avramenko said.
   He said foreigners would need an invitation from a Soviet firm
or governmental agency in order to receive quickest
attention.However, others who desire to explore economic or
professional opportunities may still gain a visa at Soviet
consulates within about five days, Avramenko said.
   There will also be a ``maximum broadening'' of the granting of
multiple entry visas, documents valid for two or three years that
allow bearers to enter and leave the Soviet Union as often as they
want, the diplomat said.
</TEXT>
