<DOCNO> AP880426-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1808EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PriceFuneral     04-26 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Price Funeral,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wright: Price Represented `the Humble, the Powerless'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political leaders eulogized Rep. Mel
Price Tuesday, saying the 22-term Democratic congressman was a
friend of the common man and a model for other leading Illinois
politicians.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, told about 1,000 mourners at
the Cathedral of St. Peter Roman Catholic Church that Price
``epitomized the best of that misused and sometimes abused
profession'' of politics.
   ``He was not fashionable, not flamboyant,'' said Wright. ``He
helped the humble, the powerless, those who have no voice. He was
their voice. He was their strength and he asked nothing for it.''
   Price, 83, who died Friday of pancreatic cancer, had planned to
retire in January at the end of his 22nd term. The East St. Louis
Democrat had served Southern Illinois' 21st District since 1944 and
was the second most senior man in the House after 24-term Rep.
Jamie Whitten, D-Mass.
   A wreath of red roses and white carnations with red, white and
blue ribbons from the U.S. House of Representatives adorned the
altar with another wreath from the Illinois congressional
delegation and American flags.
   Others attending the nearly two-hour funeral included U.S. Sen.
Paul Simon and Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, both Illinois Democrats, and
Illinois Attorney General Neil Hartigan.
   Democratic Sen. Alan Dixon, the state's senior senator, said,
``Some young men like Paul Simon and Alan Dixon copied his style
and learned from him. Not withstanding his power, he remembered his
friends back home.''
   He recalled that Price loved to tell the story of how he was in
the U.S. Army, working kitchen duty at a Virginia base, when a
general called him in to say he had been elected to Congress.
   For six hours Monday, mourners streamed through a Belleville
funeral home to pay their respects to Price's wife, Garaldine, and
their son, William.
   Gov. James R. Thompson has until Wednesday to schedule a special
election to choose Price's successor, said Bea Swartz of the
Illinois Board of Elections in Springfield. The election then must
be held within 115 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
