<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-SaudiArabia 1stLd-Writethru a0716 04-26 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Saudi Arabia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Administration To Fight For Arms Package For Saudis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Inserts 3 grafs of Shumer reaction after 16th graf, ``We
remain''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration affirmed its
determination Tuesday to push a $460 million arms purchase by Saudi
Arabia through a reluctant Congress with the argument that
enhancing AWACS radar planes is essential to protect U.S. Navy
forces in the Persian Gulf.
   A bipartisan group of 187 House members has written Secretary of
State George P. Shultz opposing the sale of advanced U.S. equipment
in light of the Saudis' recent secret purchase of missiles from
China that could devastate Israel. In the Senate, 58 members are on
record against the deal.
   But State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said the Saudis
had given assurances the missiles would not be nuclear-armed and
had decided to sign the 1968 nuclear nonproliferation treaty.
   Under the accord, states without nuclear weapons agree not to
make or acquire them.
   ``We have not changed our view that the AWACS maintenance
package is critical to our gulf policy,'' Redman told reporters.
``The Saudi AWACS operation provides important support for the U.S.
mission in the gulf, including protection of U.S. Navy personnel
and equipment.''
   American warships are protecting U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti oil
tankers in the war between Iran and Iraq. A number of clashes with
Iran resulted above the Strait of Hormuz, through which cargoes
pass.
   The area is patrolled by U.S. radar planes, with the Saudi AWACS
_ or Airborne Warning and Control System _ aircraft confined to the
southern region, State Department officials told members of
Congress last week in a secret briefing.
   In the south, U.S. forces are under threat of Silkworm anti-ship
missiles Iran purchased from China.
   The decision to sell new equipment to the Saudis sets the stage
for a debate May 9, when the Senate Foreign Relations Committee is
due to hold a hearing on the nomination of Walter Cutler to be
ambassador to Saudi Arabia.
   The missiles China sold to the Saudis are capable of carrying
nuclear or chemical warheads and have a range of about 1,600 miles.
They add to Israel's security concerns that were heightened last
year when Syria obtained missiles from the Soviet Union that also
could rocket Israeli population centers with deadly chemical
weapons.
   Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said 186 other House members had
signed a letter he wrote urging Shultz to withdraw the proposed
sale.
   Redman said Shultz had not replied yet. But, the spokesman said,
``we expect to go forward with the formal notification in the near
term.''
   When that step is taken, the deal will go through unless both
the House and Senate vote to reject it within 30 days.
   ``The Saudis have assured us that their missiles would not be
nuclear-capable,'' Redman said. ``By adhering to the NPT (Nuclear
Nonproliferation Treaty), Saudi Arabia would further obligate
itself not to develop or acquire nuclear devices.''
   The spokesman said the State Department was concerned about the
proliferation of missiles throughout the Middle East and Persian
Gulf _ not just with the Saudi purchase from China.
   ``We remain fully committed to providing the necessary support
to Saudi Arabia for the continued operation of the AWACS,'' Redman
said. ``It is in the national security interest of the United
States to conclude this deal.''
   Schumer said signing the nonproliferation treaty ``is certainly
a welcome move.'' But, he said, ``it does not diminish
congressional concerns.''
   The New York congressman said ``the Chinese missiles, even
without nuclear warheads, pose a real threat to the security of the
entire region, in part because they are easily equipped with
chemical warheads.''
   He added: ``The fact that the missiles were acquired under a
cloud of deceit only heightens our concern.''
   Meanwhile, Saudi Arabia was expected to announce a break in
diplomatic relations with Iran in response to Iranian attacks on
shipping in the gulf
   According to an informed source, who requested anonymity, the
Saudi council of ministers took the decision at a meeting Monday
night.
   Saudi Arabia, like most of the Arab countries, supports Iraq in
its war with Iran.
   The United States, already protecting 11 Kuwaiti oil tankers
flying the U.S. flag, may extend the protection to neutral shipping.
   Shultz confirmed Monday at a news conference in Brussels that a
decision was under consideration. He and Redman declined to say
whether the request for broader U.S. involvement in the tanker war
had come from the Saudis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
