<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Strength, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0742,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ranks Reduced by 19,000 in March</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: FIXES spelling of accommodate in grafs 1 and 6</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The armed forces began slashing active-duty
strength in March to accommodate budget cuts, paring almost 19,000
positions from the ranks during the month, the Pentagon said
Tuesday.
   As of March 31, the Army, Navy, Air Force and Marine Corps had
2,143,129 men and women on active duty, down 18,727 from the
2,161,856 reported Feb. 29 and 25,051 below the March 31, 1987,
total.
   All four services reported declines in personnel during March,
although the Navy's drop was relatively minor, the Pentagon said.
   The Air Force reported 594,660 personnel on active duty at the
end of March, down 8,939 from Feb. 29. The Army set its strength at
768,211 as of March 31, down 8,202 from February. And the Marine
Corps reported 197,127 on active duty, 1,104 less than in February.
   The Navy, meantime, reported a decline of 482 men and women in
March to 583,131.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci has ordered a cut of
active-duty slots to accommodate spending levels set for fiscal
1989, which begins Oct. 1. He has told Congress he would rather
maintain a smaller force that is properly equipped and ready to
fight than a larger, but ``hollow,'' force.
   As a result of that decision, the services must lower their
manpower levels to a combined 2,138,327 _ or 35,890 below the total
reported at the end of fiscal 1987 last Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
