<HEAD>Volcker Says Presidential Candidates Ignoring Economic Issues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Federal Reserve Chairman Paul Volcker says
he is skeptical about some economic positions taken by the
presidential front-runners, Republican George Bush and Democrat
Michael Dukakis.
   Volcker, who served under presidents Carter and Reagan, said the
nation's economic problems are not likely to be solved by Vice
President Bush's pledge not to raise taxes or by Massachusetts Gov.
Dukakis' call to crack down on tax cheats.
   He said the nation must increase its level of savings and must
take action to cut the trade and budget deficits. And he said
spending on such programs as Social Security and Medicare must be
limited.
   Volcker said the next president must act promptly upon taking
office next year or a recession could follow.
   ``Candidates actively don't want to talk about the issue,''
Volcker said. ``And sometimes it's better when they aren't talking
about it than when they are.''
   He was in Atlanta Monday for a competitiveness conference at the
Carter Presidential Center.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>FTC Chairman Scores Democratic Candidates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Trade Commission Chairman Daniel
Oliver offered his views of the Democratic presidential contenders
Tuesday, criticizing proposals of Jesse Jackson and Michael Dukakis
and scoring Democrats for not condemning a 1984 Jackson reference
to New York Jews.
   Oliver, a former executive editor of the conservative National
Review, said the central question of the current campaign is an
economic one: whether the policies of President Reagan will be
ratified or rejected.
   The candidacy of Jackson, who is black, represents an important
and moving moment in history, Oliver said in remarks prepared for a
luncheon at the Heritage Foundation.
   But Jackson's proposals would cost billions of dollars,
resulting in higher taxes and reducing employment instead of
helping the poor, Oliver said.
   In addition, he went on, there is a question of character
focusing on Jackson's reference to New York City as ``Hymietown.''
   What if a Republican contendor referred to Birmingham, Ala., as
``coontown?'' asked Oliver. ``I can't imagine the other Republican
candidates even appearing on the same television platform with
someone who said that.''
   ``How can Mr. Dukakis ask for our votes when he lacks even the
courage to condemn a man who calls Jews ``Hymies?'' asked Oliver.
And he said Dukakis was far from the only silent Democrat.
   Oliver also said the governor was not responsible for the
economic upturn in Massachusetts in recent years. That improvement
should be attributed to tax cuts instigated by Reagan and former
Gov. Ed King, said Oliver.
   ``Mr. Dukakis may fool some people into thinking he is a trim,
health-conscious preppie. But there dwells within him the soul of
an old-fashioned, cigar-chomping Democratic pol, a veritable Tip
O'Neill,'' said Oliver.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Delaware Republicans Support Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All but one of the delegates to the
Delaware state Republican convention support Vice President George
Bush's presidential bid, a top party official said Tuesday.
   Jeffrey T. Larson, executive director for the Republican State
Committee, said that over the past three weeks, 315 delegates to
the state convention were chosen during caucuses throughout the
state.
   ``I know of one delegate for Pat Robertson. There may be one or
two more, but I doubt it,'' he said. ``George Bush is probably
going to have 314 or 315 people supporting him at the state
convention because Pat Robertson isn't running for president
anymore.''
   The state convention is scheduled for May 14 in Rehoboth Beach,
where 17 delegates will be selected for the national nominating
convention in August in New Orleans.
