<DOCNO> AP880426-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1905EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PumpkinPapers     04-26 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pumpkin Papers,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Says Chambers' Farm Should Not Become Historic Landmark</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Maryland farm where the ``pumpkin papers''
that led to the perjury conviction of Alger Hiss were hidden should
not be designated as a national historic landmark, an advisory
panel said Tuesday.
   It was the Hiss case in 1948 that vaulted a fairly obscure young
congressman named Richard Nixon to fame.
   The recommendation of the Advisory Board of the National Park
Service could be overruled, Interior Department spokesmen said.
   The board, meeting in Harpers Ferry, W.Va., made the
recommendation on the grounds that 50 years have not elapsed since
the events that gave the site significance, said George Berklacy,
spokesman for the National Park Service.
   The principal significant event was the retrieval of microfilm
from a hollowed-out pumpkin for Nixon, then a member of the House
Un-American Activities Committee, by the owner of the farm, a Time
magazine editor named Whittaker Chambers.
   Chambers had accused Hiss, a former State Department official,
of being a fellow member of a communist spy ring. Hiss sued
Chambers for libel, but Chambers' production of the filmed State
Department documents he said Hiss had given him in 1938 led to
Hiss' conviction for perjury for denying to the committee that he
had handed over the documents.
   The park service generally follows a policy of letting a 50-year
interval lapse to make sure history has gained enough perspective
on events for fair designation of landmarks, Berklacy said.
   ``It is not a hard and fast rule,'' he said. The secretary of
the interior, who makes such designations, has the final say and
may overrule the board, Berklacy noted.
   David Prosperi, spokesman for Interior Secretary Donald P.
Hodel, hinted strongly that Hodel might do just that.
   It was Hodel who nominated the 390-acre farm at Westminster,
Md., some 30 miles northwest of Baltimore, now owned by Chambers'
son John.
   ``We're checking into the precedents,'' Prosperi said, adding,
``The secretary hasn't pushed it this hard and this far just to
leave it here.''
   Chambers' testimony before the committee and his 1952
autobiography, ``Witness,'' strongly influenced a generation of
conservatives, among them President Reagan, who awarded a
posthumous Medal of Freedom to Chambers in 1984.
   The case was a watershed in American life, with many people
becoming convinced by it that communists had targeted American life
and institutions for damage, if not for takeovers, and others
refusing to concede either a threat from communism or the guilt of
Hiss.
   Hiss, who lives in New York, served 44 months in prison. He
maintains his innocence. Chambers died in 1961.
   Designation as a landmark carries no obligation and no reward
other than a plaque. Some 1,800 sites nationwide have been made
landmarks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1908EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Ward-Koch     04-26 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ward-Koch,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Commissioner To Koch: Apologize For Jackson Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward said Tuesday
that Mayor Edward I. Koch ought to apologize for his ``divisive''
attacks on Jesse Jackson during the New York primary.
   Ward, the city's first black police commissioner and a Koch
appointee, said the mayor's acknowledgement that he had been left
``bloodied'' but unbowed by the uproar surrounding his criticism of
Jackson did not suffice as an apology.
   ``It's not enough to say `I'm bloodied.' ... It's not a time for
more people to get bloodied! If you're bloodied, maybe you need
Florence Nightingale. You don't need somebody else with a bat and a
hatchet,'' Ward told reporters at City Hall.
   At an appearance in Washington on Tuesday, Koch offered an
apology for hurting black people's feelings but stopped short of
saying he was sorry for his remarks.
   ``When you ask me about blacks and their sensitivity, I'm sorry
that I injured their feelings but I will try to redress that as
best I can,'' he said. ``Not just with words but with programs.''
   He said his new budget on May 9 would include housing, health
and education programs aimed at helping New York's blacks.
   Asked if these programs were evolving because of the harsh
criticism to which he has been subjected, Koch, who has said he
plans to run for a fourth term next year, replied, ``Oh, sure.
Absolutely.''
   During the campaign, Koch criticized Jackson's stand on Israel
and said Jews and other supporters of that nation would be
``crazy'' to vote for him.
   He also said he thought Jackson's positions on national spending
would bankrupt the country, that his defense policy would disarm
the United States, and that he had ``lied'' about his actions the
night the Rev. Martin Luther King was assassinated.
   Ward said he did not know Koch's intentions in making those
remarks.
   ``But, whatever the mayor thought he was doing ... I'm here to
tell him, and I think the whole city community, black and white, is
saying that, `It didn't come out right, Ed. And it has a divisive
tone to it. And there is a time for some healing and consensus
playing that this city really can't afford what's come out of this.
And enough is enough and times is tough.'''
</TEXT>
