<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SavingsBonds     04-26 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Savings Bonds,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Savings Bonds Now Available Around the Clock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Treasury Department annnounced a move
Tuesday to accommodate people who get a middle-of-the-night yen to
buy a U.S. Savings Bond. Now all you need is a telephone and a
credit card.
   Beginning May 3, the government will accept VISA or MasterCard
numbers on its toll-free number: 1-800-US-BONDS.
   Subject to credit limits, callers can buy Series EE bonds around
the clock in denominations ranging from $50 to $10,000.
   ``We expect sales _ already at their highest levels since World
War II _ to surge as people learn they can buy bonds at any time,
from any phone,'' Jerrold B. Speers, executive director of the
savings bond program, said in a statement.
   Speers said the program is, in part, aimed at people looking for
a last-minute gift.
   The bonds will be mailed within three weeks, but purchasers will
earn interest from the first day of the month of their order. The
bonds cost half of the face value. When held five years or longer,
they offer market-based rates of six percent or higher.
</TEXT>
