<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Hailstorm     04-26 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hailstorm,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hail The Size Of Tennis Balls Pocks Cars, Damage In Millions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Damage claims in the millions of dollars
were predicted by insurance agents Tuesday after hail the size of
tennis balls pounded cars and trucks at dealerships, shopping malls
and suburban streets.
   ``Do you know what complete havoc is?'' said Tom Hollingshead, a
State Farm insurance agent whose office was besieged by phone calls
from insured clients with pocked, pelted and smashed cars and
trucks.
   ``It looks horrible,'' car dealer Frank McGough said as he
surveyed the damage at Capitol Chevrolet in Montgomery after Monday
evening's hail storm.
   ``We've got close to 2,000 vehicles on our lot, and I would say
99 percent of them have some damage,'' McGough said. ``Hail is the
worst thing that can happen to an automobile dealership because it
dents all your vehicles up.''
   McGough said one employee estimated damages at close to
$500,000. ``We've had some people working here 40 years, and they
say this is the worst they've ever seen,'' McGough said.
   Tom McCollum, senior vice president of claims at Alfa Insurance
Co., estimated the cost of the storm will be more than $1 million
by the time all Alfa claims are submitted. He said Alfa called in
20 extra agents from throughout the state to help handle claims.
   Emergency management officials said there were numerous reports
of heavy thunderstorms and hailstorms during the afternoon and
early evening Monday but that there were no reports of any tornado
touching down. State troopers reported no fatalities or serious
injuries related to the storms.
</TEXT>
