<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SpiceMerger 1stLd-Writethru a0756 04-26 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spice Merger, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0756,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Temporarily Bars Merger Of Spice Manufacturers</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New throughout with more details about company's size,
statement from McCormick</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Tuesday temporarily
enjoined the merger of two of the nation's leading spice
manufacturers pending Federal Trade Commission review of the
proposed deal.
   U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt granted an FTC request to stop
the scheduled completion on Friday of McCormick & Co. Inc's
purchase of Specialty Brands Co. of San Francisco, which makes
Spice Islands gourmet spices.
   Pratt issued the order from the bench and scheduled a May 3
hearing on the FTC's motion for a preliminary injunction against
completion of the merger.
   The FTC contended that McCormick, the world's largest spice
manufacturer, failed to comply with its requests for documents the
agency needs to determine if the deal would lessen competition.
   Specialty Brands, owned by United Biscuit, recently sold its
salad dressing and olive business to Campbell Soup Co. McCormick,
based in Hunt Valley, Md., is seeking to buy the company's Spice
Islands and Taste of Americana gourmet spice operations.
   FTC attorney Steven Newborn told Pratt that the agency had
significant questions about whether the proposed merger would
lessen competition because both companies have large shares of the
U.S. spice market.
   Newborn said the agency can't make a final determination until
McCormick furnishes the documents sought by the FTC.
   McCormick's attorneys contended that the company did comply with
the FTC's request on April 8.
   Last week, McCormick filed a lawsuit in federal court in
Baltimore charging that the FTC was illegally using the pre-merger
notification provisions of the Hart-Scott-Rodino Act to delay the
merger.
   Company spokesman Mac Barrett said that since January, McCormick
has given the FTC more than 120,000 pages of documents.
   ``Our desire has always been to resolve this application in a
spirit of cooperation, but the company believes that the matter of
document production has reached an impasse,'' he said.
</TEXT>
