<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1931EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-ChemicalWarfare     04-26 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Chemical Warfare,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UN Says Chemical Warfare Increasing in Iran-Iraq Conflict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chemical warfare is being waged on larger
scale than ever in the Iran-Iraq war, according to a U.N. report
released Tuesday.
   The report does not say who has been using the outlawed weapons.
Iran and Iraq have accused each other of launching chemical warfare
attacks in the 7{-year-old war.
   The report could prove a disappointment to Iran, which has been
urging the United Nations to condemn Iraq for practicing chemical
warfare.
   Investigations in past years confirmed that Iraq used chemical
weapons.
   In releasing the 26-page report, Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar expressed his ``deep sense of dismay and foreboding at
the mission's conclusions that chemical weapons continue to be used
in the conflict ... and that their use in recent days has evidently
been on an even more intensive scale than before.''
   U.N. experts examined victims in Iran and Iraq and concluded
most were suffering from exposure to mustard gas, a World War I-era
agent. A few had been exposed to a nerve gas, the experts said.
   The team said they examined 39 Iraqi victims, all military
personnel, and 66 Iranians, both soldiers and civilians.
   Iran claims Iraqi victims were exposed to poisonous gases used
by Iraq on enemy troops.
   Dr. Manuel Dominguez, the head of the team, said ``the use of
yperite (mustard gas) was unmistakably confirmed.'' Dominguez is a
colonel in the Spanish army who specializes in nuclear, biological
and chemical weapons injuries.
   Even though the report did not lay blame, Iraq said it was
satisfied.
   ``It definitely bears out our contention that Iran used chemical
weapons,'' said Mudhafar al-Amin, counselor to the Iraqi mission to
the United Nations.
   Iranian officials refused to comment.
   The U.N. team spent three days in Iran and three days in Iraq,
examining victims in an Iraqi military hospital in Baghdad and at
several facilities in Iran.
   Dominguez said that because of ``security reasons,'' the team
did not visit the Kurdish border town of Halabja, where Iran says
thousands of civilians died in Iraqi bombardment on March 16-17.
   In a 1987 investigation, U.N. experts collected weapons
fragments from the scenes of chemical warfare attacks to analyze
them to determine their origin. That investigation pointed the
finger at Iraq.
   In the most recent study, the team did not gather weapons
fragments.
   However, the experts said they were shown shrapnel from bombs
dropped on an Iranian village on March 29. The report said the
shrapnel ``was observed to bear markings in Cyrillic,'' the
alphabet used in the Soviet Union.
   The Soviet Union is Iraq's main arms supplier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
