<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CyanideDeaths     04-26 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyanide Deaths,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Daughter: Mom Talked Of Copying Tylenol Poisoning Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stella Nickell, accused of killing her husband
and a second person by putting cyanide in Excedrin capsules, had
discussed copying the Tylenol poisoning case in which seven
Chicago-area people died, her daughter testified Tuesday.
   Cindy Hamilton said her mother suggested the 1982 Tylenol
episode ``would be very easy to re-enact,'' safer and less
expensive than hiring a hit man or other ways Mrs. Nickell had
discussed for killing Bruce Nickell.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Joanne Maida, who led Hamilton through
two hours of tearful testimony, asked her to explain.
   ``In her (Mrs. Nickell's) own words, it would have been `easy
because they were looking for looking for people shoplifting and
taking things from the store ... not for putting something back,'''
Hamilton said.
   The testimony occurred in the seventh day of the nation's first
trial of anyone charged with causing death by tampering with
over-the-counter medicine. The Chicago case has not been solved.
   Nickell, 52, who was Hamilton's stepfather, and Susan Katherine
Snow, 40, of suburban Kent, both died in June 1986 after ingesting
Excedrin capsules containing cyanide.
   Prosecutors say the effort by Mrs. Nickell, 44, to make the two
deaths look like random killings began to unravel when her daughter
went to authorities.
   Hamilton, 28, frequently sobbed as she described how her mother
discussed at least four ways of killing Nickell, who died in what
prosecutors say was a plot to collect insurance money.
   Government investigators found Mrs. Nickell's fingerprints in
library books about poisons, and at least one insurance policy in
Nickell's name was forged, prosecutors say.
   Hamilton said that at first she didn't think too much about what
her mother was telling her. She was an intelligent woman who
collected information on a wide range of subjects, Hamilton said of
her mother. But gradually, Hamilton said, her mother began
mentioning Nickell more often during the conversations.
   ``I know my mother very well, and basically, I knew she was
capable of it (murder),'' Hamilton sobbed on the witness stand.
``But I was hoping she wouldn't.''
   Hamilton said her mother discussed hiring a hit man, but
dismissed the idea as too expensive, and contemplated slipping him
cocaine on the theory that authorities would conclude that Nickell,
a recovering alcoholic, had switched from alcohol to drugs and had
accidentally overdosed.
   Mrs. Nickell related that the cocaine ``could be put in his tea.
It basically couldn't be tasted in iced tea,'' Hamilton quoted her
mother as saying.
   Mrs. Nickell made one failed attempt to poison her husband by
placing black seeds that she believed were toxic in capsules, and
giving the capsules to Nickell along with his morning vitamins and
orange juice, Hamilton said.
   Hamilton said her mother also asked her how much heroin was
needed for an overdose, but never linked that question to her
repeated tales of dissatisfaction with Nickell.
   When her mother initially asked about buying heroin and other
drugs, ``I thought she may have possibly been thinking about
acquiring it (heroin) to supplement her income,'' she said.
   ``I just couldn't picture my mother selling drugs,'' she said.
</TEXT>
