<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Saudi 2ndLd-Writethru a0776 04-26 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Saudi, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0776,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudi Arabia Breaks Relations With Iran</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to CLARIFY Saudi Arabia breaking diplomatic
relations.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia announced Tuesday it
was breaking diplomatic relations with Iran and asked Iranian
Embassy officials to leave the kingdom within a week.
   The announcement, read on state-run television, said the rupture
came about because of several reasons. Among them were a riot by
Iranians during a pilgrimage to Mecca last year and a subsequent
attack on the Saudi Embassy in Tehran, it said.
   An informed source in Washington, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the Saudi council of ministers made the decision at
a meeting Monday night.
   Saudi Arabia, like most of the Arab countries, supports Iraq in
its 7{-year-old war with Iran.
   Iran and oil-rich Saudi Arabia have been at odds since the riots
in Mecca on July 31, 1987 that killed 275 Iranian pilgrims and the
subsequent ransacking of the Saudi Embassy in Tehran by mobs. A
Saudi diplomat later died of injuries sustained in the attack.
   The Saudis said a total of 402 people were killed in a stampede
after a political demonstration by the Iranians turned violent.
   Tehran said that Saudi police caused most of the casualties by
shooting into the crowd.
   Mecca, the birthplace of Prophet Mohammed, and Medina, site of
Mohammed's tomb, are the holiest places for the world's 850 million
Moslems.
   They are located in a western Saudi Arabian region known as
Hijaz.
   After the Mecca riots Iranian leaders called for the overthrow
of King Fahd and the Saudi royal family, the seizure of its vast
wealth and for stripping them of the custodianship of the holy
shrines.
   Officials of the pro-Western conservative kingdom accused Iran's
revolutionary leaders of terrorism.
   Two weeks ago, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini said that 150,000
Iranian pilgrims would travel to Mecca this year and stage
demonstrations against the United States and Israel.
   Saudi Arabia had said it would cut the number of pilgrims
traveling to the holy city this year but has not announced any
figures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
