<2ND_LINE>AM-Submarines, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0745,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manual Gives Soviets Lead in Submarine Communications</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed For Release 9 p.m. EDT _ time set by source</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of manual in last graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviets have shown a ``single-minded
attitude'' in improving submarine communications and may lead the
United States in developing powerful signals, a military
publication said Wednesday.
   The 1988 edition of Jane's Military Communications said,
however, that the United States was generally believed ahead in
research into laser-aided submarine communications, the most
advanced form.
   The work has gained importance because of the key role of
submarine-launched ballistic missiles under the superpower
agreement to eliminate medium- and shorter-range land-based nuclear
missiles from Europe.
   The highly penetrating Extremely Low Frequency communications
are resistant to jamming, can operate at great depths and can
survive a nuclear explosion, said Jane's. The manuel said the
United States was ahead in the less powerful of such signals, those
that penetrate down to nine yards.
   It said the United States was also leading in finding ways to
use laser transmitters carried on board satellites to relay
messages to submarines from shore installations, aircraft or
surface vessels.
   Such light can penetrate hundreds of yards beneath salt water,
editor John Williamson said in a forward to the manual.
</TEXT>
