<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1937EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolShooting     04-26 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Shooting,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen Gunman Holds 70 at School Until Students Jump Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN GABRIEL, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-age gunman burst into a high
school classroom Tuesday and took 70 students hostage, then
randomly fired bullets into a wall before he was subdued by
students, authorities said.
   No one was hurt during the noon incident at San Gabriel High
School, 12 miles northeast of downtown Los Angeles.
   Jeff Cox, 18, a former student at the school, was arrested and
taken to Alhambra Police Department for questioning, police said.
   ``We don't know the motive, but no one was hurt,'' said Lucia
Alvelais, spokeswoman for Alhambra police, which responded to the
shots-fired call at 11:34 a.m. The school is on the border of the
two communities.
   ``He was holding approximately 70 students hostage in the
classroom and occasionally fired rounds from a semi-automatic
weapon,'' said Ms. Alvelais, adding the shots fired into a wall
were intended as a threat.
   ``Then the rifle jammed and some students jumped him. The rest
of the students ran from the classroom and police arrested him,''
she said.
   Cox was arrested at 12:10 p.m.
   The school was closed for the day, and classes will resume
Wednesday, Ms. Alvelais said.
</TEXT>
