<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TVSuspects     04-26 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV Suspects,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Fugitives Arrested As Result Of TV Shows Not Yet Broadcast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival television shows about wanted fugitives have led
indirectly to the arrests of one man on Iowa embezzlement charges
and another on California rape-murder charges, and both were
ordered held without bond Tuesday.
   James C. Stark, 40, was arraigned Tuesday in Ann Arbor, Mich.,
for being a fugitive from justice. He refused to waive extradition
to California.
   California officials said they will seek the death penalty on
rape and murder charges.
   Steven Riley Hadley, who had been living in Texas for three
years under the name Richard G. Finley, is charged with embezzling
$1.1 million in 1983 from the John Deere Employees Credit Union in
Waterloo, Iowa, where he worked. He appeared before a U.S.
magistrate in Houston.
   Asked by Texas police if he was Hadley, ``he answered, `Yes, I
am.' There was a big sigh of relief and then he said, `I'll
cooperate fully however I can,''' said Police Lt. Gary Edwards in
the Houston suburb of Friendswood.
   Both men were arrested Monday, when television programs
featuring them had not yet been broadcast.
   Stark's photograph appeared on television in Ann Arbor for 15
seconds Sunday night on a promotion for the April 30 broadcast of
Fox Broadcasting's ``America's Most Wanted.'' Five people called
police and said they recognized him.
   Hadley was scheduled to be featured in NBC's ``Unsolved
Mysteries'' on May 6. The FBI said it sent out wanted posters on
him to aid authorities in anticipation of public tips and inquiries
generated by the program. A copy was seen by Edwards, who had had
his eye on the free-spending Hadley for some time.
   ``There was no doubt in my mind it was him when I saw the
flier,'' Edwards said. ``I was shocked. I probably have 600 pages
of reports on this guy from the last three years, and he looks the
same.''
   Stark was ordered held without bail pending another hearing on
May 26. Hadley was ordered held without bail pending a bond hearing
Friday.
   California authorities had issued warrants charging Stark with
the May 1, 1987, slaying of a teen-age hitchhiker in Banning and a
Feb. 24 rape in Hemet.
   Stark, formerly of Yucaipa, Calif., allegedly shot the
still-unidentified teen-age girl when she tried to escape from him
at a service station in Banning, 90 miles east of Los Angeles.
   Riverside County Sheriff's Detective Sgt. Howard Rush, whose
investigation led to the warrant on the February kidnapping-rape,
said Stark had been convicted three times of kidnapping and sexual
assault and had spent ``almost all the time between 1971 and 1985
in California prisons and a mental hospital. He'd get out and do it
again.''
   Ann Arbor police arrested Stark on Monday at his car wash job
after the telephone tips.
   Hadley was reported missing by his wife and family in July 1983,
the same time the $1.1 million disappeared from the credit union.
   He called home to alert his wife to a letter he left behind. In
part of the letter included in federal court documents, Hadley
wrote to his wife, ``If I call you to read this letter, it means
that I have successfully left the state with around $1 million from
the credit union.''
   His first wife later divorced him, and he remarried.
   FBI agents and police called Hadley, 40, and asked him to come
to the police station Monday to discuss a neighborhood juvenile
case that Hadley and his new wife had reported, then confronted him
with the poster.
   After arriving in Friendswood, Hadley obtained the birth
certificate of Richard Glen Finley, who died after birth in Houston
in February 1948, Edwards said. With the birth certificate, he got
a Texas' drivers license and a passport.
   The ``Unsolved Mysteries'' segment that led to Hadley's capture
still will be broadcast May 6, and will include an update of his
arrest, said Wendy Bailey, field producer with Cosgrove Meurer
Productions of Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
