<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dole-Media 1stLd-Writethru a0694 04-26 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole-Media, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0694,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Blasts ``Gossip And Nit-Picking'' In Campaign Coverage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS ``sometime'' to ``something'' in graf 9, bgng
``Something is''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE GOULD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole, criticizing news coverage of
his unsuccessful campaign for the Republican presidential
nomination, said Tuesday that reporters were more interested in
``gossip and nit-picking'' than in covering the issues.
   Dole, the Senate Republican leader, said in a floor speech that
overall coverage of the 1988 presidential primaries was ``issueless
and negative.''
   The senator from Kansas said a predominantly liberal press corps
gave Republican candidates ``far more negative treatment than the
Democratic candidates.''
   ``What I witnessed generally on my own campaign plane was an
aircraft filled with reporters who became each other's best
audience,'' Dole said. ``It was an ultrainsider's game of gossip
and nit-picking that turned presidential campaign coverage into
`Trivial Pursuits.'''
   Dole cited a recent USA Today newspaper study he said showed
``network television coverage of the 1988 presidential campaign has
focused 80 percent of its time on everything but issues.''
   ``There was coverage of all kinds of gossip and `horse race'
stories, and judging from my own experience, who's on or off the
Dole campaign plane, which reporter will find that one person in a
friendly audience who can serve up a juicy negative quote, and on
and on and on.''
   He said the media were more interested in ``putting political
gossip above information, and titilation above education.''
   Dole also said GOP candidates received more negative treatment
than Democratic candidates.
   ``Something is out of whack _ and something is disturbingly
unfair _ when news coverage becomes so slanted, and the issues get
lost in the daily hype,'' he said.
   ``Look at the news rooms,'' Dole said. ``Let's face it, they
tend to be liberal. In all honesty, how many Republicans are out
there covering the candidates? Or Congress? I don't think I could
guess more than a carload.''
   ``Reporters try to be objective,'' Dole said. ``But try as they
do, they just can't help but see the world through liberal colored
glasses.''
   Dole said his audiences wanted to know where he stood on
individual issues. ``Unfortunately, the American people are not
getting what they want, at least from the news media,'' he said.
   ``It's a shame the media can't keep up with the people,'' Dole
said.
</TEXT>
