<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1958EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Stalin     04-26 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stalin,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paper Prints Details on Removal of Stalin's Body</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In another attack on the legacy of Josef Stalin, a
newspaper gave details Tuesday about the removal of his body from
the Red Square mausoleum where the body of Soviet founder Vladimir
I. Lenin is entombed.
   The labor newspaper Trud published an article in response to a
question from an 18-year-old soldier, V. Kuzmin, who said many
young Soviets knew nothing about the removal of Stalin's body from
the mausoleum in 1961.
   Under the more open atmosphere fostered by Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev, Soviet scholars and journalists have begun
re-evaluating Stalin's record. He ruled the Soviet Union from 1927
until his death in 1953.
   Under his dictatorship, millions of people perished in purges,
forced collectivization of agriculture and rapid industrialization.
   Trud said that when Stalin died, ``many people did not know of
the circumstances connected with the gross political mistakes,
massive repression and lawlessness'' during his regime.
   Stalin's body was removed from the mausoleum and buried in the
Kremlin wall during the night of Oct. 31-Nov. 1, 1961, at the time
of the 22nd Communist Party congress.
   The party was led at that time by Nikita S. Khrushchev, who had
denounced Stalin's ``cult of personality'' during a secret speech
to party officials five years earlier.
   Col. K.A. Moshkov, who was in charge of overseeing the
mausoleum, told Trud he was called to the Kremlin for a meeting
Oct. 31 at which officials decided where to place Stalin's body.
   He said the officials had considered placing it in Moscow's
Novodevichy Cemetery, where Stalin's wife Nadezhda was buried after
she committed suicide in 1932, but agreed to place it in the
Kremlin wall.
   Moshkov told Trud that soldiers moved the body during the night,
with only Stalin's daughter Svetlana present.
   In the morning the official news media carried a one-sentence
statement that Stalin's body had been moved.
   Lenin's body has been enshrined in the mausoleum since his death
in 1924.
   In a speech last November, Gorbachev said Stalin's guilt was
``enormous and unforgivable,'' but he defended the former leader's
basic policies.
</TEXT>
