<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Saudi 3dLd-Writethru a0784 04-26 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Saudi, 3d Ld - Writethru, a0784,0630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudi Arabia Breaks Relations With Iran</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with more detail, quotes.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia accused Iran of
``terrorism and subversion'' and broke relations Tuesday, ordering
all Iranian diplomats to leave the kingdom within a week.
   A statement broadcast by state-run television and distributed by
the official Saudi Press Agency cited a riot by Iranians during a
pilgrimage to Mecca last year in which hundreds of people died, a
subsequent attack on the Saudi Embassy in Tehran and attacks on
commercial shipping in the Persian Gulf.
   On Sunday, Iranian speedboats attacked a Saudi-owned tanker in
the Strait of Hormuz hours after President Reagan warned Iran to
stay clear of neutral ships.
   An informed source in Washington said privately that the Saudi
council of ministers decided Monday night to end diplomatic
relations with Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's revolutionary regime.
   Saudi Arabia and most other Arab countries support Iraq in its
war with Iran, which began in September 1980. Iran is a Moslem
nation but its people are Persian, not Arab.
   The Saudi statement said that King Fahd's government exercised
self-restraint and prudence for a long time, despite Iranian
practices that ``run counter to norms and diplomatic traditions,''
before deciding on the break.
   A memorandum about the decision was handed to the Iranian charge
d'affaires in Riyadh, the news agency reported.
   According to the published statement, ``The government of Saudi
Arabia has decided to sever its ties with the government of the
Islamic Republic of Iran and asked all personnel of the Iranian
Embassy in Riyadh and the consulate general in Jiddah to leave the
kingdom within a week.''
   Reagan warned Iran on Saturday, five days after the U.S. Navy
sank or disabled six Iranian naval vessels, against continuing
attacks on neutral shipping.
   Iran and Saudi Arabia have made virulent statements about each
other since riots in Mecca on July 31, 1987, that killed 275
Iranian pilgrims and the subsequent sacking of the Saudi Embassy in
Tehran. A Saudi diplomat died of injuries suffered in the attack.
   Saudi security officials said 402 people were killed in a
stampede after an Iranian political demonstration in Mecca turned
violent. Iran said Saudi police caused most of the casualties by
shooting into the crowd.
   Mecca, birthplace of the prophet Mohammed, and Medina, site of
his tomb, are the holiest places for the world's 850 million
Moslems. They are in a region of western Saudi Arabian called Hijaz.
   Iranian leaders, who often threaten to export their
fundamentalist revolution to Saudi Arabia and other gulf nations,
exhorted the world's Moslems after the Mecca riots to overthrow the
Saudi royal family, seize its vast wealth and take away
custodianship of the Islamic shrines.
   Officials of the pro-Western kingdom accused Iran of terrorism.
   Two weeks ago, Khomeini said 150,000 Iranian pilgrims would
travel to Mecca this year and demonstrate against the United States
and Israel.
   Government officials had said Saudi Arabia would reduce the
number of pilgrims traveling to the holy city this year but have
not given figures. Iran reacted by threatening to boycott the
annual pilgrimage.
   Saudi Arabia is the leading member of the Gulf Cooperation
Council, an economic and defense alliance that also includes
Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, Qatar and Oman.
   Arab diplomatic sources said it was unlikely other council
members would follow the Saudi lead and break with Iran, despite
Iranian missile attacks on Kuwaiti territory and raids on the
Emirates' offshore oil facilities.
   Earlier Tuesday, King Fahd decided to sign an international
treaty limiting the spread of nuclear arms. The move apparently
came in response to Israeli fears that the kingdom might arm its
missiles with nuclear warheads.
</TEXT>
