<DOCNO> AP880426-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1958EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TransportationSafety     04-26 0603</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Transportation Safety,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Revamp Airline, Highway Programs, Federal Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A restructuring of federal airline and
interstate highway programs would eliminate bureaucratic practices
that interfere with aviation safety and road improvements, U.S.
Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley said Tuesday.
   When the interstate highway system is completed in the next few
years, the states should assume responsibility for their roads
because that way, the projects with the most merit would get top
priority, Burnley said.
   ``Costly and extraneous federal requirements now imposed on the
use of funds could be virtually eliminated, ensuring a greater
transportation return on every dollar spent,'' he told a convention
of the American Automobile Association.
   ``We are looking at ways to encourage and promote innovative
financing mechanisms'' such as permitting the use of tolls on
highways built with federal funds, he said.
   Burnley, who has proposed a reshaping of the Federal Aviation
Administration, told reporters that the FAA has never done an
adequate job of safety regulation and enforcement of the airline
industry because it is subjected to the federal budgetary process
and is operated through a maze of federal laws and rules.
   There is a ``morass of inhibitions on its growth and proper
management,'' said Burnley, who took over as transportation
secretary from Elizabeth Dole in December.
   He has described the FAA as a ``hybrid'' agency that combines
safety regulation and enforcement duties with the nuts-and-bolts
operation of running the air-traffic control system. Burnley would
like to separate the FAA's safety role from its operational
functions, and there is a move afoot in Congress to separate the
FAA from the Transportation Department.
   Burnley indicated he agreed with efforts to do so. He didn't say
how this should be done, but he said he would oppose turning air
traffic functions over to a privately run company.
   On airline safety , Burnley said, ``We've tried to toughen up
inspections across the board,'' pointing to the current
investigation of Texas Air Corp.'s Eastern Airlines.
   The 30-day, plane-by-plane inspection of Eastern's fleet, which
began April 13, is evaluating Eastern's ability to comply with FAA
safety standards and has resulted in a proposed $823,000 in fines
against the airline.
   Burnley, who flew to Orlando from Washington on Eastern, said
the airline is ``one of the safest, if not the safest, airlines in
America because of the attention it has received. ... I flew it
with extreme confidence today.''
   A similar inspection is also going on at Continental, another
Texas Air subsidiary.
   The transportation secretary said the FAA investigation was
under way before Eastern's pilots began a postcard campaign
detailing alleged maintenance and safety violations.
   ``I really resent the leadership of the union and the company
... using safety issues as a weapon against each other,'' Burnley
told a press conference. He said the two sides ``could duke it
out'' without resorting to safety allegations.
   In his luncheon speech to the AAA convention, Burnley said the
1987 traffic fatality rate was the lowest in history, with 2.4
deaths per 100 million miles traveled.
   ``There were just over 46,000 Americans killed on our highways
last year, which is tragic by any standard,'' he said. ``But if
fatalities were still occurring at the 1980 rate, the death toll
would have been 17,000 higher. Both numbers are mind-boggling.''
   He credited the reduction in highway accidents to the crackdown
on drunken- and drugged-drivers, the greater use of seat belts and
new safety rules affecting trucks.
   Burnley said it was too early to say what effect the new 65 mph
speed limit on rural interstate highways was having on safety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
