<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-OilFire     04-26 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Oil Fire,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazil Hires U.S. Firm to Fight Oil Well Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Tuesday it has
hired the firm of U.S. oil-well firefighter Paul ``Red'' Adair to
put out a blaze at the country's largest offshore oil field.
   Carlos Pinto, spokesman for the government oil firm Petrobras,
said two employees of the Adair company, based in Houston, arrived
in Rio early Tuesday.
   He said they went directly to the Enchova oil field in the
Campos Basin, 120 miles east of Rio, where a fire has been burning
out of control at an offshore rig since Sunday.
   The Enchova field and four connected fields have been shut down,
cutting Brazil's oil production by 71,000 barrels a day. The
country's daily production is 615,000 barrels.
   Pinto said the fire started with a gas leak at an oil rig 50
miles off the coast and all 250 workers were evacuated unharmed.
   Four ships with water cannons sprayed the rig around the clock
to minimize damage but could not put out the blaze, according to
Pinto.
   ``There are two possibilities for putting out the fire,'' he
said. ``One is to dig a parallel well and draw off the oil and gas
feeding the fire. The other is the Americans' way, with an
explosion that uses up oxygen and kills the fire.''
   Petrobras plans to import an additional 60,000 barrels of oil a
day at a cost of about $1 million to cover most of the loss of
production from Enchova.
   ``The platform itself cost $330 million and is covered by
insurance. A few towers fell down, but apparently it will not be
destroyed by the fire,'' Pinto said.
   The Campos basin is Brazil's richest oil region and has produced
370,000 barrels daily. But Brazil still needs more oil, and imports
in the first quarter averaged 718,000 barrels per day.
</TEXT>
