<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PolarTrek 1stLd-Writethru a0734 04-26 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polar Trek, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0734,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet-Canadian Ski Team Reaches North Pole</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout to CORRECT that radio marriage proposal
not made Tuesday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine Soviet and four Canadian skiers arrived
Tuesday at the North Pole, their first major objective in an
attempt to become the first expedition to cross the Arctic on foot.
   ``Everybody is in great spirits, all hale and hearty,'' said
expedition radioman Tom Atkins in Toronto. ``It's a personal
victory. They're more than halfway.''
   Organizers revealed that wedding bells rather than jingle bells
were ringing for one jubilant skier as the group approached the
pole earlier this month.
   Max Buxton of Calabogie, Ontario, in a radio message relayed by
a Soviet air base in Siberia, asked his steady back home, Nancy
Burton: ``Will you marry me?''
   ``It's so much like Max, he has to do everything different,''
said Ms. Burton, a dental hygienist in Ottawa. Her answer, relayed
to Buxton, was yes.
   The team set out from the northernmost tip of Siberia on March 3
and hopes to complete the 1,100-mile trek through some of the
world's most hostile terrain by reaching Cape Columbia, on Canada's
Ellesmere Island, in early June. They arrived at the geographic
North Pole at 3:20 a.m. EDT Tuesday, the 55th day of their
adventure.
   Soviet explorer and folk hero Dmitri Shparo, Anglican priest
Laurie Dexter of Canada, and the other skiers planned two days of
rest before continuing the ``Polar Bridge'' expedition.
   From the pole, they sent a short radio message: ``The first span
of the bridge is complete.''
   The team seeks to become the first to make the transcontinental
trip across the Arctic without using vehicles or sled dogs.
   Bad weather prevented a group of Canadian dignitaries from
reaching the pole in time to welcome the skiers, Atkins said.
   Because of poor visibility at Alert, a refueling stop on the
northern tip of Ellesmere Island, the Canadians were stranded at
Eureka, 300 miles south. Their final destination was a floating
Soviet ice station within helicopter range of the North Pole,
Atkins said.
   He said a group of Soviet dignitaries, including former hockey
star Vladislav Tretiak, made it to the pole, where the temperature
was about 22 degrees below zero.
   Supplies were flown to the Soviet ice station Tuesday. Each
member of the expedition carries a 100-pound backpack with such
high-protein, high-fat food as bacon and dried fish to maintain
energy and body heat.
   The Soviet team has government sponsorship and the Canadians
found commercial backers. The Soviets proposed the expedition to
demonstrate benefits of world cooperation and peace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1929EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-26 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow In Northern Plains; High Temperatures Across South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm dumped more than a foot of wet snow on parts of the
northern Plains on Tuesday and sent temperatures plunging to record
lows, while parts of the Southwest and Florida basked in 90-degree
weather.
   Meanwhile, a cold front brought a showers to the upper Great
Lakes and into northwest Pennsylvania and western New York, and
showers hit eastern North Carolina.
   The snow showed no sign of abating as it moved from Nebraska and
South Dakota toward central and southern Wisconsin.
   The heaviest snow fell in South Dakota, with Custer and Black
Hills receiving 14 inches by Tuesday morning and Gregory getting 12
inches. Plainview, Neb. received 8 inches.
   Pipestone, Minn., got 7 inches, and a snow advisory was in
effect for the rest of southern Minnesota.
   Light rain covered central and eastern Iowa and extended into
southwest Wisconsin and northwest Illinois. The rain was expected
to change to snow over Wisconsin, with up to 6 inches expected.
   Record lows Tuesday included 11 degrees in Sheridan, Wyo.; 17 in
Havre, Mont.; and 35 in Paducah, Ky.
   By contrast, relatively sunny skies and warm temperatures
prevailed over much of Texas and up into the middle Mississippi
Valley. Highs reached the 80s and 90s across much of Texas, the
desert Southwest, the Gulf Coast and Florida.
   West Palm Beach, Fla., had a record-high 93 degrees.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 30 degrees at
Yellowstone, Wyo., to 96 degrees at Fort Lauderdale, Fla. The
morning low was zero at Yellowstone, Wyo.
   Wednesday's forecast called for rain in much of the Midwest,
including Illinois, the Ohio Valley and lower Michigan, with rain
or snow expected for upper Michigan and Wisconsin, and along the
mid-Atlantic coast and New England; widely scattered rain and
thunderstorms from eastern Kentucky and Tennessee into the
Carolinas and Virginia; rain in coastal areas of northern
California and the Pacific Northwest; and mostly sunny skies over
most of the rest of the nation.
   Highs were expected to reach into the 40s in Michigan, Wisconsin
and the northern parts of Illinois and Indiana; the 70s and 80s
from the southern half of California to the southern Rockies and
from Texas to the south Atlantic states as far north as the
Carolinas; and in the 50s and 60s in much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
