<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 2007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SovietSuit     04-26 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Suit,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorney Claims State Department Made `Backroom Political Deal'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for an American businessman who
claims the Soviet Union libeled him Tuesday criticized the filing
of a brief by the U.S. Justice Department in defense of the
Soviets' position.
   Attorney Jerry Kroll said he believes the U.S. State Department
has ``made a deal _ a backroom political deal'' with the Soviets to
avoid further conflict in the 3{-year-old case involving Raphael
Gregorian.
   ``They've swapped an American citizen's rights for what the
Soviets want,'' said Kroll, who seeks payment of both a libel
judgment and the cost of medical supplies which Gregorian sold to
Soviet hospitals before he was expelled from that country.
   ``Gregorian's life-saving medical equipment is being used in
hospitals in the Soviet Union and the American government is trying
to help the Soviets weasel out of paying,'' said Kroll. ``This case
has gone beyond being a simple trade case.''
   The Justice Department's legal brief, filed last week in the
U.S. 9th Circuit Court of Appeals, seeks to reopen a case which led
to an award to Gregorian for the loss of more than $200,000 worth
of medical supplies. Kroll, meanwhile, is seeking to reopen the
libel portion of the case, which was thrown out by U.S. District
Judge David Kenyon.
   Gregorian, of Palo Alto, did business in the Soviet Union for 14
years. He was operating a $10 million a year medical supply company
in Moscow when he was abruptly expelled in November 1984. Izvestia
printed an article alleging he was a spy and Gregorian decided to
sue.
   In the opening rounds of his litigation, Gregorian won by
default when the Soviets failed to come to court. But when Kroll
began seizing Soviet assets to satisfy the damage judgment, the
Soviets began to fight back, seeking a hearing in federal court.
   After long months of litigation, Kenyon reversed himself and
threw out the libel award, but the judge ruled that Gregorian must
be compensated for the medical supplies he left behind.
   The Justice Department's 49-page brief backs Kenyon's conclusion
that the Soviets should be immune from libel suits, and also argues
that they should be allowed to mount a full defense on the issue of
paying for medical supplies.
   In its brief and accompanying documents, the Justice Department
contended that the Gregorian case ``has become a significant issue
in bilateral United States-Soviet relations.''
   Kroll labeled that argument ``ridiculous.''
   ``We fail to see how forcing the Soviets to pay for medical
supplies will start World War III,'' the attorney said.
   Douglas Letter, an appellate staff attorney with the Justice
Department, said he would not comment further on the case or
Kroll's criticism. ``Our reaction is that we are not litigating the
case in the press,'' he said. ``Our position is stated in the
brief.''
   The Soviets submitted their own brief this week, stating points
similar to those raised by the Justice Department. It was filed by
New York attorney Martin Popper, who represents the Soviets in the
United States.
   A key issue raised by U.S. officials from the beginning of the
case was whether a successful libel suit against the Soviets in the
United States would leave U.S. citizens open to similar suits in
the Soviet Union.
   The Justice Department has offered this possibility as a reason
for their support of the Soviet position in the Gregorian case.
</TEXT>
