<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SDIContracts     04-26 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SDI Contracts,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Request Ethics Review of SDI Research Contracts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two senators Tuesday asked the head of the
Office of Government Ethics to determine whether any laws were
violated in the award of government research contracts to a company
with employees who served on a federal advisory committee.
   Sens. John Glenn, D-Ohio, and Carl Levin, D-Mich., said a recent
hearing by the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee turned up
possible conflicts of interest.
   Those conflicts involved two members of the Eastport Group, an
eight-member panel that gives advice on computer and battle
management issues to the federal agency managing the nation's
``Star Wars'' missile defense program.
   Those two Eastport Group members, whose names were not
immediately available, are employed by Information Sciences
Institute, which has won two SDI contracts.
   In a letter to Frank Nebeker, director of the Office of
Government Ethics, Glenn and Levin said the two multimillion-dollar
contracts at issue pay for research directly related to
recommendations made by the Eastport Group.
   ``In fact, the first contract was based on an unsolicited
proposal by ISI, submitted within two weeks of the (committee)
report recommending such research,'' Glenn and Levin said in their
letter. ``Both contracts were awarded under questionable
circumstances.''
   When questioned about the contracts, the senators said, the
Defense Department ended the first contract earlier than planned
and announced it would reopen negotiations on the second.
   The senators said the Federal Advisory Committee Act requires
agencies to impose management controls on advisory committees and
that Defense Department conflict-of-interest rules require
committee members to follow certain ethical standards and file
financial disclosure forms.
   They asked Nebeker whether the committee members were subject to
federal standards of conduct at the time of the contract awards,
whether any laws or regulations governing ethical conduct were
violated and whether the matter should be referred to the Justice
Department for investigation.
   ISI is a research group affiliated with the University of
Southern California. Robert Biller, ISI's vice president for
external affairs, said the institute welcomes the review by the
Office of Government Ethics.
   ``We don't believe there is anything that represents an ethical
concern ... or a legal problem,'' said Biller. ``We believe
everyone has acted in good faith.''
</TEXT>
