<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 2012EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     04-26 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Television Shows First Pictures of Ethnic Protests in Caucasus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet television broadcast film Tuesday of
chanting crowds of thousands in two Caucasus republics, the first
scenes it has shown of ethnic unrest two months ago that led to at
least 32 deaths.
   A 90-minute special about the trouble in Armenia and Azerbaijan
included criticism of the official press and appeared to be an
acknowledgment that reporting on the unrest was slow and
incomplete. The host was Genrikh Borovik, a journalist and head of
the Soviet Peace Committee.
   The show laid much of the blame for rioting on rumors, but also
indicated silence by the media did nothing to squelch the rumors.
   Such a program could not have been appeared before Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's program of ``glasnost,'' or greater
openness. It was called ``Nagorno-Karabakh _ Reflection on Rumors''
and began with a woman from Yerevan, capital of Armenia,
criticizing lack of information from the media.
   ``I myself am not satisfied with the mass media, which
incorrectly reflected the events that took place in
Nagorno-Karabakh,'' said the woman, who was not identified.
``Central television also was silent about what happened there.''
   Borovik's broadcast, which preceded the main news program
Vremya, showed black-and-white film of thousands of chanting people
jamming open areas in Stepanakert, capital of the Nagorno-Karabakh
region of Azerbaijan.
   Signs visible in the crowd demanded that the region,
three-fourths of whose people are ethnic Armenians, be annexed to
Armenia. Nagorno-Karabakh was assigned to Azerbaijan in 1923.
   Protesters also demanded improved cultural and economic
conditions in Nagorno-Karabakh. Borovik did not reveal the origin
of the film.
   He said protests began in Nagorno-Karabakh in mid-February,
leading to demonstrations in Yerevan by hundreds of thousands of
people who heard rumors that protesting Armenians had been killed.
More demonstrations followed in Baku, capital of Azerbaijan, he
said.
   Soviet officials have rejected the demand that Nagorno-Karabakh
be annexed to Armenia, but offered a long-term program to improve
the area's economic and cultural life.
   About 15 minutes of film showed demonstrations in Stepanakert,
Yerevan and Baku. It also showed broken windows and damaged
buildings in Sumgait, the city in Azerbaijan where the deaths
occurred.
   The number of injured at Sumgait was given as 200, much higher
than the 81 reported April 13 by the newspaper Moscow News.
Officials told the program more than 80 people were under arrest on
charges of murder or participating in the ``massive disorder in
Sumgait.''
   Borovik criticized Sumgait officials for negligence and said
some lived in Baku rather than the city they governed. He did not
identify them, but the city Communist Party chief, mayor and police
chief were fired after the rioting.
   According to the program, 50 people were hurt in Agdan, a town
in Azerbaijan. Borovik said a criminal spread a rumor in Agdam that
a 12-year-old boy had been killed by Armenians in Stepanakert.
   A young man interviewed by Borovik in Yerevan criticized Soviet
media for not providing information sooner on those killed in the
ethnic rioting. Reports several weeks afterward said the dead were
26 Armenians and six Azerbaijanis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
