<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugDispute 1stLd-Writethru a0761 04-26 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Dispute, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0761,0795</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parents, School Dispute Drug Use For HyperActive Third-Grader</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf, `Outside the...'., to UPDATE
with later testimony from boy's second-grade teacher. Picks up 8th
graf pvs, `Ritalin is...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA ENGLERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drug Ritalin turned a difficult,
hyperactive 9-year-old boy into ``a zombie,'' the boy's parents
charged as they appealed to state school officials Tuesday not to
force him to take the medicine.
   Casey Jesson's parents appealed to a state education department
hearing officer, and said they will go to court if necessary to
override the Derry school district's order that he go back on drug
Ritalin, or another medication, before he is allowed back in his
third-grade class.
   ``We stopped the pills after my husband suggested that he should
get in the car with Casey and drive until they hit a wall,'' said
Casey's mother, Valerie. ``Life had become that much hell.
Everything was coming apart.''
   State school hearing officer Eric Falkenham did not indicate
when he would rule on the Jessons' appeal of the school district
requirement that he take the medication. The child is currently
being taught by a tutor provided by the school system, pending the
outcome of the hearing.
   Both sides agree Casey has serious behavior problems, but no one
has pinpointed the cause.
   With medication, Casey is manageable, school officials said in
testimony submitted earlier. Without it, they said, he is
disruptive and insults school officials, and refuses to follow the
simplest of classroom instructions.
   Outside the hearing, Derry School Superintendent David Brown
said that Casey's teacher sometimes had to call the principal to
the class to physically remove Casey from the room when he refused
to go out for lunch.
   Rachel Cobban, Casey's second-grade teacher, testified Tuesday
that when the boy quit taking Ritalin, he ``didn't stay in his seat
and pestered other children. I got no work from him.''
   ``He couldn't sit still even to do a five-minute reading task,''
she said, adding that Casey began having temper tantrums, tipped
over his desk and ate pencils and erasers.
   Ritalin is a stimulant, but paradoxically it can calm
hyperactive children, many experts say.
   Casey began taking Ritalin in the first grade when behavior
problems surfaced and continued taking it before school and during
the day for 18 months until the spring of last year.
   Off Ritalin, Casey has gained weight, sleeps better and looks
healthier, said his father, Michael. But he still does not know
right from wrong, has a very short attention span and, in general
is a ``bright but very trying child,'' Jesson said.
   On Ritalin, Casey looked and acted like a drug addict with
facial twitches, pale skin, little appetite and insomnia, his
parents said. He would sit for hours in front of the television and
rock back and forth, his mother said.
   Late in the afternoon, when the drug began to wear off, he would
begin to kick, scream, cry for hours, remain awake until after
midnight, refuse to eat, make repetitive animal noises and stare
transfixed at the faces he would make in a mirror, his parents said.
   ``He was a child in the driver's seat,'' said Mrs. Jesson. ``If
we had a good day, it was because Casey let us have a good day. He
was full of rage and it demanded our constant attention.''
   The Jessons rejected suggestions that they increase the amount
of Ritalin to keep Casey medicated at night. ``The stuff made him a
zombie. I couldn't do that to him,'' said Mrs. Jesson.
   The alternative to Ritalin is Cylert, which can cause an enzyme
buildup in the liver and would require Casey's blood to be checked
periodically, according to testimony from doctors who evaluated
Casey at Children's Hospital in Boston.
   Since taking Casey off Ritalin, the Jessons have experimented
with their son's diet, trying to see what food substances or
additives affect his behavior. Some experts have linked
hyperactivity to a child's diet.
   ``We know he craves sugar and feels better when amounts of it
are kept to the absolute minimum,'' said Mrs. Jesson.
   The Jessons have rejected the school district's proposal to put
Casey, provided he goes back on medication, in a program of
counseling and behavior therapy.
   His parents want the school district to offer Casey a
educational curriculum that includes counseling, behavior
modification, and more focus on the needs of hyperactive children,
such as special dietary needs _ but no medication.
   ``This kid had problems to begin with and then was blown apart
by Ritalin,'' said Mrs. Jesson. ``This family is through with
drugs. We need answers without drugs.''
</TEXT>
