<2ND_LINE>AM-Kite-Museum,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flying Kite Flyer Lands In Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 8-year-old girl who hitched a ride with
her kite on an airplane has landed in a museum.
   A life-size photo of DeAndra Anrig of Dublin, along with the
12-foot kite itself, will become part of the Ripley's Believe It or
Not Museum on Fisherman's Wharf, her father, Brad Anrig, said
Monday.
   On Saturday, the Anrigs delivered their daughter's kite to the
museum, where manager Ian Iljas said it and full-size photo of
DeAndra would go on permanent display after museum is remodeled
later this year.
   ``They offered us $200. We countered with $1,000,'' Brad Anrig
said. ``They came back and said their limit was $500.''
   Last month, DeAndra was flying her hang glider-shaped kite at
Shoreline Park in Mountain View when an air ambulance headed to
Palo Alto Municipal Airport caught the kite's line, lifting DeAndra
10 feet into the air.
   DeAndra traveled about 100 feet, then let go when she saw she
was headed toward some trees. She was not seriously hurt.
   Since then, DeAndra has received attention from reporters and
gotten letters from all over the country.
   ``She handles it like an old pro,'' her father said.
   DeAndra and the owner of the kite, Steve Chase, will split the
money from Ripley's, her share going into a savings account, Anrig
said.
   Iljas could not confirm the amount the museum was paying. The
sale was handled out of Ripley's main office in Toronto, he said.
</TEXT>
