<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ecuador     04-26 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecuador,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ecuador Campaign Riot Injures Six</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of two rival presidential
candidates clashed in a provincial capital and police fired tear
gas to disperse the mob, officials said Tuesday. At least six
people were injured.
   Newspapers and radio stations reported one person was killed and
at least 10 were wounded by gunfire after fighting broke out in
Cuenca, 185 miles south of Quito, during a campaign visit Monday by
populist candidate Abdala Bucaram.
   Officials denied the reports of shooting, however.
   The clash in Cuenca, an Andean mountain capital and tourist
center, was the most violent in a series of scuffles so far in the
campaign. The presidential election is set for May 8.
   The chief administrator of Cuenca, Italo Ordonez, told The
Associated Press ``six or seven'' people were hurt in the fighting,
but there was no gunfire. He said witnesses confused the explosion
of tear gas canisters with gunshots.
   He said scores of Bucaram backers fought in the streets with
supporters of Rodrigo Borja, candidate of the Democratic Left Party.
   Borja was first and Bucaram, of the Roldosista Party, second in
a field of 10 candidates in the first round of voting Jan. 31. They
will compete in a runoff to succeed conservative President Leon
Febres Cordero, whose four-year term expires in August.
   Newspaper reports said police surrounded Bucaram and escorted
him to safety when fighting broke out at Cuenca. He was not injured.
   Bucaram's populist, anti-establishment rhetoric and the leftist
programs espoused by Borja have caused uncertainty in Ecuador over
what the winning candidate will do once in office.
   Rumors of a military coup have circulated for months.
</TEXT>
