<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 2022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Trade 2ndLd-Writethru a0787 04-26 0846</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0787,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Byrd Puts Brakes on Trade Bill as Demos Scramble for GOP Support</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS grafs 4-5 pvs, `Byrd also ... this year,' with 2 grafs
to explain delay and UPDATE with quote from Reagan's letter to
Dole; MOVES UP 18th graf pvs bgng, `The centerpiece,' which becomes
new 6th graf; INSERTS 2 grafs after 17th graf pvs bgng, `It's a
tempest,' to UPDATE with lawmakers meet and administration confirms
oil provision in US-Canada pact; TRIMS last 2 grafs pvs to EDIT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic leaders put the brakes on a major
trade bill Tuesday, postponing a vote on final passage while they
scrambled for enough Republican support to override a threatened
presidential veto.
   Provisions that would limit export of Alaskan oil became a
critical stumbling block as leaders campaigned to line up enough
votes to make President Reagan think twice before reaching for his
veto pen.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., postponed until
Wednesday or possibly even Thursday a vote on the 1,000-page bill
Reagan opposes because it would require all but the smallest
employers to give notice of plant-closings and major layoffs.
   The delay gave Democratic leaders more time to beat the bushes
for Republican support.
   Reagan again signaled that he would veto the measure as it
stands, saying in a letter to Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole,
R-Kan., that lawmakers should ``finish the trade bill process in a
way that serves America's interests _ not special interests.''
   The centerpiece of the bill would streamline the system under
which the United States imposes import restrictions to retaliate
against international trade violations and aid U.S. industries
threatened by stepped up foreign competition.
   Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, said
he was searching for ways to take care of complaints from Alaska's
senators that the bill was too restrictive of their state's oil
exports.
   Party leaders figured that Democrats need 14 Republican votes to
demonstrate the two-thirds support needed to override a veto.
Bentsen did not tip his hand by offering a specific count. He again
said it was close.
   Both parties were bidding for support from Alaska's Republican
senators, Ted Stevens and Frank Murkowski, who reported themselves
incensed over the oil exports provision.
   ``This legislation discriminates very violently against my
state,'' Stevens told the Senate. ``It is a concept that I am
unable to accept.''
   Currently it is illegal to export any oil from the Alaska oil
pipeline, but the state does export about 4,000 barrels a day from
Cook Inlet.
   The trade bill would limit export of refined oil from a new
installation at Valdez to 70,000 barrels a day and 50 percent of
output. The limit would apply statewide and thus act as a cap on
any additional refineries built.
   Another provision would require that crude oil exports to Canada
of 50,000 barrels a day envisioned under a pending trade pact would
have to be transported first to some point in the lower 48 states,
presumably Seattle, before being sent back north of the border.
   Murkowski said it was unconstitutional to discriminate against
one state in legislation applying to the entire country.
   The crude oil provision had been sought by the maritime
industry, which currently transports the oil to West Coast ports
and would lose jobs if it were merely piped over the border to
Canada.
   Mark Murray, press secretary to Rep. Don Bonker, D-Wash., said
Bonker and other lawmakers had drawn the provision requiring
shipment of crude to the lower 48 states before export to Canada.
He said it merely echoed provisions already in the pending
U.S.-Canada free trade agreement.
   He said Bonker supported the provision because he feared
maritime unions would scuttle the free trade agreement without it
and because he was concerned about dwindling employment in the West
Coast maritime industry.
   ``It's a tempest in a teapot,'' he said. He said criticism of
the provision contained political overtones for Bonker, who is
currently running for a Senate seat against former GOP Sen. Slade
Gorton. ``This has a lot to do with Slade Gorton,'' Murray said.
   Bonker later met with Bentsen and Murkowski and issued a
statement afterward saying he believed it would be possible to
reach a compromise. He added: ``I don't think anybody in the House
or Senate wants to scuttle the entire bill on a single issue like
Alaska oil.''
   The provision requiring a stopoff in a West Coast port for
Alaska crude exports does appear in the U.S. free trade agreement,
confirmed Gary Holmes, a press aide to U.S. Trade Representative
Clayton K. Yeutter. He said it was placed in the pact at the urging
of maritime interests.
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said he would vote against the bill.
He said the savings and loan industry in Texas and numerous other
industries would be crippled by the plant-closings provision.
   He acknowledged a political risk in opposing the bill because it
also calls for the repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil
companies _ a move favored by the Texas oil industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
