<HEAD>Convicted Killer Wins Stay 20 Hours Before Scheduled Execution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Florida Supreme Court granted a
stay of execution for convicted killer Raymond Robert Clark on
Tuesday about 20 hours before he was scheduled to die in the
electric chair.
   The justices offered no immediate reason for their decision.
   The reprieve was the second Clark had gained within the past
three months. The warrant was the third Clark had faced for the
1977 shooting of David Drake, 49, a kidnapped convenience store
clerk. He was convicted the same year.
   Clark, 46, drove Drake to a secluded area, told him to write a
$5,000 check payable to cash, then shot him twice in the head,
court records show.
   A co-defendant, Ty Johnson, was sentenced to 25 years in prison.
