<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     04-26 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Bar Youths From Holding Anti-government Rallies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bands of young people set fire to
street barricades Tuesday after police prevented them from holding
anti-government rallies in mixed-race townships near Cape Town.
   A group of academic leaders held a news conference and issued a
statement denouncing security force actions during more than a week
of protests at township schools. ``Education cannot happen at
gunpoint,'' it said.
   Students in the townships are demanding the reinstatement of
activist teachers dismissed by the government, the release of
youths detained during protests and boycotts, and the lifting of
restrictions on political meetings.
   In at least three townships _ Athlone, Mitchell's Plain and
Bonteheuwel _ police blocked planned protest meetings Tuesday,
local reporters said.
   Several journalists were questioned by officers and ordered out
of the area under state-of-emergency regulations.
   There were unconfirmed reports that up to 20 youths were
detained.
   Last week, police sent letters to school principals saying
officers would be deployed on school grounds to enforce order if
disruptions continued. Some principals said they would close the
schools rather than allow security forces on the premises.
   At the news conference, student leaders, teachers and university
administrators accused security forces of ``provocative actions.''
   ``The security forces are effectively threatening to occupy
schools in the name of law and order,'' their statement said. ``The
response of the authorities is a recipe for chaos and
confrontation.''
   Among those signing the statement were Stuart Saunders, chief
administrator of the predominantly white University of Cape Town,
and Jakes Gerwel, administrator of the mainly mixed-race University
of the Western Cape.
   In other developments:
   _ The Weekly Mail, an anti-apartheid publication, received a
warning from Home Affairs Minister Stoffel Botha that it could soon
be closed for publishing material he considers subversive.
   Irwin Manoim, the newspaper's co-publisher, said the warning
meant Botha could act within three weeks to install an in-house
censor or close the paper for three months.
   The New Nation, another anti-apartheid newspaper, has been
closed for three months and several other publications have
received warnings from Botha. He has censorship authority under the
state of emergency imposed by the white-controlled government.
   _ Civil rights workers said the government has declared the
black township of Oukasie ``an emergency camp.'' The government is
trying to relocate the township's residents and thousands are
refusing to move.
   The civil rights workers of the Transvaal Rural Action Committee
said the emergency-camp designation meant that Oukasie, near the
northeastern city of Brits, was no longer governed by regular
municipal laws and could be abolished.
   About 5,000 Oukasie residents have complied with government
directions and moved to an area 15 miles away, but 8,000 have
defied the government and refused to leave.
   Opponents of the relocation said the government wants to
demolish Oukasie because of complaints from white residents in
Brits who say the township is too close to their neighborhoods.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
   South Africa's racial classifications include whites, blacks,
Asians and people of mixed race.
</TEXT>
