<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSRecords     04-26 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Records,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pregnant Woman Views AIDS Records Under Court Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pregnant woman who suspects that the
father of her unborn child may have AIDS has been allowed to see
the man's medical records under a court order.
   Alison Tradup, 25, demanded the information in a suit she filed
here so she could decide whether to abort the 9-week-old fetus. On
April 22, Monroe Circuit Judge Ignatius Lester ordered the records
turned over to her.
   State Health and Rehabilitative Services officials complied
Monday in a closed hearing. Under the judge's order, Ms. Tradup
cannot reveal the contents of the records. Her lawyer said Ms.
Tradup had made her decision but would not reveal what it was.
   The suit names James Mayer, co-owner of the Key West landmark
Sloppy Joe's Bar, as the defendant. Mayer was hospitalized recently
with an undisclosed illness, and his wife died earlier this month
of causes that have been kept confidential by county officials.
   The suit said Mayer ``is reputed in the community to have the
AIDS virus, but has denied this to (Ms. Tradup) and refuses to give
(her) access to his medical records.''
   Ms. Tradup's attorney, Imogene Synon, said she was pleased with
the result of the court action, but wished Mayer had complied
voluntarily.
   She said Ms. Tradup's own AIDS test was negative and that an
AIDS test conducted on Mayer several weeks ago was negative.
However, Ms. Synon said, Ms. Tradup wanted to examine further
medical information.
   Mayer's attorney, Michael Halpern, said his client had no
objection to Ms. Tradup's access to the records, but he felt
compelled to defend the confidentiality of AIDS data.
   ``My client recognized that anybody who was tested for AIDS
would be faced with the same situation he was faced with,'' Halpern
said. ``The potential abuse is horrifying that his records could
turn up on the streets.''
   But Halpern called Lester's decision, ``a perfect balancing of
the plaintiff's right to know while protecting the defendant's
confidentiality.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
