<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Security,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Criticized for Failing To Prevent Guerrilla Hijack</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli legislators criticized police Tuesday
for failing to prevent a commuter bus hijacking in which three
Israeli nuclear workers were killed by Palestinian guerrillas last
month.
   Mordechai Virshubsky, a legislator from the left-wing Citizens'
Rights Movement, said the March 7 hijacking could have been
prevented and charged police with trying to conceal mistakes.
   Details of the police actions emerged after military censors
lifted the lid off what news media here called a ``police failure
in a security affair.''
   A three-man guerrilla squad that infiltrated from Egypt killed
three Israelis and wounded nine before being shot dead by a special
anti-terrorist police unit that stormed the bus in the southern
Negev desert.
   The guerrillas seized a military Renault-4 vehicle before
hijacking the bus carrying workers from the Dimona nuclear plant.
   Israel Radio said at the hub of ``the affair'' were three
Israeli policemen who were ordered to erect a roadblock on the
highway linking Dimona with the Negev's capital of Beersheva and
stop the Renault-4.
   It said one policeman fired at the guerrillas' car but missed. A
second policeman tried to fire but his Uzi submachine gun jammed.
   The third police officer did not fire at all because he was busy
erecting the roadblock, the radio said, adding that the guerrillas
passed through the barrier unharmed.
   ``At first they wanted to conceal all this from the public. They
made every effort so that it does not reach public knowledge,''
Virshubsky told the radio.
   Ran Cohen, a legislator of Virshubsky's movement, told army
radio the incident ``was not ... a catastrophe. But it was a
serious failure.''
   Israel Radio quoted police officials as saying ``the affair was
blown up and a simple technical breakdown presented as failure.''
It added that after the incident, instructions were given to issue
an M-14 rifle to every police patrol and check all weapons in the
police arsenal.
   Police Commissioner David Krauss told Israel Radio the police
had learned a lesson and no one should be put on trial.
</TEXT>
