<HEAD>Former Armed Forces Chief Given Provisional Freedom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civilian court ordered the
provisional release Tuesday of a former armed forces commander
charged with overseeing death squads, a judicial source said.
   Former Gen. Gustavo Alvarez Martinez, about 50, was put under
house arrest 10 days after he returned April 9 from four years of
exile in Miami.
   He led the armed forces and was considered the military
strongman from 1982 until the military expelled him in March 1984.
   Dishonorably discharged and stripped of his rank, he was charged
in 1984 in the disappearances of about 130 suspected leftists and
the killings of about 30 others.
   When he returned to Honduras, he said he was a born-again
Christian.
   Judge Saul Suazo Lara of the 1st Criminal Court released Alvarez
without bail but ordered him not to leave the country, said the
source, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   On his return home, the former general said: ``If anyone thinks
they have evidence against me, let them take it to the courts. I
have found tranquility and fear nothing and no one except God.''
   Some subordinates may have kidnapped or killed suspected
subversives, he said, ``and now it's being placed at my feet.''
   Some legal experts said the Alvarez case would fall under an
amnesty ordered in late 1984.
</TEXT>
