<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-US     04-26 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-US,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Calls Extension of U.S. Embargo Criminal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said Tuesday
that President Reagan's decision to extend the U.S. economic
embargo against Nicaragua reflected a criminal attitude.
   ``The embargo will not demoralize the Nicaraguan workers,''
Ortega told a group of laborers who are working to develop 26 wells
to improve the Managua area's water supply.
   ``Our response to the embargo is this production of more water
for the population of Managua,'' Ortega said.
   ``Here we have the results. The morality and conscience of the
workers is stronger than the criminal attitude of Reagan with all
his embargos.''
   Ortega said Reagan's statement that Nicaragua represented a
security threat to the United States was ``a ridiculous thing.''
Reagan ``has done this to justify his terrorist and aggressive
policy against the Nicaraguan people and workers,'' he added.
   In a statement sent to Congress on Monday, Reagan said, ``The
actions and policies of the government of Nicaragua continue to
pose an unusual and extroardinary threat to the national security
and foreign policy of the United States.''
   The embargo would have expired May 1. Reagan first ordered the
embargo in May 1985, cutting off all trade with the Central
American country and denying Nicaraguan airliners and flag vessels
access to the United States.
   The United States maintains diplomatic relations with
Nicaragua's leftist government but also has provided aid to rebels
fighting to overthrow Ortega's Sandinista government.
   On March 23 the rebels, known as Contras, and Sandinistas agreed
to a 60-day cease-fire that went into effect April 1. Under the
agreement the two sides are to negotiate a permanent truce. They
have held meetings this month in Managua.
</TEXT>
