<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 2204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Afghanistan     04-26 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghanistan,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Warn Against Breaking Geneva Accords on Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet government said Tuesday the United
States and Pakistan would face international moral condemnation if
they violated the Geneva agreement on the civil war in Aghanistan.
   It also urged Pakistan to shut down Afghan guerrilla bases
inside that country.
   An official statement carried by the Tass news agency said
politicians and officials, who it did not identify, began making
``statements contradicting the letter and the spirit of the Geneva
accords'' immediately after they were signed April 14.
   ``Any deviation from the recorded accords can harm the cause of
the Afghan settlement and impair the moral prestige of a state that
breaks the obligation assumed before the whole world,'' it said.
   The United States, Pakistan, the Soviet Union and Afghanistan
signed the agreement, but Afghan rebel leaders did not.
   The statement carried by Tass said the Soviet Union will keep
its part of the agreement and will withdraw its soldiers from
Afghanistan. About 115,000 Soviet military personnel are thought to
be in the country.
   ``Their withdrawal will begin on May 15, 1988, and be completed
not later than Feb. 15, 1989,'' it said. ``Our country is waiting
for its sons who have helped a friendly neighboring nation that has
found itself in trouble.''
   ``The Soviet people will never forget their exploits and will
hold sacred the memory of those who have laid down their lives on
Afghan soil,'' it added.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to help the
Marxist government fight the anti-communist guerrillas.
   The statement denounced the rebels, saying their rejection of
the Geneva accords ``only shows that the sense of responsibility
for the destinies of their country and their people is lacking.''
</TEXT>
