<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 2209EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chernobyl     04-26 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chernobyl,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Acreage Near Chernobyl Reactor To Be Planted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials have decided it is safe to cultivate
about 74,000 acres of land near the Chernobyl plant back two years
after the world's worst nuclear power accident, Tass said Tuesday.
   The Soviet news agency said in a report from Chernobyl that
radiation levels around the power plant in the Soviet Ukraine are
well within internationally accepted norms.
   In a separate report, Soviet television showed film of a
memorial gathering of relatives of those killed in the explosion
and fire at the plant's No. 4 reactor on April 26, 1986.
   At least 31 people were killed by the blast and the release of
radiation, and a cloud of radiactive material circled the Earth.
   Alexei Denisenko, deputy chairman of the Ukraine State
Agro-Industrial Committee, told Tass the land to be brought back
into cultivation lies within the 18-mile zone around the plant that
was evacuated after the accident.
   It said scientists are working in Pripyat, the former home of
49,000 people located three miles from the plant, to see if any
long-term damage was done to plant life.
   ``So far we have not detected any mutations or changes in the
chromosome systems of plants,'' said laboratory director Nikolai
Arkhipov. ``The research shows that the level of its contamination
with radionuclides does not exceed the international medical norm
for foodstuffs.''
   Tass said the radiation level near the plant's first reactor is
about 0.5 milliroentgen an hour, and about four milliroentgen near
the second reactor.
   A milliroentgen is one-thousandth of a roentgen, the standard
measure of ionizing radiation. Experts say exposure to 50 roentgens
or more per year is dangerous and 400 roentgens per year can be
fatal.
   The news agency said a power plant worker would have to stay on
the site for 50 years to receive the dosage of radiation considered
the maximum allowable by international standards.
   Soviet news media generally have given a positive picture of
work at the Chernobyl plant in a series of reports dedicated to the
anniversary of the accident.
   But on Sunday, the Communist Party newspaper Pravda blasted
sloppy repairs, drunkenness and nepotism at the plant. It said
managers there act ``as though there hasn't been an accident.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
