<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 2212EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghan-Refugees 1stLd-Writethru a0794 04-26 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Refugees, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0794,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Honing Plans For Refugee Return</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT one graf after 6th graf pvs, Officials of ... UPDATING
with secretary-general's announcement on Soviet withdrawal
monitoring. Pick up 7th graf pvs, Faubert said ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. officials are putting the finishing touches
on a return program for more than 5 million Afghan refugees,
potentially one of the biggest United Nations operations ever.
   The prospect of continued civil war in Afghanistan makes a swift
refugee return seem unlikely, but the world body is preparing for
several possibilities. Envoys of the Office of the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees have begun talks on repatriation with the
governments of the three countries involved _ Afghanistan, Pakistan
and Iran.
   Carrol Faubert, head of the Afghan repatriation unit at UNHCR,
said plans for returning the refugees are ``almost final _ and
provisional, of course, because we don't know when, how many and in
what time frame people will move.''
   ``We're trying to be ready for quick action if there is more
rapid movement than some expect,'' he added.
   Also, the refugee situation differs in Pakistan and in Iran, two
border nations harboring the displaced Afghans.
   Officials of various U.N. agencies will meet in New York
Thursday to distribute tasks in the repatriation, said UNHCR
sources, who spoke on the condition of anonymity. U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar is expected to appoint a
special program coordinator shortly, as was done during the African
drought emergency.
   Perez de Cuellar told a news conference Tuesday that U.N.
observers will soon be deployed to monitor withdrawal of Soviet
troops from Afghanistan and a political settlement. He said the
Security Council authorized him to proceed with the U.N. mission.
``Our operation will be very much on in the next few days,'' he
said.
   Faubert said in an interview with The Associated Press that
UNHCR intends to supervise protection for the returnees, organize
transportation back to their place of origin, and oversee the
initial distribution of food, seeds and agricultural tools after
they return. A communications network to monitor the different
parts of the program must also be built.
   The effort is expected to cost hundreds of millions of dollars
if all Afghans return, U.N. refugee commissioner Jean-Pierre Hocke
has said.
   Perez de Cuellar is expected to launch an appeal for money soon.
   ``Our people are drawing up a number of scenarios that go from a
massive rush to people not moving very quickly. In Pakistan, there
are about 20 different scenarios,'' Faubert said.
   He said it is also difficult to predict whether the refugees
will return to several areas simultaneously or move region by
region.
   Apart from logistics, U.N. officials are evaluating what aid is
needed to rebuild roads and dwellings and restore land in
Afghanistan.
   More than a third of the population fled during 10 years of
civil war. Official figures list 3.1 million Afghan refugees in
Pakistan and 2.4 million in Iran.
   Under a U.N.-sponsored agreement signed April 14, the Soviet
Union pledged to withdraw its troops backing the Afghan government,
starting May 15. Afghanistan and Pakistan agreed to ensure the safe
and voluntary return of refugees.
   Not signing were Moslem Afghan guerrillas, who say they will
continue fighting to overthrow the communist Kabul government.
   UNHCR officials in Pakistan met with the resistance shortly
before the pact's conclusion, apparently aiming to draw them into
the repatriation plans. Faubert refused to reveal the outcome of
the talks but said they will continue.
   U.N. plans must also take into account the differences between
government policy and the composition of the refugee population in
Iran and Pakistan.
   Most Afghans in Pakistan are displaced farmers, housed in 320
refugee villages within about 60 miles of the border. They own
about 4,000 private trucks, so there could be sizeable,
unsupervised returns.
   In Iran, about 60 percent of the Afghan refugees are in cities
relatively far from the border. Many are said to have found menial
jobs. They may wait for years to return, Faubert said.
   Iran, which did not take part in the U.N. negotiations, and
Pakistan both pledge not to expel refugees. But Pakistani officials
make clear they would welcome a quick return home of the Afghans.
Many Pakistanis blame the refugees for a wide range of the
country's social and economic problems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
