<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0880,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Calls Pennsylvania Win `Big Boost' But Won't Claim
Nomination</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 9 grafs Dukakis reax; picks up 6th graf pvs, bgng:
Earlier, Dukakis</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis said his triumph in Tuesday's
Pennsylvania primary was ``a very big boost' toward the Dmeocratic
presidential nomination, but the Massachusets governor refused to
say he has won the battle.
   ``I'm going to campaign as hard as I can in the primaries
between now and June 7,'' Dukakis told reporters. ``I'm gong to
campaign in every single primary.''
   Dukakis said he was particularly pleased to win another big
state _ his fourth in a row _ in such a convincing fashion, racking
up a better than 2-1 margin over remaining rival Jesse Jackson.
   ``It's a very big boost....particuarly in a state that has been
a bellwether state in the general election,'' Dukakis added. ``It's
going to be very helpful.''
   Asked if the big win meant the nomination is now his, Dukakis
refused to claim the crown yet, refering to Democratic nominee
Walter Mondale's probelms in 1984.
   ``I reminded you several time that Fritz Mondale won New York
and Pennsylvania and then lost a string of primaries,'' he said.
   He said he would not change his campaign themes or strategy.
   `I'm going to keep it as strong and positive as I possibly
can,'' Dukakis said.
   The next round of contests comes next Tuesday, in Ohio, Indiana
and the District of Columbia. Dukakis was heading for Ohio on
Thursday.
   Earlier, Dukakis said Vice President George Bush has
flip-flopped on his pledge not to raise taxes. Bush won the
Republican primary in Pennsylvania, and the contest was expected to
yield enough delegates to give him a mathematical lock on the
nomination.
   Dukakis, bringing up the politically risky tax issue, said
Bush's pledge was a shaky one, like the claim by a comic opera
character that he never gets seasick _ ``What, Never? Hardly ever.''
   In recent days, Dukakis has been referring to Bush, his possible
November opponent, in answer to questions.
   Asked whether he would raise taxes, Dukakis gave his standard
answer:
   ``We've got to find new revenue. I don't think any responsible
candidate for the presidency can rule out new taxes. I can't make
that judgment at the present time.''
   Then he added:
   ``Even the vice president found that out. He announced on
Saturday (promising no new taxes) and then kind of like the captain
of the Pinafore, on Monday he said `Well, hardly ever,''' Dukakis
told the luncheon crowd.
   Dukakis was referring a line from the Gilbert and Sullivan
musical, ``HMS Pinafore.'' In the musical, the ship captain takes
part in this famous dialogue:
   ``And I'm never, never sick at sea.''
   ``What, never?''
   ``No, never!''
   ``What, never?''
   ``Hardly ever.''
   When Bush announced his campaign for the 1988 GOP nomination in
October 1987, he said, ``I am not going to raise your taxes.
Period.''
   But two days later, Bush said in an interview on the Cable News
Network that he might.
   ``What I have said is if I were convinced that all the spending
that could possibly be constrained or cut had taken place, then and
only then would I consider a tax increase,'' he said.
   Dukakis has been talking on the campaign trail about the giant
federal deficit and what he calls the ``fiscal mess'' the next
president will inherit from the Reagan administration. And this
mess exists even with recent tax increases, he said.
   ``The current administration has raised taxes three or four
times in six years,'' he said.
</TEXT>
