<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, April 27, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Raul Julia Only Saving Grace in `Onassis'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At one point in ABC's ``The Richest Man in the
World: The Story of Aristotle Onassis,'' Winston Churchill asks Ari
how he thinks history will remember him.
   Onassis demurs, but he could have predicted that he would be
immortalized in lame, exploitative made-for-TV movies to run in
sweeps months on American networks. This latest airs Sunday and
Monday.
   What starts as inconsequential pulp basically stays that way,
although, when Raul Julia takes over the title role late in the
first half, it threatens to become an interesting character study
of a powerful man who knew exactly what he wanted and just couldn't
quite get it.
   This is a sympathetic portrait of Onassis, as well as Maria
Callas, played by Jane Seymour. Jackie (Francesca Annis) and the
rest of the Kennedy clan come off as a bunch of money-grubbing ugly
Americans.
   The movie, based on the best-selling biography ``Ari,'' by Peter
Evans, isn't the first TV treatment of the Greek shipping magnate's
life.
   Anthony Quinn portrayed a character obviously based on Onassis
in the TV movie ``The Greek Tycoon'' several years ago. This time,
he plays Onassis' father, a thankless role that has him alternately
fuming and spouting fortune-cookie proverbs. Quinn's son, Lorenzo,
incidentally, plays Onassis' son, Alexander.
   Elias Koteas is adequate as the young Ari, though his role lasts
too long, and he doesn't in the least resemble Julia, whose droopy
eyelids and languid sensuality are perfect for playing Onassis, who
in real life wasn't exactly a matinee idol.
   The movie begins with Onassis as a youth in Turkey where his
father was a tobacco dealer. When the Turks begin rounding up
Greeks, attractive young Aristo avoids being sent to a labor camp
by having an affair with a Turkish colonel, no doubt with the words
of his father _ ``A wise man does what is necessary'' _ ringing in
his ears.
   But his father doesn't appreciate the way Aristo has won the
family's freedom, so Ari moves to Argentina where he sells
cigarettes and begins a habit of seducing opera stars.
   Julia shows up as Ari at 46, when he marries Tina (Beatie
Edney), the 17-year-old daughter of a shipping competitor (Anthony
Zerbe).
   Now the luscious trashiness begins in earnest.
   After having two children, Tina, who may be young but is not
stupid, notices her husband's philandering and leaves.
   Ari continues his pursuit of the volatile Callas while wining
and dining jet-setters like Lee Radziwill, and the powerful of the
world, including Churchill. Through Lee, he meets her sister, the
delicate wife of an up-and-coming U.S. senator. The short, stocky
Onassis probably would have been delighted at a yacht scene in
which Julia towers over the actor playing John F. Kennedy. Annis
plays Jackie as a symbol of respect, devoid of personality.
   After Kennedy is assassinated, Jackie, desperate for protection,
figures Onassis and his millions can provide it.
   Instead of marrying the tried-and-true Callas, Onassis opts for
symbolic triumph by wedding the world's most revered woman. His
children care for no one but their real mother and contemptuously
refer to her as ``the widow.''
   Jackie begins a spending spree that could put even Onassis in
the poorhouse, and she becomes enraged when photographers with
scuba equipment and long lenses are able to photograph her topless.
   Onassis goes back once again to Callas. He also repairs a
strained relationship with his son. But Alexander dies in a plane
crash, devastating Onassis.
   Shortly before he falls into ill health, Onassis bequeaths to
his daughter, Christina (Harriet Bagnell), his business secrets,
such as ``Write down everything, especially about people. When you
meet them again, you'll know how much time they're worth.''
   Too late for viewers, who will have already wasted almost four
hours on the miniseries.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   MARIST AWARD _ Harry Reasoner, a founding editor on CBS' ``60
Minutes'' is this year's recipient of Marist College's Lowell
Thomas Award. The award was instituted in 1983 to honor life-time
achievements by leaders in broadcast journalism. Thomas, a pioneer
broadcaster, is an honorary alumnus of the Poughkeepsie, N.Y.,
college. Previous recipients include Reasoner's colleagues Walter
Cronkite, Douglas Edwards, Howard K. Smith and David Brinkley.
Reasoner will receive the award at a luncheon Thursday presided
over by Kathleen Sullivan, co-host of ``CBS This Morning.'' The
award is to be presented by former CBS President Frank Stanton and
Marist President Dennis J. Murray. ``60 Minutes'' is in its 20th
season.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, April 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
