<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv27   04-26 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 27 ,0559</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Wednesday April 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>Crises By Forecast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every day since the stock market crash a
half-year ago, an economic crisis of one sort or another has been
forecast _ in trade, credit, stocks, bonds, car sales and more.
   Oddly, and offering a flash of insight about our times, none of
the ``crises'' has arrived. They fade quietly, no apologies from
their creators, and are replaced by vitally fresh hair-raisers.
   Are mortgage rates headed higher? Will the Federal Reserve clamp
down on the money supply? Can the dollar be saved?
   Economically speaking, the six months since the great stock
market crash have been unusually calm. The economy has neither
boomed nor busted. The jobless rate has trended lower. Securites
have been fairly stable.
   It has not been that way in the forecasts. Had they been right,
securities would be deeply depressed, unemployment would have
soared, home mortgages would have been unattainable, plants and
factories would be shutting down.
   In short, the economy as forecast would be in ruins.
   While forecasters suggest it is a miracle their worst estimates
haven't come true, it is equally amazing to others that some
forecasters won't give up. In almost every economic forecast there
remains a sense of punishment due. Good economic news is seldom
accepted for what it is; instead, it provokes forecasts of worse to
come. Poor economic news is almost welcomed.
   The contrast between forecast and performance is especially
obvious in the stock market, where it has become axiomatic that a
pervading bearishness in the forecasts indicates, of all things, a
higher market to come.
   Whatever the reasons, the persistent sense of fear in the
forecasts has created the impression that the past six months have
been ones of turmoil, whereas they have been closer to tranquillity.
   Why then do the fears linger?
   A sense of guilt, perhaps. If the stock market crashed why
shouldn't a recession follow?. Recessions almost always follow, so
why not now?
   A recognition that deep, and largely unresolved problems remain.
The trade and budget deficits, Third World loans, a high level of
credit at every level of the economy, the threat of trade wars, the
volatility of markets.
   But that doesn't fully explain why the good news is discounted.
   The economy, for example, has been neither strong nor weak, and
either one could cause trouble; inflation in one instance,
recession in the other. Jobs are being created. Inflation remains
in check. Interest rates, though edging higher, haven't been
jumping around as they once did. Exports are improving.
   Eventually there will be a recession, because if there is one
clearly demonstrable trait of economies is that they run in cycles.
Sooner or later expansions get out of hand, inflation begins,
recession ensues.
   While recession is viewed as an event to avoid, it can be argued
that it is necessary for clearing the way for the next expansion.
But to view it that way might be more than the human mind can
accept.
   No less acceptable, however, than the reign of terror in the
forecasts of things to come that destroy the calm of the present.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday April 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:Doo-wop Adv02   04-26 0956</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Doo-wop, Adv 02,0983</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, May 2 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Doo-wop Lives in Philly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sound can still be heard in the city:
four or five voices working on a street corner, in a resonant
subway tunnel, maybe up on the roof.
   Doo-wop crested 25 or 30 years ago, with hits such as ``Earth
Angel,'' ``Under the Boardwalk'' and Philadelphia's own Silhouettes
singing ``Get a Job,'' but it's never gone away.
   ``In the early '60s, this music was disappearing as a trend. But
for the past four or five years it's coming back as an underground
situation,'' said Stan Weaver, tenor with the Zip Codes.
   The hopping and bobbing doo-wop sound now turns up in
commercials for McDonalds, Kentucky Fried Chicken and Levi's blue
jeans. But Philadelphia's street corners can still attract some
harmony on a warm evening with a group of guys with nothing but a
pitch pipe to get started on the right key.
   Doo-wop was city music _ New York, Philadelphia, Los Angeles _
and that's where it survives.
   In Philadelphia, Charlie Horner's ``Rhythm and Blues Show'' on
WXPN-FM keeps the flame alive. About 30 singers, who couldn't
afford instruments as teen-agers and don't want them now, were in
the studio recently to help Horner celebrate his 13th year on the
air.
   Horner travels 75 miles from his album-packed home in South
Bound Brook, N.J., to west Philadelphia to ``spin the sides'' every
Saturday afternoon.
   ``It's like having a a second job, but a good portion of my
paycheck goes into records,'' said Horner, a chemist.
   With tens of thousands of records stacked on the floor, couch
and tables of his New Jersey apartment, Horner has plenty of tunes
from which to choose.
   And with a man who spends every spare moment and all his spare
change on this music, don't call them oldies or nostalgia; they're
terms that make Horner wince. To him, these songs aren't locked in
the past, or symbols of a lost era.
   ``The type of music we play on the air is mostly from the '50s,
but that's just an accident of time,'' he said.
   Horner started in college as a deejay on Drexel University's
student-run radio station, then moved on to WXPN.
   He hasn't found any reason to leave a microphone that puts him
at the center of doo-wop singers and fans in Philadelphia.
   During his radio show, Horner fields telephone calls from
singers who recorded the 30- or 35-year-old records he plays.
   Occassionaly, he finds himself as the middleman in a reunion.
The Keystoners credit Horner with bringing the group back together
after 25 years of estrangement. Five years ago they sang in public
for the first time since 1958 and are back recording, hoping to
relive the success of their regional hit, ``Magic Kiss.''
   Most singers, though, realize doo-wop stands little chance of
ever being more than a hobby for them.
   ``You have to love to sing, because you're not going to get rich
off it,'' Horner said.
   ``We're looking forward to something very serious,'' said Harold
Shipman, baritone with Choice, a group that traveled from northern
New Jersey to sing live on Horner's show during the anniversary
special.
   While doo-wop bears the imprint of church choirs and of mellow
quartets such as the Mills Brothers, Horton says the specific
doo-wop sound can be traced to Sonny Til and the Orioles, whose
1948 hit, ``It's Too Soon to Know,'' inspired black teen-agers to
sing on the street corners, Horner said.
   ``He was to blacks what Frank Sinatra was to whites at the
time,'' Horner said.
   Til's group was among the first to use a wordless falsetto, with
other parts singing nonsensical syllables to round out the chord.
   Doo-wop legend has it that The Ravens' bass singer, Jimmy Ricks,
mistakenly started singing his part a few notes early one night,
drawing a gleeful and raucous response from the crowd at the Apollo
Theater in Harlem. The doo-wop bass lead was born. With Ricks
singing lead, the group scored a hit with ``Old Man River.''
   The Orioles' 1949 hit, ``Don't Tell Me So,'' reached No. 1 on
the rhythm and blues charts, while ``Crying in the Chapel'' hit No.
11 on the pop charts, making it one of the first R&B songs to cross
over into the white market.
   ``For black kids, it was something they heard all their lives.
It was white America that suddenly turned on to it in the
mid-'50s,'' Horner said.
   Horner isn't sure when it happened, but at some point he turned
from a fan to a historian of vocal harmony.
   With Karen Caplan, he is working on a book about the Delta
Rhythm Boys, whose style was more an extension of jazz than rhythm
and blues. The Delta Rhythm Boys went to Finland in 1960 when their
popularity in this country waned.
   ``The sad thing is, a lot of forms of American music, while they
have die-hard fans, need mass appeal. It's unfortunate a lot of
black musicians have to go to Europe,'' he said.
   Lee Gains of the Delta Rhythm Boys, ``probably one of the best
bass singers in the history of the planet'' in Horner's estimation,
died July 15, 1987. Seven days later, while singing a spiritual at
the funeral, Hugh Bryant suffered a fatal heart attack.
   With two members of the group dead, Horner is more determined to
chronicle the music and its influences.
   ``People may not appreciate it (the music) now, but might in
2050 and won't know anything about it. I'm trying to preserve the
history of this music before its lost,'' Horner said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, May 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
