<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv29   04-26 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Today, Adv 29,0853</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, April 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Prize For Moslem Leader Delayed For Inquiry At His Request</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials say the postponement in giving the
1988 Templeton Prize for progress in religion to Moslem leader
Inamullah Khan was at his request after some Jewish leaders accused
him of anti-Semitism.
   ``He himself asked for the delay so assurances could be given
that the charges were not valid,'' says the Rev. Wilbert Forker, of
Nassau, the Bahamas, vice president of the Templeton Foundation.
   ``Board members are now looking into it in this country and
abroad.'' He said the postponment was ordered April 5 and the
inquiry was not likely to be concluded until mid-summer.
   Charges that Khan was anti-Semitic came after he was named in
March to receive the $390,000 prize for advancing cooperation among
Moslems, Christians and Jews.
   It had been scheduled for presentation May 10 in London.
   Khan, 73, of Karachi, Pakistan, secretary-general of the World
Moslem Congress, said in a letter to the prize office:
   ``I request that the prize ceremony be delayed, if necessary for
several months, to allow full assurances to be given to the
Templeton judges and the public to clear away untruthful
accusations and misunderstandings.''
   The criticisms were raised by the Anti-Defamation League of
B'nai B'rith, which alleged past anti-Jewish comments by Moslem
Congress officers and in its newsletter.
   Khan says, ``The allegation that the World Moslem Congress ever
issued or mailed from its office any anti-Semitic literature is a
palpable falsehood.''
   He also said in a lengthy memorandum, answering questions
relayed to him by the New York Times:
   ``I can never support anti-Semitic feelings because I am myself
a decendant of Semitic ancestors from the Middle East...I respect
Jews as `People of the Book'; I respect Moses as a prophet of God.''
   However, mentioning a point that outrages Jews _ the United
Nations classifying of Zionism (Jewish nationalism) as racism _
Khan added:
   ``My difference is with the Zionists because the UN General
Assembly has declared Zionism a racist creed.''
   He also said the common Arab description of Israel as the
``Zionist entity'' has no significance. Jews, however,
overwhelmingly resent it.
   Noting that he is a president of the interfaith World Conference
of Religion and Peace, he said, ``I have consistently preached
inter-religious concord and understanding and promoted interfaith
meetings.''
   William P. Thompson, associate general secretary of the
interfaith conference, observed of the controversy:
   ``The prize is not because the winner is a saint but because he
has made some religious progress. Khan has made some remarkable
strides toward greater openness to other religions and respect for
them.''
   Khan had been accused by Abraham H. Foxman, national director of
the ADL, of denying Israel's right to exist. However, Khan said he
backs UN resolution 242, which supports a secure Israel, and also
Palestinian statehood.
   The New York Times said a Congress newsletter in the 1970's
advertised the ``Protocols of the Elders of Zion,'' a anti-Jewish
forgery, and carried other anti-Jewish tracts _ not mentioned in
questions to Khan.
   Foxman said Khan ``may have changed somewhat but not
sufficiently to set him up as a model of interreligious
understanding and reconciliation.''
   Particularly criticizing Khan's reference to Zionism as racism,
Foxman said, ``It reflects a mindset that hasn't changed that
much.''
   Jane Evans, a Jewish leader acquainted with Khan through the
interfaith conference, said he ``has kept open paths of
communication with other religions.''
   But she said he also has shown what Jews see as ``strongly
anti-Semitic views,'' by disparaging Zionism as distinct from
Judaism.
   He reflects a ``very difficult mixture of right and wrong,''
added Ms. Evans, executive director emeritus of the National
Federation of Temple Sisterhoods.
   Much of the criticism of Khan involved alleged Congress
newsletter items a decade or more ago. But Foxman also cited a
June, l986, item about a dinner Khan hosted for Chicago black
Moslem leader Louis Farrakhan.
   Farrakhan has called Judaism a ``dirty religion.''
   Foxman also criticized Khan for a 1985 letter of appreciation to
The Spotlight, a Washington, D.C., newsletter of the Liberty Lobby,
which Foxman describes as virulently anti-Jewish.
   Khan said his ``innocuous'' letter mentioned no religion.
   John Taylor of Geneva Switzerland, general secretary of the
World Conference on Religion and Peace, said the letter was merely
a courteous response to solicited comment.
   ``Almost identical letters were written by Jewish personalities
before knowing the anti-Semitic qualities of the publication,''
Taylor said in a telephone interview.
   ``Most of the accusations against Khan do not reflect personally
on him, but on the distant history of organizations and others...He
distances himself from these institutional aberrations.
   ``Khan has stuck his neck out in some very unfriendly climate to
build bridges of dialogue with Jews, Christians, Hindus and others.
He has risked unpopularity in his own circles to do it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, April 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
