<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC and independent oil exporters are
gathering for a series of meetings aimed at tightening oil supplies
and boosting prices.
   Officials of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
and rival oil producers expressed cautious optimism Monday that an
agreement could be reached this week on joint measures to support
prices.
   ``Any meeting between OPEC and non-OPEC (nations) is important,
but this one is particularly so because prices seem to be weak,''
said Indonesian delegate Subroto, the nation's former oil minister.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of domestically-produced cars and light
trucks have risen slightly in mid-April from the same period last
year, according to automakers.
   Chrysler Corp. said Monday its daily sales rate rose 21.4
percent during the April 11-20 period, while General Motors Corp.
reported a 4.4 percent decline and Ford Motor Co. was off 2.6
percent.
   Sales of all domestically made cars and light trucks totaled
353,314 for the eight-day period, up from 308,240 in the nine-day
period a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes edged up 2.5 percent
in March for the second month in a row, a real estate trade group
says.
   The National Association of Realtors said Monday that existing
single-family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted rate of 3.33
million units last month.
   The March rise matched a 2.5 percent increase in February, but
the sales rate remained 9.8 percent below March 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.P. Stevens & Co. has agreed to be acquired for
$1.22 billion by West Point-Pepperell Inc., which plans to split
the textile giant's assets with a partner and a rival bidder.
   Pepperell, which made its bid in conjunction with NTC Group,
said Monday it will pay $68.50 in cash for each of Stevens 17.8
million outstanding shares under terms of deal forged over the
weekend.
   West Point, Ga.-based Pepperell will sell $530 million in
Stevens assets to the New York investment firm Odyssey Partners,
its rival in the lengthy takeover battle.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three health groups are asking the government
to begin regulating low-tar cigarettes on grounds that advertising
claims for the products make them a drug subject to federal
oversight.
   If accepted by the Food and Drug Administration, agreed to by
Congress and upheld in court, the arguments made by the three
groups on Monday would place the FDA in the ironic position of
regulating cigarettes low in tar and nicotine, but not other
cigarettes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has let stand an Arizona
telephone company's ban on sexually explicit dial-up message
services.
   In the first ``dial-a-porn'' case to reach the high court, the
justices without comment declined Monday to hear arguments that
Mountain Bell's refusal to carry sexually explicit message services
violates free-speech rights.
   The court's action came a week after Congress sent to President
Reagan a bill that would ban all dial-a-porn services, which are
available to callers through ``976'' exchanges and AT&T's ``900''
long-distance lines.
</TEXT>
