   U.S. and Soviet publishers have agreed on joint
publication of the first Russian-language magazine devoted to
personal computers, tapping a market of about 100,000 users.
   International Data Group Inc., which publishes PC World and
InfoWorld magazines, said Monday that the venture with Radio i
Sviaz, a Soviet communications industry publisher, was the first
joint effort of its kind.
   The first issue of PC World USSR is scheduled to hit Soviet
newsstands at the end of June.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has
delayed by two months the effective date of a rule designed to make
it easier for investors to shop for mutual funds.
   The commission said Monday that mutual funds can wait until July
1 before they must calculate yield in a standardized way so that
consumers can readily compare the track records of competing funds.
   When the commission decided on the new rule in January, it set
May 1 as the effective date but the industry asked for more time to
adjust computer and accounting systems.
</TEXT>
