<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   04-26 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Domestic Auto Makers Report Modest Mid-April Sales Increase</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic auto sales rose slightly during
mid-April, although among the biggest automakers only Chrysler
Corp. recorded car sales gains in the period.
   Sales of U.S.-made cars and light trucks totaled 353,314 from
April 11-20, up from 308,240 a year earlier, a 1.9 percent gain in
daily sales, domestic automakers reported Monday.
   There were eight sales days in the period this year and nine
days in the period last year. The percentage changes compare
average daily sales, not straight totals.
   The daily sales rate for light trucks rose 3.2 percent, while
car sales rose 1.2 percent.
   Chrysler Corp. posted a 21.4 percent increase in car sales from
a soft performance in the year earlier period. Car sales declined
4.4 percent at General Motors Corp. and 2.6 percent at Ford Motor
Co. from strong mid-April 1987 periods.
   GM car sales totaled 112,344 in mid-April, compared with Ford's
65,626 and Chrysler's 33,842.
   ``I think that April is going to be a month in which you are
going to see auto sales go back to some sort of sustainable rate,''
said Jeanette Garretty, an industry analyst with Bank of America in
San Francisco.
   She said the easing sales were not surprising after automakers'
incentives kept sales brisker than expected for most of the first
quarter.
   Ray Windecker, an analyst at Ford, said sales incentives had
pushed industry sales to a 7.6 million seasonally adjusted annual
rate in April 1987, a year that ended up averaging a 7.1 million
rate. This year's mid-April sales were at a 7.5 million seasonally
adjusted annual rate.
   ``These are good substantial sales, against very strong sales
last year,'' Windecker said. ``It's differences in timing of
incentives more than anything else.''
   Among foreign manufacturers making cars in U.S. plants, American
Honda, which moved more production to the United States, sold
10,738 of its U.S.-made cars in the period, up from 6,488 a year
earlier.
   Nissan USA's sales of 2,950 U.S.-made cars represented a 19.3
percent drop in daily sales; Toyota sold 1,396, a 17.7 percent
increase; and Volkswagen sold 1,375, a 4.7 percent increase.
   Sales of imported cars and trucks are reported at the end of
each month.
</TEXT>
