<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Media     04-26 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Media,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Belo Reports 59 Percent Earnings Drop In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A.H. Belo Corp. said Monday its earnings declined
by 59 percent in the first quarter of 1988 from the same period
last year, due to higher operating costs and weak advertising
demand.
   The media company posted a profit of $896,000, or 9 cents per
share, on revenue of $87.3 million during the three months ended
March 31. That compared with earnings of $2.2 million, or 20 cents
per share on revenue of $87.5 million in first quarter 1987.
   Excluding revenue from two Denver radio stations sold in 1987,
first quarter revenue would have been up by $1.9 million from a
year earlier, Belo stated.
   The company attributed the profit decline to higher broadcast
programming costs, higher newsprint costs and weak advertising
demand.
   Belo owns The Dallas Morning News and Dallas-Fort Worth Suburban
Newspapers Inc., publisher of seven community newspapers. It also
owns and operates five network-affiliated television stations.
   The Dallas Morning News' publishing revenue dipped to $50.7
million from $50.9 million a year earlier due to a sharply lower
volume of advertising, Belo stated.
   Broadcasting revenue rose only slightly during the quarter, but
was up 6.1 percent if revenue from the divested radio stations was
excluded, the company said.
</TEXT>
