<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Boeing     04-26 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Boeing,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing Profit Up 15 Percent In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. said Monday its first quarter profit
rose by 15 percent from a year earlier, aided by reduced spending
on research, development and new business expenses.
   Boeing had net earnings of $136 million, or 89 cents a share, on
sales of $3.61 billion in the quarter ended March 31. That compared
with a profit of $118 million, or 76 cents a share, on sales of
$3.76 billion for the first quarter of 1987.
   Frank Shrontz, Boeing's chairman and chief execurive, said the
increase in first quarter profits was due primarily to lower levels
of research, development and other expenses for new commercial
jetliners, future military and space programs, and computer and
electronics work. A lower federal income tax rate and increases in
other income also helped, he said.
   Shrontz said the lower expenses were offset partly by higher
research, development and production costs for commuter aircraft,
performance problems on military aircraft work and a higher share
of costs on government contracts.
   During the first quarter, Boeing received orders for 129
commercial jets and six de Havilland turboprop planes, with a total
value of $4.7 billion. That compares with orders totaling $3.5
billion in first-quarter 1987.
   On Monday, Boeing announced a $1.4 billion order by
International Leisure Group, the parent company of Britain's Air
Europe, for 30 Boeing jetliners. That order includes 22 757-200s
and eight 737-400s, subject to the completion of financing, and was
scheduled for delivery beginning in 1989.
   Government and foreign military sales fell $200 million to $1.1
billion for the quarter, but Shrontz said military sales for the
year were expected to be slightly higher than in 1987.
   Boeing had a backlog of $38 billion in unfinished orders at the
end of the first quarter, up from $33.2 billion at the end of 1987.
</TEXT>
