<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   04-26 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quarterly GNP, Corporate Profits, Advance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with reports on gross national
product and corporate profits; uppicks 2nd graf pvs: Sales of...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy, shrugging off the effects of the October stock
market collapse, grew at a 2.3 percent annual rate in the first
three months of 1988, the government said today.
   It also said after-tax corporate profits rose an even faster 2.6
percent in the last three months of 1987. This was an upward
revision from a month ago, when the government put the increase in
business profits at 1.6 percent.
   A strong increase in consumer spending and the biggest surge in
business investment in more than four years fueled the gross
national product advance, the Commerce Department said, in its
first look at overall economic performance this year.
   The GNP report should put to rest any fears that the record
508-point drop in the stock market on Oct. 19 would topple the
country into a recession, economists said.
   In addition, the rate of inflation slowed, with a price measure
tied to the GNP rising at an annual rate of 2.4 percent, down from
a 2.7 percent increase in the fourth quarter.
   The reports came amid a continuing modest rebound in home sales
from a winter slump, a recovery experts say reflects a decline in
mortgage interest rates.
   Sales of existing homes edged up 2.5 percent last month, the
National Association of Realtors said Monday as it reported that
single-family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted rate of 3.33
million units.
   Despite the March rise, which followed a 2.5 percent increase in
February, the rate of sales remained 9.8 percent below that of
March 1987. The sales pace had dipped in November, December and
January after mortgage rates increased.
   Meanwhile, trading on financial markets was quiet as investors
awaited today's release of first quarter gross national product
figures, reflecting the economy's growth rate from January through
March.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed
22.21 points to 2,037.30. Trading was moderate.
   The dollar was mixed, and many dealers attributed the currency's
behavior partly to uncertainty about the GNP report. Bond prices
dipped, pushing interest rates higher.
   The home sales increase was expected to carry over into April,
said John A. Tuccillo, the realtors' chief economist.
   Mark Obrinsky, an economist with the U.S. League of Savings
Institutions, said interest rates likely would to rise slowly and
steadily this year, but predicted the rise would disrupt sales less
than the sharp jumps by interest rates in 1987.
   A year ago, 30-year, fixed-rate mortgages bottomed out at just
above 9 percent. They rose in spurts, topping 11.5 percent in early
October. Rates eased after the stock market crash, dipping just
below 10 percent in February and March before rising again to 10.3
percent last week.
   The March sales increase was accompanied by a 4.1 percent rise
in prices to a national median, or midpoint, of $88,700, from
$88,100 in February. Tuccillo predicted only modest increases for
the rest of the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
