<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ContinentalTrial     04-26 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Continental Trial,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Argues Bank Policy, Not Scheme, Caused Continental Loan
Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's case against three men accused
of defrauding Continental Illinois National Bank is as shaky as a
broken three-legged stool, a defense attorney contends.
   ``If any leg is missing, it won't stand up, and at any point in
this case, one or more of the legs are missing.'' said attorney
Burck Bailey, who represents William Patterson, former head of oil
and gas lending at the failed Penn Square Bank of Oklahoma City.
   The government charged that Patterson joined with Tulsa oil
driller Jere Sturgis and another bank officer, John Lytle, in a
scheme to defraud the Chicago bank. The three men pleaded innocent
to charges of fraud and misapplication of funds.
   Closing arguments in the 6{-week trial before U.S. District
Judge Milton Shadur were expected to be completed today before the
case goes to the jury.
   In his closing argument Monday, Bailey contended that
Continental was saddled with troublesome oil and energy loans
because of an aggressive lending policy, not because of a fraud
scheme.
   Between July 1981 and 1982, when the alleged fraud scheme took
place, ``there was the widely held view that oil and gas prices
would rise so quickly that time would take care of any problems
with these loans,'' Bailey said.
   Lytle, a former Continental vice president, was accused of
taking kickbacks in exchange for funding high-risk energy loans
from Continental Illinois National Bank & Trust Co. to Penn Square
customers.
   The government also contended Lytle and Sturgis engaged in an
investment scheme in which Sturgis inflated the return on Lytle's
investment threefold so he could receive a favorable loan from
Continental. Sturgis never received the loan but made several
attempts, according to court records.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Ted Helwig portrayed Lytle, a 20-year
employee at Continental, as a bank officer who needed the money
because he was living well beyond his means.
   ``He had become so completely dependent on Bill Patterson, he no
longer had the interest of Continental first and foremost,'' Helwig
added.
   The indictment cited Lytle's involvement in $44 million in loans
made by Continental to 12 Penn Square customers. It did not say how
much was recovered by the Chicago bank, which came to the brink of
collapse in 1984 in part because of its troubled energy loans.
   The loans to customers of Penn Square, which failed in July
1982, were approved at about the same time Lytle received nearly
$600,000 in kickbacks from Patterson in the form of unsecured
personal loans from Penn Square, Helwig said.
   Lytle, impassive during government arguments, took notes Monday.
He sat facing the jury, wearing a brown suit and scuffed penny
loafers _ one with a hole in the sole.
   His attorney, James Streicker, noted that even when Continental
officials began reviewing Lytle's potential conflict-of-interest no
one told him to stop making loans to Penn Square customers.
   ``Because in spite of all the problems, Continental Bank wanted
the business,'' Streicker said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
