<1ST_LINE>u f PM-IBM-MCI     04-26 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IBM-MCI,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Giant May Sell Its Stake in MCI</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. may sell its 16 percent
chunk of MCI Communications Corp. back to the company over the next
several years, the head of the world's biggest computer company
said.
   The disclosure by IBM Chairman John F. Akers substantiated
earlier eports that MCI wants to repurchase the stake, which IBM
bought three years ago when the long-distance telecommunications
company was weaker than it is now. MCI's profit and revenue have
since risen significantly.
   Akers' statement also further weakened a theory that IBM's
original interest in MCI would lead to a major confrontation with
American Telephone & Telegraph Co., the long-distance phone giant
that also has been trying to develop a computer vending business.
   Since then, AT&T's performance in the computer market has been
considered disappointing, while IBM's attempts to develop its
telecommunications business also has been slow.
   Akers spoke in response to a shareholder question Monday at
IBM's annual meeting in Richmond, Va. He was asked about future
plans for the company's investment in MCI.
   ``We don't have any plans to increase our holdings with MCI,
although contractually they can ask us to, if they so desire,''
Akers said. He added that was unlikely because of MCI's desire to
repurchase the stock.
   ``I would expect that would come to pass and that will be the
action that you'll see over the next several years,'' Akers said.
   IBM initially made the investment, then valued at about $427
million, under an agreement whereby MCI acquired the assets of
Satellite Business Systems, a competing long-distance phone company
started by IBM in 1975.
</TEXT>
