<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0335</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved moderately higher today,
extending gains in the previous session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 20 points
on Monday, was up another 3.98 points at 2,041.28 after a half-hour
of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by nearly 2 to 1 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 613 up, 315 down and
525 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 20.18 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Before trading started, the government reported that the the
economy grew at a 2.3 percent annual rate in the first three months
of 1988.
   That was down from growth of 4.8 percent in the October-December
quarter, but the first-quarter growth figure was in line with most
pre-announcement forecasts.
   The Commerce Department said the first-quarter growth in the
gross national product was propelled by a strong increase in
consumer spending and the biggest surge in business investment in
more than four years.
   In addition, the government said the growth was accompanied by a
slowdown in the rate of inflation, with a price measure tied to the
GNP rising at an annual rate of 2.4 percent, down from a 2.7
percent increase in the fourth quarter.
   Among the actively-traded issues in the early going, Occidental
Petroleum was off [ at 27], Lucky Stores was up } at 54} and
American Telephone & Telegraph was unchanged at 27\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.33 to 148.54. At the American Stock Exchange, the composite
market index rose 0.60 to 299.55.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 22.21 points
to 2,037.30.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 3 on the
NYSE, with 932 up, 584 down and 483 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 156.95 million shares, against 152.52 million in the
previous session.
