<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Koppers     04-26 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Koppers,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Majority Backs Bid By Beazer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group led by British
industrialist Brian Beazer says its $1.7 billion hostile takeover
bid for Koppers Co. has been backed by a majority of the cement
company's shareholders.
   BNS Inc., the takeover company Beazer formed with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. and National Westminster Bank, disclosed Monday
that as of last Friday, 13.9 million of Koppers' common shares, or
53.4 percent, had been tendered in response to its $60-per-share
offer.
   If BNS were able to consummate its offer, those shares plus the
2.1 million BNS already holds, would give it 56.9 percent of
Koppers' stock.
   But BNS is barred by two federal court orders from actually
purchasing more shares unless and until legal challenges to its
offer are overturned.
   One of those challenges, which claims the takeover would violate
antitrust laws, will stand at least until May 13 when the federal
court in San Francisco hears an appear from BNS.
   Koppers declined to comment on Beazer's tally, but Koppers
spokesman Roger Beidler noted shareholders who have tendered their
shares can still withdraw them at any time before the BNS offer
expires.
   Koppers has said it is studying ways to financially restructure
in order to increase the value of its stock.
</TEXT>
