<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoTalks 1stLead-Writethru   04-26 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Talks, 1st Lead-Writethru,0732</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW Bargainers Return to Table After Four-Hour Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs to UPDATE with Stepp comments on K-cars after
6th graf, Angering the ... in 1989; picks up 7th graf pvs bgng: At
the...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early contract negotiations between
Chrysler Corp. and the United Auto Workers have soured but remain
alive, despite a ``no-show'' protest by union representatives and
other frictions inside and outside of actual bargaining.
   UAW negotiators and union leaders scheduled to begin this week's
meetings with Chrysler on Monday morning instead met privately for
four hours and debated whether to continue the talks, said UAW
spokesman Bob Barbee.
   While Chrysler's team cooled its heels, union negotiators
discussed the rank-and-file's angry reaction to several
announcements last week _ such as disclosure of Chrysler chairman
Lee Iacocca's eight-figure wages for 1987 _ that seemed timed to
doom the talks.
   ``The talks may be in fatal trouble already but it's a little
too early to tell,'' said Harley Shaiken, labor and technology
expert at the University of California at San Diego.
   The union and the No. 3 automaker are negotiating a replacement
for a contract expiring Sept. 14. The contract covers at least
66,000 active and laid-off workers in 15 states and 65,000 retirees.
   Angering the rank and file were revelations of executive
compensation for 1987 that included nearly $18 million for Iacocca,
and the planned transfer of waning K-car production from two U.S.
plants to one in Mexico in 1989.
   The union will urge Chrysler to keep producing K-cars _ the
Dodge Aries and Plymouth Reliant _ at its Jefferson Avenue plant in
Detroit, said Marc Stepp, UAW vice president and head of the
union's Chrysler department.
   The Jefferson Avenue plant produces four-door K-cars while a
Toluca, Mexico factory produces two-door models.
   Chrysler is scheduled to move Omni and Horizon production from a
plant it is closing in Wisconsin to the Jefferson Avenue Plant this
summer and said last week it would consolidate K-car production in
Mexico.
   Stepp said union officials think the plant can produce both
cars. ``We would urge the corporation to change its plan,'' he said.
   At the bargaining table, talks that were supposed to last two to
three weeks as the two sides fit an industry-pattern contract to
Chrysler began to drag as Chrysler made proposals guaranteed to be
rejected.
   Chrysler Vice President Anthony St. John has publicly said he
will work within the job-protecting pattern contract already in
force at Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp., but union
officials say Chrysler bargainers are strongly resisting it.
   ``They have not come up with any pattern proposals. Chrysler's
first offer is garbage _ all take-aways. We're not going to take
any concessions,'' said Tony DeFrancesco, an official at UAW Local
624 in Syracuse, N.Y.
   DeFrancesco was among nearly 100 officials of local unions at
Chrysler plants nationwide who gathered in Huntsville, Ala.,
Thursday night and Friday. At the meeting, the local leaders heard
and booed company proposals and urged bargainers to break off
talks, according to DeFrancesco and others who attended.
   Chrysler spokesman Lloyd Northard said he still believed the two
sides would reach an early settlement, which had been intended to
mend their damaged relationship.
   Chrysler seeks a minimum age for early retirement instead of the
current ``30-and-out'' provision, which is the right to retire
after 30 years in the factory regardless of age. It wants workers
to take vacations only when plants are shut down, or lose them and
wants workers who don't join pre-paid health plans to pay $35 a
month in insurance fees.
   The automaker also wants widespread adoption of Japanese-style
plant work agreements at a time when some plants that have accepted
them are hitting snags in putting the so-called Modern Operating
Agreements into practice.
   Workers who made deep sacrifices that helped save Chrysler in
the early 1980s expected a return to normality once Chrysler
returned to profitability. Instead, Chrysler early this year
announced plans to close a 5,500-worker former American Motors
Corp. assembly plant in Kenosha, Wis., that it had said would stay
open at least five more years.
   Chrysler's later attempt to sell its 28,000-worker Acustar Inc.
met with strike threats and other strong union opposition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
