<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pushed ahead today, extending their
advance of the past three sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which rose more than 20
points on Monday, was up another 16.91 points at 2,052.88 after 90
minutes of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by 3 to 1 in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 940 up, 303 down and 491
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 50.58 million shares as of 11
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Before trading started, the Commerce Department reported that
the the economy grew at a 2.3 percent annual rate in the first
three months of 1988.
   That was down from growth of 4.8 percent in the October-December
quarter, but was in line with most economists' forecasts for the
January-March period.
   The report also said the rate of inflation had slowed, with a
price measure tied to the GNP rising at an annual rate of 2.4
percent, down from a 2.7 percent increase in the fourth quarter.
   Analysts said the report contained little that was unexpected,
and said it had little effect on the movement of stock prices.
   But by the same token, the report failed to dampen recent
expectations that the economy continues to show signs of strength
despite earlier fears that it would bog down after last October's
market crash.
   Stock prices have also benefitted in recent days from some
strong earnings reports.
   Among the actively-traded issues on the NYSE, Tandem was up 1~
at 19[, American Telephone & Telegraph was unchanged at 27\ and
International Business Machines was up | at 114{.
   Lucky Stores was up 1[ at 55[ after announcing it has received
some buyout proposals.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
1.11 to 149.32. At the American Stock Exchange, the composite
market index rose 1.49 to 300.44.
