<2ND_LINE>PM-Earns Oil,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco Says 1st Quarter Earnings Doubled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc., the nation's third-largest oil
company, today announced that its first-quarter earnings rose by
105 percent compared with the same period last year.
   The White Plains, N.Y.-based company said it earned $242
million, or $1.00 per share, on $8.7 billion of revenue, vs. $118
million, or 49 cents per share, on $8.5 billion in 1987
first-quarter sales.
   The latest earnings included a $66 million gain on the sale of
Texaco's interest in an offshore Angola joint venture, as well as
$29 million gain on foreign currency transactions, which compared
with a $7 million loss in the same period last year, the company
said.
   It also included an increase of corporate and nonoperating
charges to $249 million from $100 million in the 1987 first quarter.
   That hike was due in part ``to the recognition in the 1987
quarter of $73 million in nonrecurring benefits relating to prior
years income tax adjustments,'' Texaco said.
   ``The legal and related costs associated with the bankruptcy
proceedings and the financing expenses incident to the company's
ultimate emergence from Chapter 11 also contributed to the increase
in corporate expenses,'' the company said.
   Otherwise, Texaco President James W. Kinnear said its
performance was helped by improved domestic refining and marketing
margins and strong petrochemical results.
   Slumping crude prices were offset by improved earnings from
natural gas operations due to settlement of certain take-or-pay
issues and higher natural gas sales prices and volumes, the company
said.
   Texaco emerged from Chapter 11 earlier this month in a
reorganization that included a $3 billion payment to Pennzoil Co.
to settle a $10.3 judgment held against Texaco by Pennzoil
resulting from a jury's decision that Texaco had improperly
interfered with a Pennzoil acquisition of part of Getty Oil Co.
</TEXT>
