<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-UnitedLawsuit     04-26 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-United Lawsuit,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilots Union Sues United Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines pilots are suing the airline, its
parent, Allegis Corp., and the Machinists union in an effort to
strike down contract provisions they say could block an employee
takeover of United.
   The lawsuit was filed Monday in U.S. District Court in Chicago
by the Airline Pilots Association, said Hank Krakowski, a union
spokesman.
   The suit challenges two provisions in a November agreement
between United and the Machinists union, Krakowski said.
   ``We want a judgment from the court to declare that these
provisions are illegal, so we can move forward in our attempts to
affect employee ownership of United Airlines,'' he said.
   One provision prohibits the union from participating in an
employee ownership plan unless the Machinists union agrees to the
terms.
   The other contested provision would give the Machinists the
option of receiving substantial pay increases, reopening their
contract or striking in the event of a change in control of Allegis.
   The pilots' lawsuit alleges that the provisions, called
``protective covenants,'' are part of an illegal campaign by United
directors to ``entrench themselves in office at the expense of
Allegis shareholders,'' the union stated.
   ``We haven't seen the suit so we have no comment,'' said United
spokesman Joe Hopkins.
   Dan Sheehy, another United spokesman, said the provisions
addressed in the suit are part of a three-year agreement between
the company and the union regarding work and wage rules.
   ``Details of it aren't for public consumption,'' he said.
   A spokesman for the Machinists union could not be reached for
comment Monday night.
   United pilots have been working toward an employee takeover for
about a year, but the Machinists union has opposed the plan.
   United pilots made an unsuccessful $4.5 billion bid for the
airline last April, opposing Allegis' diversification into a travel
services conglomerate. The offer led to a proxy fight by a New York
investor group, Coniston Partners, to unseat Allegis directors, and
Allegis Chairman Richard Ferris later resigned.
   Allegis directors agreed to sell the company's hotel and rental
car businesses and to drop the Allegis name as part of a $3.65
billion restructuring plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     04-26 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0409</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved broadly higher today, as
a new government report indicated the economy continues to show
some strength.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 20 points
on Monday, rose another 14.10 points to 2,050.07 by noon on Wall
Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 2 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 948 up, 368 down and
512 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 74.44 million shares as of
noontime compared with 87.93 million shares at the same point
Monday.
   Before trading started, the government reported that the the
economy grew at a 2.3 percent annual rate in the first three months
of 1988.
   That was down from growth of 4.8 percent in the October-December
quarter, but fell well within most forecasts.
   Charles Jensen, a technical analyst for MKI Securities Corp.,
said that even though the latest growth figure had been
anticipated, the market took some encouragement from it anyway.
   ``It wasn't too low to dim hopes that the economic recovery
would continue,'' he said.
   He also noted that the dollar and bond prices seem to have
stabilized in recent days, and said that has helped the psychology
of some stock investors.
   The market has also benefitted in recent days from some strong
corporate earnings reports.
   In its latest economic report, the government also said
inflation slowed, with a price measure tied to the GNP rising at an
annual rate of 2.4 percent, down from a 2.7 percent increase in the
fourth quarter.
   Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer for First Albany Corp.,
said that was a slower inflation rate than some analysts had
expected.
   But he said the stock market is less concerned about the recent
past than with the future and is already looking toward a report on
the Index of Leading Indicators scheduled for release later this
week.
   Among actively-traded issues on the NYSE, Texaco was off [ at
48], Tandem was up 1~ at 19[ and American Telephone & Telegraph was
off [ at 27[.
   Lucky Stores was up 1] at 55] on takeover speculation.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.95 to 149.16. At the American Stock Exchange, the composite
market index rose 1.88 to 300.83.
