<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ManufacturingEmployment Bjt   04-26 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Manufacturing Employment, Bjt,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manufacturing Employment Plummets, Some Business Buck Trend</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT; Manufactures is cq in 3rd graf.
A version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of Americans manufacturing things
for a living has fallen in this decade, although such areas as
transportation equipment, plastics and furniture are bucking the
trend, the Census Bureau reported Tuesday.
   Overall, employment in manufacturing businesses fell by 731,900
between 1982 and 1986, the bureau said.
   That represented a decline of 4 percent, to 17,086,200 workers,
according to preliminary statistics from the 1986 Annual Survey of
Manufactures.
   More recently, however, manufacturing employment has been
increasing as the devalued dollar boosts sale of U.S. goods abroad.
According to the Labor Department, manufacturing jobs rose by
400,000 between June 1987 and March 1988, a period not covered by
the Census Bureau's survey.
   Between 1982 and 1986, the hardest-hit sector was machinery
manufacturing, which lost 325,700 jobs. Imports were a major reason
for the 15 percent decline to 1,863,000 employees in businesses
making heavy industrial and construction machinery, said Kenneth
Hansen, a Census Bureau analyst.
   Another area affected by imported products in recent years _
apparel and textile products _ saw employment fall 14 percent to
1,016,500 in 1986. That represented a loss of 172,500 jobs, the
report said.
   Primary metal industries also suffered, losing 164,900 jobs to
fall to a total of 689,200 in 1986.
   Manufacture of leather goods saw a loss of 70,000 jobs,
representing a 35 percent decline to 1986 employment of 129,800.
   Tobacco products suffered a 20 percent job loss between 1982 and
1986, with employment falling to 46,100 in the continuation of a
20-year trend.
   On the positive side, companies making transportation equipment
added 173,600 workers over the period, an 11 percent increase to
1,769,500.
   Transportation equipment is a wide-ranging field including
aircraft, trucks and trailers, automobiles, ships, motor homes and
even some defense equipment such as missiles, Hansen said.
   Computer products have helped boost employment in electronic
industries slightly, the study showed. That area employed 1,941,400
people in 1986, up 26,900 from 1982.
   Printing and publishing added 84,400 people over the period and
wood products and furniture-making also showed growth.
   Nationally, while total employment in manufacturing fell between
1982 and 1986, payroll was up from $204.5 billion to $231.7 billion.
   Here is a rundown of industry groups, employment in 1986 and
change from 1982:
   _All industries: 17,086,200, down 731,900.
   Gainers:
   _Transportation equipment, 1,769,500, up 173,600.
   _Printing and publishing, 1,376,200, up 84,400.
   _Rubber and plastics products, 741,300, up 59,600.
   _Lumber and wood products, 619,500, up 43,100.
   _Furniture and fixtures, 466,700, up 30,700.
   _Electric and electronic equipment, 1,941,400, up 26,900.
   Losers:
   _Machinery, except electrical, 1,863,000, down 325,700.
   _Apparel and other textile products, 1,016,500, down 172,500.
   _Primary metal industries, 689,200, down 164,900.
   _Food and kindred products: 1,408,900, down 78,800.
   _Textile mill products, 644,300, down 73,100.
   _Chemicals and allied products, 801,600, down 71,000.
   _Leather and leather products, 129,800, down 70,000.
   _Miscellaneous manufacturing, 326,100, down 56,500.
   _Fabricated metal products, 1,419,500, down 40,200.
   _Instruments and related products, 585,400, down 38,200.
   _Petroleum and coal products, 124,500, down 27,100.
   _Stone, clay and glass products, 514,100, down 17,400.
   _Tobacco products, 46,100, down 11,800.
   _Paper and allied products, 602,600, down 3,000.
</TEXT>
