<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0041,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Jump 23.2 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rose sharply Tuesday as a buoyant New
York market injected added confidence into London trading, which
already was bullish on takeover news.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed up
23.2 points, or 1.3 percent, to 1,800.8.
   Volume was modest at 428.0 million shares, although up from the
307.1 million shares traded Monday.
   Swiss coffee and chocolate maker Nestle S.A.'s offer of 2.1
billion pounds, or $3.95 billion, for British confectioner Rowntree
PLC, dominated the market from start to finish.
   The $16.73-a-share price exceeds the $11.84 paid by Jacobs
Suchard S.A., another Swiss coffee and chocolate company, when it
increased its stake in Rowntree to 14.9 percent earlier this month
and said it was seeking a 25-percent holding.
   By the close, Rowntree was up around $3.31 to $17.45.
   The surge pulled other food stocks up with it.
   The market broadened its advance through the day, helped by the
rise in New York as London trading wound down.
   Only eight of the 100-share index stocks finished lower, while
77 finished higher, and the rest unchanged.
</TEXT>
