<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Media,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington Post Profit Soars on One-Time Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Washington Post Co. said Tuesday its
first-quarter profit soared from a year ago mainly because of a
huge gain on the sale of its cellular telephone operations in
Florida.
   The company said its profit rose to $144.8 million, or $11.25 a
share, in the quarter compared with $18.6 million, or $1.45 a
share, a year earlier.
   Revenue for the quarter rose 7.7 percent to $321.2 million from
$298.4 million a year earlier.
   The latest results included a non-recurring, after-tax gain of
$115.7 million from the sale of the Florida cellular telephone
operations.
   Without that gain, the company said its first quarter results
would have risen 56.3 percent to $29.1 million, or $2.26 a share.
   Both newspaper division and television stations revenue were up
10 percent, the Post said. It said cable TV revenue increased 17
percent and Newsweek's first-quarter revenue was up by 4 percent.
</TEXT>
