<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-MartinMarietta     04-26 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Martin Marietta,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Martin Marietta's Profit Up 15.4 Percent in First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Marietta Corp. reported that its
profit jumped 15.4 percent in the first quarter from a year
earlier, boosted by improved results from all its businesses.
   The diversified aerospace and electronics company said Tuesday
that its first-quarter profit rose to $50.9 million, or 96 cents a
share, from $44.1 million, or 80 cents a share, in the first three
months of 1987.
   First-quarter sales increased to $1.3 billion from $1.1 billion
a year earlier. The company reported a record backlog of $11.1
billion in sales for the latest quarter.
   ``The improvement in first-quarter results supports our
expectation for further solid earnings progress in the balance of
the year,'' said Norman R. Augustine, the company's vice chairman
and chief executive.
   Martin Marietta delivered the first of its new Titan 4 rockets
to Cape Canaveral, Fla., in January for a planned launch in
October. The new launch vehicle can put 10,000 pounds of payload
into a stationary orbit 22,300 miles high.
</TEXT>
