<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-HealthCare     04-26 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Health Care,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baxter Travenol Profit Up 38 Percent In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEERFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baxter Travenol Laboratories Inc.
reported that its profit jumped 38 percent in the first quarter
from a year earlier, boosted by improved sales.
   The manufacturer of health care products and equipment said
Tuesday that its first-quarter profit rose to $91 million, or 31
cents a share, from $66 million, or 22 cents a share, in the first
three months of 1987.
   Sales expanded 12 percent, to more than $1.6 billion, including
$355 million in international sales. The dollar's weakness against
major foreign currencies contributed about $41 million to
international sales during the quarter, Baxter Travenol said. A
lower dollar makes U.S. products more competitive abroad.
   Sales of hospital products and services, the company's largest
business, contributed $880 million to revenue. All business sectors
showed improved revenue, but the industrial products division was
the best performer with sales rising 25 percent to $95 million, the
company said.
   ``Our first-quarter operating results point to another excellent
year for Baxter,'' said Vernon R. Loucks Jr., chairman and chief
executive officer. ``Our strong sales growth reflects a
continuation of an improving U.S. hospital market.''
   The company will seek shareholders' approval next month to
change its name to Baxter International Inc.
</TEXT>
