<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Soar On Acreage Set-Aside Talk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices rose sharply in late
trading Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, closing as much as
18 cents higher.
   The late surge on heavy trading volume followed comments made in
Washington by an Agriculture Department official that farmers
signing up for price support programs had agreed to take 3.5
million acres out of corn production instead of the 1.5 million
acres that the market had anticpated, said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   The acreage could not be used for soybean production, which adds
new tension to a market already stressed by fears of tight supplies.
   ``That was the catalyst,'' Lespinasse said.
   He said speculation that Pakistan might be offered 50,000 tons
of U.S. soybean oil under a subsidized export program added further
fuel to the soybean rally.
   Corn and wheat futures advanced in sympathy with soybeans,
analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was } cent to 1} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.12 a bushel; corn was } cent to
1} cents higher with May at $2.00{ a bushel; oats were unchanged to
{ cent higher with May at $1.65{ a bushel; soybeans were 16 cents
to 18 cents higher with May at $6.77 a bushel.
</TEXT>
