<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1604EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MediaGeneral Bjt   04-26 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Media General, Bjt,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takeover Fight Involves Court, Advertising, Proxies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California investor and television game
show magnate Burt Sugarman, whose sucesses include ``The Dating
Game,'' wants a match that will last with Media General Inc.
   But the family that controls the media empire through a special
class of stock hopes shareholders will give Sugarman's $1.6 billion
takeover bid the cutoff treatment accorded many contestants on
another Sugarman program _ ``The Gong Show.''
   The takeover fight under way in advance of Media General's May
20 shareholders meeting has been waged on three fronts _ in court,
in proxy materials and in newspaper advertisements.
   The battle is being monitored closely by major publishers
including the Washington Post Co., the New York Times Co., and Dow
Jones & Co., among other media companies that have dual classes of
stock intended to keep control in the hands of a few people. The
Graham family is seeking to tighten its grip on Washington Post
with a charter change to be voted on next month in reaction to the
bid for Media General.
   Sugarman, through two companies he heads, offered in February to
pay $61.50 a share for the nearly 90 percent of Media General stock
he does not control.
   But the family of Media General Chairman D. Tennant Bryan
declined the offer, expressing a desire to keep the Richmond-based
company independent.
   Sugarman controls just over 10 percent of the 28 million shares
of Media General's Class A common stock. But the Bryan family owns
71 percent of the more powerful 559,168 outstanding Class B shares,
which elect seven of the company's 10 directors.
   In lawsuits filed last month in U.S. District Court in Richmond,
Media General accused Sugarman of inciting speculation in the
company's stock. Management also wants the court to order Sugarman
to sell his shares.
   Sugarman, meanwhile, asked the court to allow Media General
shareholders to vote as a single class on his offer and maintained
only the three Class A directors should be allowed to consider the
buyout.
   Media General's management contends the buyout requires approval
of two-thirds of each class voting separately, but Sugarman says a
majority vote of the combined Class A and B shares is all that is
necessary for ratification.
   A hearing is set for Wednesday in the court dispute.
   After the suits were filed, Sugarman placed full-page ads in The
Wall Street Journal and two Media General daily newspapers, the
Richmond Times-Dispatch and The Richmond News Leader.
   The ads criticized the company's two-tier stock arrangement and
asked shareholders not to vote on management's proxy statement
until receiving Sugarman's proposals.
   Sugarman also is seeking to be elected to Media General's board
along with his allies, Dallas billionaire Harold C. Simmons and
David Gotterer, vice chairman of the two Sugarman companies that
control the Media General stock, Barris Industries Inc. of Beverly
Hills, Calif. and Giant Group Ltd. of Harleyville, S.C.
   Media General last week launched its own newspaper ad attack in
which it urged shareholders to back the company's slate of Class A
directors. The ads also advised shareholders against acting on
Sugarman's $61.50-per-share offer.
   In addition to Richmond Newspapers Inc., the parent of the
Times-Dispatch and News Leader, Media General also owns the
Winston-Salem Journal in North Carolina, the Tampa Tribune in
Florida, 32 weekly newspapers in southern California and a 40
percent interest in Garden State Newspapers Inc., which owns 18
dailies and four weeklies in eight states.
   Media General also owns television stations WCBD-TV in
Charleston, S.C., WJKS-TV in Jacksonville, Fla., and WXFL-TV in
Tampa, Fla.
   Sugarman's Barris Industries, which takes its name from founder
and TV personality Chuck Barris, is the maker of ``The Dating
Game,'' ``The Newlywed Game'' and ``The Gong Show.'' The Giant
Group is the parent firm of two cement companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880426-0294 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1610EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Cartier     04-26 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cartier,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cartier To Acquire Controlling Interest In Piaget, Baume & Mercier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cartier S.A. said Tuesday it will acquire a
controlling interest in Swiss watchmakers Piaget S.A. and Baume &
Mercier S.A., a move that will give the French luxury products
company a commanding share of the upscale watch market.
   Terms of the transaction were not disclosed, but Cartier
Chairman Alain Perrin said the acquisition should help boost
Cartier's sales to $840 million this year. Piaget and Baume &
Mercier had combined sales of $162 million last year.
   Perrin also said the acquisition will give Cartier control of
more than 40 percent of the $2.2 billion international luxury watch
market, and the combined company should pose a formidable challenge
to upscale watchmaker Rolex.
   The two companies will be held through Piaget Baume & Mercier
Holding, a parent company that will be 75 percent owned by Cartier
and 25 percent owned by Luxco, a Luxembourg-based holding company
that Cartier and its partners control.
   The holding company will hold 60 percent of both Piaget and
Baume & Mercier, and the Piaget family will retain the remaining
interest in each company.
   Both Piaget and Baume & Mercier, which are owned by the Piaget
family, will retain their management ``at least for the time
being,'' Perrin said.
   The move follows a wave of mergers and acquisitions in the
international luxury goods business, with further consolidation
likely in the watchmaking industry.
   Perrin disclosed Cartier hopes within the next year to gain a
controlling interest in Ebel S.A., another Swiss watchmaker.
   He also said discussions are underway with two other
privately-owned European luxury goods companies with a view to
expanding Cartier's market share in other product lines, but he
declined to give details.
   In addition to watches, Cartier is known for its jewelry,
cigarette lighters, luxury leather goods and perfumes.
   Cartier is 46.8 percent owned by Rothmans International PLC of
Britain. Sofina S.A., a unit of the Societe Generale de Belgique
group of Belgium, and the U.S. brokerage firm Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. hold up to 18 percent of Cartier. Perrin would not
identify other Cartier shareholders.
   Cartier's consolidated sales jumped by 36.8 percent last year to
$680 million from $497 million in 1986, while aggregate sales of
Piaget and Baume & Mercier were up 15 percent to $161.9 million.
   Cartier has never disclosed its earnings, but Perrin said the
company's sales could reach $840 million this year.
   Piaget, which initiated the takeover talks with Cartier, holds
the No. 1 position for luxury watch sales in the United States
despite a sales slump that hit the sector in 1986, Perrin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
