<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AutoTalks     04-26 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Talks,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW, Chrysler Talks Appear to be Back on Track</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contract talks between Chrysler Corp. and the
United Auto Workers appeared back on track Tuesday after a week of
rank-and-file pressure that led to a UAW boycott of the talks a day
earlier.
   Meanwhile, Chrysler opened separate talks Tuesday with local
union leaders from Kenosha, Wis., over the closing of a
5,500-worker assembly plant and a pact covering 1,000 workers at a
remaining engine plant.
   UAW Local 72 President Ed Steagall and Chairman Rudy Kuzel,
along with national UAW representatives, were meeting with a
Chrysler team led by union relations manager James Carmichael, said
Chrysler spokesman Lloyd Northard.
   The talks were moved from Wisconsin to Detroit to make it easier
for the UAW and Chrysler to handle the negotiations. Stepp also is
bargaining with General Dynamics' Land Systems Division and several
battery companies.
   Chrysler announced early this year that it will close by year's
end a former American Motors Corp. assembly plant in Kenosha but
leave open a neighboring engine plant. The announcement angered
workers and Wisconsin officials who had assumed Chrysler would be a
strong provider of jobs.
   At the national contract negotiations, Chrysler and the UAW
continued talking Tuesday in an atmosphere that improved after a
protest Monday by UAW bargainers, who boycotted the talks for
several hours.
   Union bargainers had debated whether to break off the early
negotiations because of what they considered disruptive
announcements the previous week, including Chrysler Chairman Lee
Iacocca's $18 million 1987 earnings.
   Rank-and-file members also were angered by Chrysler's decision
to halt U.S. production of its Dodge Aries and Plymouth Reliant
K-cars at the end of the year and fill 1989 orders by increasing
production at a Mexican plant.
   On Thursday and Friday, local union leaders received detailed
reports of Chrysler's initial contract proposals, which veered
sharply from a job-protecting industry-pattern pact established
last fall at Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp.
   The contract, which covers 66,000 active and laid-off workers in
15 states and 65,000 retirees, expires Sept. 14. The two sides
agreed to early talks to prevent further deterioration in their
damaged relationship.
   Workers already angered by the Kenosha decision threatened to
cripple Chrysler with plant-by-plant strikes and general
non-cooperation when it attempted to sell its 28,000-worker Acustar
Inc. parts subsidiary.
   Chrysler backed off from the sale and asked for early talks in
March.
</TEXT>
