<HEAD>Lucky Stores Considers Alternative Takeover Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucky Stores Inc., which three weeks ago
rejected a $1.74 billion takeover bid that would have created the
nation's largest supermarket chain, said Tuesday it has received
other takeover proposals.
   Lucky, California's second-biggest grocery chain, said it was
reviewing the new bids as well as other possibilities that would
benefit shareholders more than American Stores Co.'s pending tender
offer of $45 a share.
   A spokeswoman for Lucky declined to elaborate on the brief
formal statement.
   The company's soaring stock, which was trading at $32 a share a
month ago before American Stores announced its offer, closed up
another $1.37{ to $55.37{ Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   In a separate development, American Stores _ which has extended
the deadline on its offer to Saturday _ suggested to the Securities
and Exchange Commission that Lucky hold an auction among interested
parties.
   Industry analysts said they had only vague ideas as to the
identity of Lucky's new suitors but said the company would be an
attractive acquisition.
   ``It's (one of) the largest in California with a very strong
identity of being the low-price leader and it has a meaningful
position in Florida. And it's a well-run company,'' said Ron Rotter
of Morgan, Olmstead, Kennedy & Gardner in Los Angeles.
   Lucky, based in Dublin, about 25 miles east of San Francisco,
employs 39,000 people and has 480 outlets. With 340 stores in
California, it is smaller only than Safeway among supermarket
chains based in the state.
   In March, Salt Lake City-based American Stores offered $1.74
billion to acquire Lucky's 38.6 million outstanding shares. The bid
came just 17 months after Lucky derailed a hostile takeover attempt
by New York investor Asher Edelman.
   American Stores, a grocery and drugstore chain, has 1,700
outlets in 40 states. A merger with Lucky would create the nation's
largest supermarket chain, surpassing Kroger Co.
   But Lucky turned the offer down and also rejected American
Stores' proposal to raise the bid to $50 a share, or $1.93 billion,
in a negotiated acquisition. In a statement, Lucky's board of
directors said its financial adviser, Goldman Sachs & Co.,
considered both offers inadequate.
   The Lucky board also authorized the company's management to
consider other ways to ncrease shareholder value, including a
possible reorganization of the company to focus on California, a
leveraged recapitalization with a possible special payment to
shareholders, and a negotiated sale of the company.
   Lucky Chairman John Lillie had asked interested parties to
submit bids by Monday.
   ``Just knowing management, I think they would just like to
remain independent,'' Rotter said.
   ``They are under the gun to enhance shareholders' value, maybe
through a leveraged buyout or having someone acquire them that is
not a supermarket retail company and who would let the existing
management team run the company,'' he said.
</TEXT>
