<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Polaroid     04-26 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Polaroid,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poloroid Reports Drop In Quarterly Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. said Tuesday that its
first quarter profit slipped nearly 50 percent from a year ago
despite a moderate rise in worldwide sales.
   The company blamed part of the poor performance on higher tax
rates and a sharp increase in expenditures linked to the planned
introduction of a new instant camera line next month.
   For the first three months of the year, net income totaled $12.8
million, or 21 cents a share, on sales of $410.1 million. That
compared with earnings of $24.6 million, or 40 cents a share, and
sales of $381.1 million in 1987.
   Polaroid said profits from operations fell to $26.2 million for
the period from $30.1 million during the first quarter last year.
   Polaroid spokesman Samuel Yanes said expenditures associated
with the introduction of the Impulse instant camera hurt earnings.
   Yanes said some of the first quarter costs involved marketing
geared toward clearing inventory of existing cameras and promotion
of the two Impluse cameras, scheduled to be introduced in stores
nationwide on May 9. Yanes said other expenditures included
research and development.
   The cameras, unveiled to the media in New York earlier this
month, are listed to sell at $89 and $69.
   The company also noted foreign currency exchange losses and a 30
percent increase in worldwide tax payments compared with the first
quarter of 1987 contributed to the profit and earnings decline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
