<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1952EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Abortion-GE     04-26 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion-GE,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GE Shareholders To Vote On Abortion Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FAIRFIELD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A General Electric Co. stockholder is
asking the company's shareholders to vote on ``refraining from
support of any organizations that counsel or perform abortion.''
   The company, whose annual meeting is Wednesday in Milwaukee,
says in its proxy statement that it recommends a vote against the
proposal.
   George Jamison, a spokesman for GE, said the company ``doesn't
knowingly support any organization that is pro- or anti-abortion.''
   The proposal is being offered in the name of Anthony Leschin of
Marshalltown, Iowa, but he referred questions to his wife, Shirley,
who said she had ``nothing to say other than what is worded in the
resolution.''
   The proposal said the ``the cumulative demographic facts of
abortion on demand ... have now begun to impact on the American
society.''
   It said abortion's consequences include ``the closing of schools
due to an absence of children, the ongoing expansion of nursing
care facilities of the elderly, and the future lack of younger
workers to sustain the Social Security system and the defense of
our nation.''
   In the proxy statement, GE said its ``board opposes this
proposal because the company does not adopt positions unrelated to
business interests ... the company has adopted no position on the
abortion issue.''
   When asked if the company offers charitable contributions to
groups on either side of the abortion issue, Jamison said, ``Not
that we know of.''
   Ned Raynolds, a senior vice president of the public relations
firm Hill and Knowlton Inc. in New York, said the anti-abortion
proposal reflects ``the basic phenomenon where people like to use
the proxy machinery to express an opinion on something.''
   ``This woman has an anti-abortion point of view, apparently,''
he said.
   Raynolds, who said he has supervised studies of company annual
reports, said ``there are all kinds of things'' showing up on proxy
statements ranging from experimental tests with animals to
protesting South Africa holdings.
   Shareholders of International Business Machines Corp., for
instance, defeated a resolution on Monday that would have
prohibited company benefit payments for abortions and related
services and required management to disclose to shareholders any
information about research and testing on animals.
   ``Nothing really surprises me in a proxy statement anymore,''
Raynolds said. ``This is a trend documented in lots of places where
institutions used to sell stock if they didn't like management, but
now they want to own stock and stay in, but get their point of
across.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
