<FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 1858EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-FirstRepublicBank     04-26 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-First RepublicBank,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First RepublicBank Reports $1.5 Billion Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ailing First RepublicBank Corp., confirming an
earlier announcement, reported Tuesday a $1.5 billion loss for the
first quarter of 1988 and attributed much of it to heavy real
estate loan losses.
   The amount is the sixth-largest quarterly loss by a U.S.
corporation and is triple the amount of corporate projections.
   A preliminary announcement of the earnings loss on April 12
followed a $1 billion emergency loan extended by the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp. to the Dallas-based holding company on
March 19.
   In 1987, bank officials reported a loss of $656 million.
   Company officials said the first quarter loss primarily is the
result of a $1.4 billion loan loss in its real estate loan
portfolio and $126 million of losses and write-downs of assets.
   Earlier this month, Comptroller of the Currency Robert L. Clarke
urged First RepublicBank to begin restructuring and change its
leadership.
   Gerald W. Fronterhouse, former chairman and chief executive
officer, resigned April 12, when the huge loss was first indicated.
He was the second top executive to leave the firm during the
management shake-up arranged by federal regulators. Other top
officials followed Fronterhouse's departure.
   Fronterhouse was replaced by Albert V. Casey, 68, former
chairman of the board of AMR Corp., parent company of American
Airlines.
   ``The actions taken in the first quarter are consistent with our
intention that the company move ahead with its plan to restructure
and to recapitalize operations,'' Casey said in a statement Monday.
   First RepublicBank, the nation's 13th largest bank holding
company, included $235 million in its loan-loss provision for Third
World countries, increasing the provision to $612 million or 50
percent of the bank's $1.2 billion of outstanding debt to these
countries.
   The total loan loss provision exceeded what the company already
had written off in loan losses by $1.1 billion.
   The bank reported total non-performing assets increased from
$543 million in the fourth quarter of 1987 to $4.5 billion in the
first quarter of 1988 ending March 31.
   Eighty-five percent of the non-performing assets increase was
attributed to real estate-related assets, the bank said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
